	(332,95,'dan hartung','lakefxdan@aol.com','http://stilicho.blogspot.com/','68.78.237.157','2005-03-17 18:21:02','2005-03-17 23:21:02','As anthonyk notes, there is a whole raft of places to file free. The IRS did have a debate about doing a public site of their own, but it wasn\'t just TurboTax who objected, probably. The compromise is that almost all major tax preparation vendors have a free-filing option, but each one develops its own qualifications for that program. The IRS site lets you find one that you fit.\r\n\r\nIf anything, Intuit deserves some credit for keeping the program going in the face of the new IRS flagging requirement:\r\nhttp://www.usatoday.com/money/perfi/taxes/2004-01-09-efile_x.htm\r\n\r\nOther vendors dropped out this year rather than open up their customers to extra scrutiny. \r\n\r\nThe problem the IRS has is not an easy one, as electronic filing is the method of choice for tax scammers, e.g. people who file for thousands of dollars in Earned Income Tax Credits to which they are not entitled -- for instance, by claiming a relative as a dependent. Scammers can file, get a loan on the refund/credit, and disappear before an human eyes at the IRS catch the fraud.\r\n\r\nThat said there\'s a lot of problems with the free filing program from the consumer perspective:\r\nhttp://www.consumerfed.org/011603_IRSfree.html',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.7.6) Gecko/20050225 Firefox/1.0.1 Mnenhy/0.7','',0),
