	(1104,248,'Tim','timothycrowe@gmail.com','http://veryraw.com/','68.81.88.235','2005-07-27 17:18:45','2005-07-27 22:18:45','Brain and Rascal, I am totally into getting everything off of my own computer.  At some point I may want a backup of all those images I have sent to flickr but for now I want them archived and backedup and more immediately I want them described.  I thought that picassa would satisfy my needs but it didn\'t.  I was sort of a waste of time.  I ended up spending a bunch of time on sorting and it still wasn\'t easy to find images.  For looking at digital images I have to say flickr is far superior to picassa.  It just flows.  I should say it just flows for me.  It works like I work. \r\n\r\nAs for having bigger problems than photos if your house burns down, you may have more problems in the immediate but in the long run there is nearly nothing that you would lose (save the life of a loved one) that could not be replaced other than photos.  When photos are gone they are gone.  Couches or books or computers can be replaced.  Photos and the lost memories they may help you uncover are irreplacable.',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.7.10) Gecko/20050716 Firefox/1.0.6','',0),
	(1110,248,'Mac','brian.mcelaney@gmail.com','http://www.mcelaney.com','199.112.55.146','2005-07-29 03:34:31','2005-07-29 08:34:31','Yahoo is taking a bet with Flickr... either users won\'t sign up for the premium service (revenue from ads is higher than cost of serving limited space) or that premium members won\'t â€œover-useâ€ the service ($25 a year revenue higher than cost of hosting).  I personally have 60 gigs of hi-res original images from the last five months alone.   When someone like me (or probably you) signs up for their premium service... they lose money on our account.  \r\n\r\nIt simply isn\'t a profitable idea to offer unlimited storage for free (which $25 might as well be) in the long term.  And profit is what drives Yahoo.  Period.\r\n\r\nWhy does this matter?\r\n\r\nBecause my tape drive doesn\'t make it\'s first general condition of use \"We reserve the right to modify or TERMINATE the Flickr.com service for ANY reason, WITHOUT NOTICE at ANY TIME.\"  (Emph added.)  \r\n\r\nMy tape drive is also not a Beta system which Yahoo is still on the fence about keeping up once the trial is over.\r\n\r\nYou always risk losing data... but trusting your memories to a stockholder held corporation makes less sense than worrying about a house fire and meteor hitting your bank at the same time.  If I were you, I\'d run a quit smoking campaign in your apartment building, invest in a fire proof safe and look into designing a desktop app that works as well or better than flickr and retire on selling it to Microsoft as part of Windows 2010.',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.0; .NET CLR 1.1.4322)','',0),
	(1113,248,'Tim','timothycrowe@gmail.com','http://veryraw.com/','68.81.88.235','2005-07-29 07:36:28','2005-07-29 12:36:28','Every service you sign up for has that condition in the TOS.  It gives them power if they need it.  Storage costs nothing.  The cost of storage is so low that its nearly nothing. As of yesterday there are <a href=\"http://blog.flickr.com/flickrblog/2005/07/1000000_members.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">1,000,000 users</a> The number of those users who have paid? I don\'t know.  But I am sure that the greatest number of those is not like you or I.\r\n\r\nI think for Yahoo, they already have farms with Gig upon gig of bandwidth. Who cares if you add another 10 gig.  Whats the price increase.  Most likely minimal.  \r\n\r\nI certainly don\'t expect flickr to be around forever (sob), the next installment addresses this concept and tell what I want to do.  Wait for it.  You\'ll see why I am dumping all this information into flickr.',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.7.10) Gecko/20050716 Firefox/1.0.6','',0),
	(1117,248,'Matthom','matt@matthom.com','http://www.matthom.com/','216.43.207.214','2005-08-01 16:29:28','2005-08-01 21:29:28','I\'d almost rather have my own application, that I develop as my main \"image management system.\"\r\n\r\nFor example, I\'d like to use Flickr for corporate/business use, but they don\'t allow it - and rightfully so. The point is, those restrictions are not necessary, when I could, very well, come up with a feasible solution, using SQL, PHP, or something like that.\r\n\r\nWhat really \"spins my head\" is the fact that there are too many image management utilities, and I\'d like to have ONE utility - that can store unlimited images, for business or personal use - and that runs on the web, or the desktop.\r\n\r\nRight now there are web tools (Flickr), desktop tools (Picasa, iPhoto) - and dozens more variations of each.\r\n\r\nIt\'s too much for me.\r\n\r\nAnd if there\'s too many options, that means I should just create something of my own, and use that. That way, I\'m not limited to \"business vs. personal,\" or having my account be disabled, etc. In other words, I\'d be in complete control.',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.0; en-US; rv:1.7.7) Gecko/20050414 Firefox/1.0.3','',0),
