	(1270,61,'Charlie','chendrixstats@juno.com','','4.248.40.43','2005-10-03 16:34:53','2005-10-03 21:34:53','We\'ve had camelback crickets for about 15 years. It\'s a good bet they are breeding in a woodpile that\'s too near our house.\r\nBut I don\'t have another place to put the woodpile.  Some of these buggers get in the house. In particular they come inside in the fall.  I\'ve applied Sevin dust around the woodpile (it\'s in a shelter and does not get wet). Also, I go out at night and kill individual crickets with Raid or something similar. This keeps the population down. \r\n\r\nOn another site I just noticed two more ideas. (1) Use glue boards inside the house in dark cave-like places. Glue boards are just cardboard with a very sticky glue. This should get rid of individual crickets that stray into the house. (2) Sprinkle Borax dust near where they are breeding. Good idea!!! This is a little known idea. Borax dust kills cockroaches and a lot of other pests. As some have said, \"it cuts the bugs like glass cuts humans\". It really does. They lose fluids through the cuts and dehydrate and die. I\'m going to apply Borax powder right after I finish this note. I\'ve used it for other pests, and feel sort of stupid because I didn\'t think of it sooner.\r\n\r\nA by-the-way... you can make ant poison (sweet eating ants only) by blending Borax powder into Karo syrup. Add Borax and stir and do this until the mixture is saturated. Borax is CHEAP... a lot cheaper than the usual pesticides.',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; .NET CLR 1.1.4322)','',0),
