	(1357,61,'Charlie','chendrixstats@juno.com','','63.23.78.84','2005-10-23 16:01:25','2005-10-23 21:01:25','On October 3 I posted a message concerning our camelback cricket problem.  All experts say the trick is to kill them outside the house. Apparently the ones that come inside just wander in through cracks. Kill them outside the the problem is gone.\r\n\r\nSo we sprinkled Borax (Boric Acid) powder around our woodpile.\r\nThat\'s where they seem to be hatching. It\'s under a shelter, dry, and near the house. Borax (sold as a roach killer) will kill most crawling insects.  I bought a large container of Borax (advertised as a roach killer) at a dollar store for $2.00 and sprinkled it generously around the woodpile in a band about 12 inches wide.  Then I sprinkled some flakes of dry oatmeal on top of the Borax to give the buggers something to eat and a reason to walk in the Borax. Contact with the Borax kills them... they do not have to eat it. There are now dead camelback crickets around the woodpile. I check every night after dark and the live cricket count is zero.  Before doing this treatment those critters were having a party out there every night.  We\'ve had no camelbacks in our home for about three weeks. None!!\r\n\r\nAfter 15 years of putting up with these things we seem to have a solution. And it\'s a cheap solution, too.\r\n\r\nOf course if you put the Borax in places were it will be wet from rain, this may not work at all.\r\n\r\nAnother thing we did was to sprinkle Borax on the threshold of basement doors that we seldom open. We have been convinced this is the place they have been coming inside.  There are now dead sowbugs and other dead creepy-crawly things on the thresholds along with the corpses of a few camelback crickets.\r\n\r\nThis turned out to be easier than we thought. We\'ve used Borax (Boric Acid) to kill roaches but until recently never thought about using it to kill camelback crickets.\r\n ',0,'1',0,'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; .NET CLR 1.1.4322)','',0),
