	(20,1,'2004-11-09 21:44:04','2004-11-10 02:44:04','<h4>The media what a piece of crap...</h4>\r\n<p>I used to read <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com\">cnn.com</a> every single day. I mean religiously.  Then one day I realized that there was an entire world that I wasn\'t getting.  It seemed that there were stories that were never getting to CNN. I doubt that the problem is poor correspondents.  I think that they filter their news.  It\'s rather obvious when the most important things on the site deal with mainly Iraq and George Bush.  Now I\'m not saying that these topics aren\'t important.  I just think that there is alot more to life on this planet than Geo and Iraq.</p>\r\n<p>A few days ago I wrote about the <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/bush-wins-we-all-lose/\">travesty of an election</a> that we had.  In that entry I mentioned Fox News.  I believe Fox News is close to the worst thing that has happened to the world.  Ever.  They select stories which are violent and depressing.  They take angles on stories with the main focus being whatever will get the masses to throw up there arms in discust at the condition of the world.  This counter-productive way of reporting the news misleads and causes things to happen like this most recent election.  I trully don\'t believe most of the country even realized that they knew that there were other important things happening in the world outside of terrorism. Organizations like Fox News are to blame for the destruction of intelligence and inquisitiveness in America.</p>\r\n<p>A few years ago there was an article in the <a href=\"http://www.delcotimes.com/\">Delaware County Daily Times</a>.  This paper is easily the most biased publication I have ever gotten my hands on.  I have read the <a href=\"http://www.cst-phl.com/\">Catholic Standard and Times</a> and felt like I was reading less propagandistic materials.  I digress.  The paper had an article about a man who was bitten by a badger.  The way they delivered the facts you would think the man was attacked by an elephant with a shark tied to its head.  This was, from what I saw, an attempt to get the people of Delaware County angry.  I could hear old and fictional  Mr. Jones on Poplar Street saying, \"We got to do sompthin about them dang badgers!\"</p>\r\n<p>Everyday this newspaper has articles in it about violent, depressing things.  When they actually do run an article about something good it\'s in the context of \'dag, in a world full of such hate and greed, there still are a few decent people left.\'  There are alot of decent people left.  But decent people don\'t sell newspapers, scumbags do.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Enter the alternatives...</h4>\r\n<p>After realizing that all of the news sources that I had been reading for almost two years at that point I dumped them. Dumped them like the hateful, misery seeking vultures they are.  But what was I to do.  An information addict like myself needs his fix.</p>\r\n<p>I have read recently that more young americans are turning to shows like <a href=\"http://www.comedycentral.com/tv_shows/thedailyshowwithjonstewart/\">The Daily Show</a> and <a href=\"http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/best_week_ever/series.jhtml\">The Best Week Ever</a> for their news.  I think this is a great turn.  You get all the same facts that you would anywhere else but you get multiple sides.  You also get a dose of humor which most people watching Fox News could use anyway.</p>\r\n<p>I think you should go further though.  If you are unsatisfied with the information you are getting then search deeper, search harder.  Find what you are aching for. When those get old dump them too.</p>\r\n<p>I have found that the best sources for information are the free ones.   People and organizations which don\'t profit from the information that they provide are the best source out there.  They give you everything and they give you truth.  Free thinkers provide free thinkers with free information that\'s real.</p>\r\n<p>For the weak and weary, for those tired of the crap that the Media Dishes us.  For those who hate the drivel of Fox News and the Delaware County Daily Times and all the money mongering whores like them around the country, I recommend you take a look at my \"Frequently Visited\" links on the side of the page.  This is where I find my best information.  Search out sites that provide you with what you want.  Oh and tell me about them because I am still searching.</p>','Alternate Information Sources',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','alternate-information-sources','','','2004-11-09 21:48:20','2004-11-10 02:48:20','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/alternate-information-sources/',0,'','',8),
	(21,1,'2004-11-11 15:37:30','2004-11-11 20:37:30','<p>I got this email today...</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\nDear Valued Go Daddy Customer,<br />\r\n\r\nEffective November 12, 2004, ICANN, the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers, will put in place its new transfer policy for all accredited domain name service providers.<br />\r\n\r\nThe previous ICANN policy allowed us to deny requests to transfer your domain names to another registrar unless you explicitly confirmed to us your intent to transfer. The new ICANN policy removes that protection. When we receive a request to transfer your domain name to a new registrar, we will still attempt to contact you to confirm that you authorized the request. However, if you do not respond, or are not able to respond within 5 days, your domain name WILL be transferred.<br />\r\n\r\nRest assured, your domains have NOT been transferred, and IT IS UNLIKELY that this will happen.\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Although <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net\">Mark</a> has stated how stupid this policy is, I disagree.  I have many times, particularly when I was looking for a new <acronym title=\"Universal Resource Locator\">URL</acronym> for my blog, ran into a case where the site wasn\'t doing anything but it was still registered. I wish I had saved the names of those sites for this exact circumstance.  My thought is that this policy has been changed at ICANN to help recover some of these <acronym title=\"Universal Resource Locator\">URL</acronym>\'s if they are wanted by someone else.  I think I am going to start trying to steal people\'s domains. You know... just for fun.\r\n</p>','Take my domain... PLEASE!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','','','take-my-domain','','','2004-11-11 15:37:30','2004-11-11 20:37:30','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/take-my-domain/',0,'','',0),
	(22,1,'2004-11-12 00:06:28','2004-11-12 05:06:28','<p>I need some help.  I created this thing last night and today I got alot of great feedback from specific people I have sent it to.  I need everyone\'s help now.  This could potentially save a lot of people the trouble of fixing other people\'s computers because it would give them a place to send them to find some information to help.  It\'s a windows security checklist.  It covers anti-virus software, pop-up blockers,  anti-spyware and some other stuff.  Leave me comments. Thanks.<p>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<p>You can find a full, properly styled version of this page on my <a href=\"http://faculty.dccc.edu/~timothy/windowssecurity/\">dccc homepage</a></p>\r\n\r\n<h1>A few simple steps to a happier, healthier computer!</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2>What are we going to do?</h2>\r\n<p>Maintaining your computer is easy.  There are a few simple things which you can do to keep everything in proper working order. This list does not require any special computer wizardry.  I\'ve received a hundred kajillion request for assistance from people who are frustrated with what their computers are doing.  Follow these simple steps and you will find yourself a happy existance which is spyware free, spam free, and ad free. Be patient and don\'t get discouraged. Good luck.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>What do I do?</h2>\r\n<h3>Run Windows Update</h3>\r\n<p>You will need to use Internet Explorer for this.  Open Internet Explorer, go to <a href=\"http://www.windowsupdate.com\">www.windowsupdate.com</a> They will most likely ask you a bunch of questions, for example, \'Do you trust Microsoft?\' or \'Do you want to give Microsoft permission to?\'  I am paraphrasing but you will get the option to click <i>Yes</i> or <i>No</i>; choose <i>Yes</i>.  If the options are <i>continue</i> or <i>cancel</i>, choose <i>continue</i>.</p>\r\n<p>Once the page opens you will have two main options, <i>Express Install</i> or <i>Custom Install</i>.  Choose <i>Express Install</i>.  At this point you will see a green bar moving across the screen.  This is Windows Update examining the configuration of your computer.  This is probably the only time you ever want a website examining your computer\'s configuration.</p>\r\n<p>When the results of this search appear you should choose the <i>Install</i> button on the right hand side of the page. You can rest assured that this method is installing all of the most important and sritical updates that Microsoft has released for your version of Windows</p>\r\n<p>Do whatever Windows Update instructs you to do.  Be patient.  Read the instructions and messages it gives you.  This is not difficult. You may have to run this three or four times after restarts to get all of the updates if you have never updated before.</p>\r\n<p>I suggest this be done at least once a week or setting Windows update to <i>Automatically download and install updates</i>.  Setting this is easy and can be done from the <a href=\"www.windowsupdate.com\">Windows Update</a> page.  This will help you from suffering from horrible flesh eating virii.</p>\r\n	\r\n<h3>Get some anti-Spyware software.</h3>\r\n<p>Spyware is software that is installed on your computer without your knowledge.  Spyware is angry software that can perform any wide variety of tasks.  Spyware can collect what you type.  Spyware can collect passwords.  Spyware can collect your credit card information, your social security number or worse the addresses of naughty sites you might visit.  I\'m not telling you this so you leave the internet and never come back.  It\'s important to know about this so you can protect yourself.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.safer-networking.org/en/index.html\">Spybot</a> is an excellent <strong>free</strong> anti-Spyware program.  Download this program and run the installation.  Very straight forward and easy to use.  When you run Spybot, you will need to use the <i>search and destroy</i> feature. It will help you eliminate both spyware and, our next enemy,	adware.</p>\r\n\r\n	\r\n<h3>Adware.  The most annoying part of the internet.</h3>\r\n<p>Spam is irritating.  The only thing more annoying than spam though is pop-up advertisements.  There are several solutions to this plague upon your house.  Half of your pop-ups are probably caused by programs called adware which have been installed on your computer in a method similar to  the way Spyware is installed.  The differences are important though.  Adware\'s only objective is to annoy you with its advertisements.  <a href=\"http://www.lavasoftusa.com/\">Download Ad-Aware</a>.  This is a program which finds the adware programs in your computer and removes them.  It also serves as anti-spyware. This program is very easy to use and self explainatory.</p>\r\n<p>The other half of your pop-up problem is surely provided by the pages you visit.  If you insist on using Internet Explorer, install the <a href=\"http://toolbar.google.com/\">Google Toolbar</a>. It has a built in pop-up blocker and really helps fight this problem. Although if you take my next piece of advice you won\'t need a search toolbar or a pop-up blocker because thats all integrated into <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/products/firefox/\">Firefox</a>.</p>\r\n	\r\n<h3>The browser is the proof in the pudding.</h3>\r\n<p>A significant portion of the problems that I have heard about on computer has to do with the browser that you are using.  If you are using Internet Explorer you are opening yourself to vulnerabilities.  <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/products/firefox/\">Download Firefox</a>.  Use Firefox. Never deal with these issues again.</p>\r\n<p>I switched to Firefox about eight months ago and haven\'t looked back since.  I have not had the same problems I had prior to using Firefox and the only explaination is that Firefox is omnipotent. I could tell you about all the wonderful features of Firefox and all the reasons why you should switch but <a href=\"http://browsehappy.com/\">it\'s already been written</a>. You should read up and then switch.  It will save you alot of grief.</p>\r\n<p>If you are using Outlook or Outlook Express for your email you should switch to <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/products/thunderbird/\">Thunderbird</a>.  It\'s Firefox\'s sister email program.  Again you wont regret it. <a href=\"http://www.mozilla.org/products/thunderbird/why/\">Read why you should switch to Thunderbird</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>The last bits... virus protection</h3>\r\n<p>I start by saying, \"I have never had anti-virus software and I have never had a virus.\"  <del>Screen goes blank and Tim screams... KHAAAAAAAN!!!</del> You may want to look into a virus scanning software.  My father uses <a href=\"http://www.symantec.com/index.htm\">Norton Anti-Virus</a>.  The College uses <a href=\"http://www.mcafee.com/us/default.asp\">McAfee VirusScan</a>.  My father has never steered me wrong but he	doesn\'t have the technical saavy of an entire IT team.  You be the judge.  Like I said I have never used one but I think they are important.</p>\r\n<p>If you are lookinf for something of the <strong>free</strong> nature you can download the <a href=\"http://free.grisoft.com/freeweb.php/doc/1/\">AVG Anti-Virus program</a>. Not only do they provide free virus protection software but they also ofer free updates.</p> \r\n	\r\n<h2>So what\'s the bottom line?</h2>\r\n<p>So the bottom line is that if you do all of the things I have written about you may still get a bowel wrenching computer virus.  You may still have to deal with pop-ups and you may still risk getting hacked.  The chance is always there but these will significantly decrease those chances.</p>\r\n<p>When you are surfing the internet <strong>use common sense</strong>.  If something seems to be shady, it probably is.  Don\'t download files from websites you aren\'t familiar with.  Don\'t accept email from strange email addresses (my email address used to be mulefritters@yahoo.com, that\'s	sort of strange).  Don\'t download attachments from people you don\'t know.  Read the error messages that appear.  Don\'t just click <i>okay</i> or <i>cancel</i> assuming that you are answering the right question.  It\'s better to read a pop-up and answer a question correctly than to assume and end up with a piece of software on your computer that you don\'t want.  You may not know exactly what they mean but usually if you give it that good old college try and use your intuition you will be able to tell whether it\'s good or bad.  Good Luck and happy browsing.</p>\r\n<p>This checklist is inspired by Jason Kottke.  His recycled <a href=\"http://www.kottke.org/04/09/windows-security-checklist\">Windows Security Checklist</a> assisted in creating this expanded and more extensive Checklist. Michael Zaleski and Donald Sloat were also a big help with his free versions of some of this software. Notable help was also provided by Ed Eckel, Mark Platt and Lori Wushensky.</p>	\r\n','HELP! - Windows Security Checklist',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','windows-security-checklist-helpme','','','2004-11-12 00:19:04','2004-11-12 05:19:04','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/windows-security-checklist-helpme/',0,'','',3),
	(107,1,'2005-03-23 00:07:54','2005-03-23 05:07:54','<p>I looked at this image as \"Miranda That Ghost Just Isn\'t Holy Anymore\" from <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B0007GAEW6/qid=1111554316/sr=2-1/ref=pd_bbs_b_2_1/002-8070210-8055264\">the new The Mars Volta album</a> hit its big trumpet blasts (if you ain\'t heard it you better go hear it) and a chill crescendo went down my spine for about a minute.  I seriously thought I was going to pass out.  The original is from <a href=\"http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap050322.html\">APOD</a>.  Makes me feel very small in a very big way.</p>\r\n<img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/astronautaboveearth.jpg\" />','Very small in a very big way!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','verysmall-verybig','','','2005-03-23 00:07:59','2005-03-23 05:07:59','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/107/',0,'','',2),
	(24,1,'2004-11-15 20:02:57','2004-11-16 01:02:57','<p>Thursday night I installed a <acronym title=\"Virtual Private Network\">VPN</acronym> client on my computer at home to connect to the web servers  at work.  After installation I was asked to restart and I complied.</p>\r\n<p>When the box came back up iTunes opened and my stomach dropped as I read, \"iTunes can not read iPod \"Mr. Bojangles\". Use iPod restore utility to restore your iPod back to original factory settings.</p>\r\n<h4>Houston, we have a problem!</h4>\r\n<p>A big freaking problem.  I restored it to original factory settings with the iPod software and afterwards it was stuck in file storage mode.  A trip to the Apple store and it worked on the Mac we attached it to.  Bring it home and nothing again. Symantec, what the fuck have you done to my iPod.  I have just uninstalled practically everything from my computer that I don\'t use.  This includes iTunes the iPod updating software and that heaping pile of shit Symantic calls a <acronym title=\"Virtual Private Network\">VPN</acronym> client.  I have restarted and I will now reinstall iTunes and the the iPod software.  Then I will try re-attaching the iPod to my computer. </p>\r\n<p>If this doesn\'t work you may hear about it on the news. update in few minutes...</p>\r\n<p><strong>Update:</strong> In the words of Ben Franklin, \"iPod is proof that there is a god and he wants us to be happy.\"  It worked.  I am currently loading my music back onto my iPod.  A process that took me over a week the first time.  I\'m glad it worked.  I didn\'t feel like killing tonight.</p>','iBrick',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','ibrick','','','2004-11-15 20:23:57','2004-11-16 01:23:57','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/ibrick/',0,'','',5),
