	(140,1,'2005-05-02 12:10:06','2005-05-02 17:10:06','<p>Recently at dccc.edu we suddenly started having a problem where the curling quotes, apostrophes, em dashes were appearing as question marks.  I couldn\'t figure out for the life of me what it was.  It\'s not the first time I had run into this problem and I knew the root of it was in the fact that that some of the content is copied from Microsoft Word and pasted directly into ZOPE (our CMS) and saved to the site.  The fact that this suddenly started happening had me even more confused. </p>\r\n<p>Last night I was reading <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0321303474/mezzoblue-20/102-1829308-9192157\">The Zen of CSS Design</a> and came onto the bit about character sets and it clicked.  A few weeks ago I was checking how the site did in a validation.  This is very close to impossible based on the size of the site and the number of people who are maintaining content.  I do the best I can and check every now and then.  Well at some point I lost the charset information in the meta data of the site.  I wen to veryraw and copied the charset information and pasted it into the header of dccc.edu.  Here is where the problem began.</p>\r\n<p>This site uses <code>text/html; charset=utf-8</code>,  dccc.edu uses <code>text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1</code>.  The differences are not all that extreme.  Though utf-8 does not accomodate curly quotes, em dashes or curly apostrophes.  Ideally we should be using HTML entities for these anyway.  Changed the charset and the problem is solved.</p>\r\n<p>Moral of the story is \'If you have alot of people copying from Microsoft word onto the web, use charset ISO-8859-1\'.  Thats one to teach the kids at bedtime. \r\n\r\n<h3>further resources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.dwheeler.com/essays/quotes-in-html.html\">Curling Quotes in HTML, SGML, and XML</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.rossde.com/malaprops/writing_internet.html\">Writing for the internet</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.douggreenconsulting.com/articles/htmlamp.php\">HTML Character References, HTML Entity Names, HTML Ampersand Escape Codes</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://webstandards.org/learn/askw3c/dec2002.html\">Specifying Character Encoding</a></li></ul></p>','Choose your charset wisely.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','140','','','2005-05-02 12:10:39','2005-05-02 17:10:39','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/140/',0,'','',0),
	(33,1,'2004-11-22 13:11:28','2004-11-22 18:11:28','<p>In my never ceasing narcissism I have done what every self obsessed freak does at least once a month.  I have <a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=%22timothy+crowe%22\">googled my name</a>.  I have used quotes to ensure only matches for my entire name, <code>timothy crowe</code>.  Here are my results.</p>\r\n<p>In the first page of results, there were two hits to pages that were actually me.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://veryraw.com\">veryraw.com</a> - My very own blog</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.gawds.org/showmember.php?memberid=245\">gawds.org</a> - My profile at the Guild of Accessible Web Designers.  I am member 245</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Then there were countless questionable results. </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://movies2.nytimes.com/gst/movies/filmography.html?p_id=272107&mod=films\">A film director</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.gettextbooks.com/isbn/075067198X/\">An author</a> - There were alot of results for this fellow who has written many books in criminology</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.trinityrep.com/index.cfm?Action=About.Display&PageName=TCrowe\">An actor for the Trinity Reportory Comany</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.dailycal.org/article.php?id=8831\">A victorian in drag</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.locateadoc.com/directory.cfm/34/IL/Chicago/2\">A dentist</a> - I practice Implant Dentistry in Chicago.</li>\r\n<li><a href=http://mentalhelp.net/books/books.php?type=de&id=499\">An Evironmental Zoologist</a> - I have strong opinions about evolution and I studied guineafowl</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~langdongoff/crowe-geneweb.html\">A dublin man</a> - born in 1803</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://staff.business.auckland.ac.nz/t.crowe\">Programme Co-ordinator</a> - of the The University of Auckland Business School.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.mopie.com/sims/simdex.html\">A sim</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.psal.org/psalsports/player/psal_playerprofile.asp?cid=248811721&csport=028\">A high school basketball player</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The strangest result I got though was an article called<a href=\"http://www.providencephoenix.com/theater/other_stories/documents/03162957.asp\">Living Proof: Trinity journeys to the center of the mind</a>.  It\'s about The guy about who does theater for the Trinity Reportory Comany.  In the notes about this play it says it was directed by Brian McEleney.  I did theater in high school with <a href=\"http://macweblog.blogspot.com/\">Brian McElaney</a> not <a href=\"http://www.trinityrep.com/index.cfm?Action=About.Display&PageName=BMceleney\">Brian McElaney</a>, but still wierd</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.googlism.com/\">Googlism</a> has also compiled <a href=\"http://www.googlism.com/index.htm?ism=Timothy+Crowe&type=1\">a similar list about me</a>.  Googlism is awesome it searches you in <a href=\"http://www.google.com\">google</a> then compiles the results and tells you what <a href=\"http://www.google.com\">google</a> thinks about you.</p>','Narcissism 101',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','narcissism-101','','','2004-11-22 13:11:45','2004-11-22 18:11:45','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/narcissism-101/',0,'','',6),
	(98,1,'2004-05-17 13:07:59','2004-05-17 18:07:59','The conversation starts like this.  \"I want a pair of boxers that say \'chmod 777\' across the crotch.\"\r\n\r\nTo enjoy this concept I must first make sure you all understand the concept.  I\'ll give a quick rundown for the layman.  Any <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chmod\">further explaination</a> is on you.\r\n\r\nLinux is an operating system based on unix.  chmod is a shell command for the unix-like environment. It is the abbreviation of \"<strong>ch</strong>ange <strong>mod</strong>e.\"  It\'s used to give different users access to different things in the network environment.  This command becomes very useful in web design when you start doing file manipulation and if you don\'t understand it you may lose your mind.\r\n\r\nThere are three user groups, owner, group and world.  These are relatively self explainatory and I am sure you can figure out which each one means.  Then there are three settings which must be taken into consideration when creating security policies.  Read, which give the right to read.  Write, which give the ability to alter the file.  Then there is execute, which as the name implies gives the right to execute the file to a particular user type.\r\n\r\nThe chart ends up like this.\r\n<table cellpadding=\"4\" border=\"1\" title=\"chmod chart\">\r\n<tr>\r\n<th></th>\r\n<th>owner</th>\r\n<th>group</th>\r\n<th>world</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th>read</th>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">4</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">4</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">4</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th>write</th>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">2</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">2</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">2</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th>execute</th>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">1</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">1</div>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<div align=\"center\">1</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\nYou then use binary to figure out the settings. The chart makes it easy. <a href=\"http://www.intuitor.com/counting/\">I use my fingers</a> though. You can check the spots you want rights for and then add the numbers in those columns and voila.  You have your security settings.\r\nYou would run the command by typing in the chmod then the 3 digit security setting. Full rights you would type, \"chmod 777.\" No rights you would type, \"chmod 000\"\r\n\r\nBack to the original, \"I want a pair of boxers that say \'chmod 777\' across the crotch.\" This would give everyone full access to your boxer shorts.\r\n\r\nI saw something intrinsically wrong with this.  When you use chmod on a folder.  Which in my opinion the underwear serves as, you arealso giving the same settings to everything in the underwear.  Therefore if you \"chmod 777\" your underpants, you are not only giving full rights to the pants, but also the cock, the balls and the anus.  This could possibly offer a serious situation.  I mean who knows what who is going to do to the contents of your underwear once they have full rights.\r\n\r\nThis idea obviously has some ver significant security holes in it.  Not a very werll thought out plan.  And we wonder why there are so many security flaws in systems today.\r\n\r\nMy own personal underpants security settings would be \"chmod 444.\"  This would give all the rights to take a peak but none the ability to delete.  Then I would set the contents seperatly.\r\n\r\nMy penis gets a \"chmod 550.\" You would think that I need full rights.  I don\'t.  There are very few time when write permissions are needed.  You don\'t want to end up chopping it off or tattoing it sometime when you are wrecked and stranded in Vegas with four french hookers and a chinamen.  No.  Write privileges can be turned on when they are absolutely needed.  But I have turned them off to avoid serious accidents.  As for giving the group settings a five.  This is a relatively elite group of people.  Girlfriends and doctors really.  They may have equal rights to me.  Everyone else gets nothing.  There will have nothing of strangers executing my penis.\r\n\r\nLast but possibly the most important security setting.  The anus.  I give my anus a \"chmod 100.\" This way I may execute it which is obviously a must, But no one will have the freedom to just read and certainly not write to it any time they please.','Chmod and your underpants',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','chmod-and-your-underpants','','','2006-02-15 09:46:41','2006-02-15 14:46:41','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/chmod-and-your-underpants/',0,'','',0),
	(47,1,'2004-12-10 23:46:19','2004-12-11 04:46:19','<p><a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> informed me this morning that its been a while since I\'ve posted.  He\'s right.  It has.  Partially his fault though.  I have been hella busy.  I\'ve been working on a redesign of Mark\'s company\'s website.  In addition, like many others who read this, its finals week next week which means my brain is burning with final projects, late papers and exams.</p>\r\n<p>I took fifteen credits this semester thinking I would have time at work to do homework.  Then I was promoted.  The new position rules (more on this later) but I have <strong>no time</strong> for homework.  So I am playing catchup. </p>\r\n<p>Next weekend it will all be over and I can go back to a regular pace of posting.  For now though you will have to bare with me.  I have about five half written entries and another ten which are researched but not written.  I just don\'t have time. In addition, I have all of the old timmyfury.com content which will be going up here and all the animations.  There are photos to scan, sites to develop, stories to tell.  Be patient. Thanks for being understanding.</p>\r\n<p>Now go enjoy <a href=\"http://www.jengajam.com/r/Disco-Hitler\">Hitler the disco-f&#252;hrer</a>.  This one should hold you over until Wednesday.  I have a meeting with an Army Intelligence Agent. I\'ll tell you about it Wednesday.</p>','It\'s been a while!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','been-a-while','','','2004-12-10 23:58:34','2004-12-11 04:58:34','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/12/been-a-while/',0,'','',1),
