	(40,1,'2005-01-04 13:55:14','2005-01-04 18:55:14','<p>So a few days ago I told you about <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2004/12/here-goes-everything/\">finishing the first leg of my education</a>.  The semester was complicated infinitly though by my promotion.  Previously I was Library Technology support.  After a major shift in the chain of command at <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/\">the college</a> I was moved into Web Services, given a new title and a little bit of compensation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have been studying <a href=\"http://www.webstandards.org/\">web standards</a> based design along with server-side languages and database driven web sites for almost two and a half years now.  My skill set has grown significantly and I had been looking for a new job that would utilize these skills.  I had a difficult time finding anything though because I had no official education and the only proof I had that I could do what I said I could do was my personal sites.  And my word... right... personal sites.  I have been given the chance to prove myself.  It\'s probably the best thing (professionally) that could have happened to me.  When I finished <a href=\"http://www.mis.temple.edu/\">my degree at Temple</a> I\'ll also have five years of experience in an academic institution and two years in a development environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only thing that makes it better is that I joined the team at a point just before the first redesign of the site in over a year.  I was able to influence enough to redesign using <a href=\"http://www.webstandards.org/\">web standards</a>.  At the moment there are some hitches we are trying to overcome so the new design isn\'t up.  I didn\'t choose the design, but I am taking the design and marking it up with <acronym title=\"Cascading Style Sheets\">CSS</acronym> and <acronym title=\"eXtensible Hypertext Markup Language\">xHTML</acronym>.  WOW!  How lucky am I?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plus I get along very well with the rest of the department.  We laugh and play and have fun at work.  We listen to music and make jokes about <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">goatse</a>.  Man, jokes about <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">goatse</a>. (Go ahead Mark.  <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">You</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">know</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">you</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">want</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">to</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">click</a> <a href=\"http://goat.cx\">it</a>!)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cheers to Web Services at DCCC!</p>','My promotion',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','my-promotion','','','2005-01-04 22:55:14','2005-01-05 03:55:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/my-promotion/',0,'','',5),
	(41,1,'2004-11-30 23:06:54','2004-12-01 04:06:54','<p>After recent, extensive personnel changes at <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu\">the college</a>, the creative freedoms of my department at work have shifted significantly in a positive way.  This article, <a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/89/creativity.html\">The 6 Myths of Creativity</a>, is interesting though and I think alot of people, from the lowest to the highest, could benefit from the research that Teresa Amabile is doing in creativity research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her first myth, \"Creativity Comes From Creative Types\",  is my favorite.  I have found that a significant amount of people at <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu\">the college</a> either don\'t give their own ideas enough credit or don\'t give each other enough credit. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Michael and I had a meeting today that I watched peoples faces explode with inspiration as they arrived at the same ideas as we had without our coaxing and without the same training and knowledge as we have.  These people still think that we came up with the ideas and we will probably be given credit but really it was their inspiration, not ours, that will lead to improvements in the application that we are building for them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since I moved into a new office and began my new position two weeks ago, I have heard at least three people call the Web Services office the center of the institutions creative juices (among other things - the bachelor pad, the frat house - I digress).  It\'s almost sad that people think that.  I\'m not saying that the new department isn\'t creative.  I\'m not saying that we don\'t accomplish alot of things that haven\'t been attempted before now.  I\'m just saying that there are alot of very creative, interesting ideas coming out of every part of the institution and perhaps more people should give themselves credit.</p>','Creativity Comes From Creative Types',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','','','creativity-comes-from-creative-types','','','2004-11-30 23:06:54','2004-12-01 04:06:54','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/creativity-comes-from-creative-types/',0,'','',0),
	(48,1,'2004-12-13 19:05:56','2004-12-14 00:05:56','<p>Your mom\'s so nasty, she has a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gastrovascular_cavity\">gastrovascular cavity</a>.</p>','Insults that weren\'t...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','insults-that-werent','','','2004-12-13 21:06:52','2004-12-14 02:06:52','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/12/insults-that-werent/',0,'','',5),
	(49,1,'2004-12-20 10:04:28','2004-12-20 15:04:28','<p>Long ago when I first started amassing my ever growing music collection (mp3 collection which is nearing 9,000 songs).  I was a song listener.  I listened to individual songs with little rhyme or reason.  In those days my musical taste was, Shall I say, immature and had not reached the level which it is now.  I have become quite a music snob.  Thanks alot <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a>.</p>\r\n<p>I digress</p>\r\n<p>In those early days of naivety I had little thought of organization and little conscienseness of what I was listening to.  With 300 songs to browse, there was little need.  As my collection has grown though I have lost track of individual songs and they all become one big mass of data.  The individual song has lost its importance. </p>\r\n<p>Albums have become my way of distincting good from bad.  I search for good albums now.  Any retard with half a brain and three fingers can put out a good song.  It takes a real artist to compose a 12 song masterpiece.  A list of songs which speaks to me and tells me a story.  A piece of works which holds my ever waning attention span.  To move me.  To make me feel something, good or bad.</p>\r\n<p>I offer you this list of albums which I consider masterpieces.  Feel free to offer yours as well.  If you are interested in hearing any of these, let me know and maybe you can <del>download them</del> borrow the CD from me.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Underworld - Beaucoup Fish</li>\r\n<li>Lovage - Music to Make Love to Your Old Lady By</li>\r\n<li>Ultraviolence - Life of Destructor</li>\r\n<li>The Mars Volta - De-Loused in the Comatorium</li>\r\n<li>Kid Loco - A Grand Love Story</li>\r\n<li>Shirley Bassey - The Remix Album... Diamonds Are Forever</li>\r\n<li>Venetian Snares - Finding Candace</li>\r\n<li>Coldplay - Parachutes</li>\r\n<li>Radiohead - Kid A</li>\r\n<li>Tom Waits - Anything by Tom Waits, I mean come on, he\'s Tom Waits</li>\r\n</ul>','I am an album listener!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','album-listener','','','2004-12-20 10:04:44','2004-12-20 15:04:44','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/12/album-listener/',0,'','',9),
	(50,1,'2004-12-24 23:29:25','2004-12-25 04:29:25','<p>After two hard faught years I have graduated.  I have finished two out of three degree programs at <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu\">Delaware County Community College</a> and next semester I am off to <a href=\"http://www.temple.edu/\">Temple University</a>.  At <acronym title=\"Delaware County Community College\">DCCC</acronym> I completed the <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/catalog/college_transfer_programs.html#computer_information_systems\">Computer Information Systems</a> program <strong>and</strong> the <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/catalog/college_transfer_programs.html#business_administration\">Business Administration</a> program.  Just under 100 credits.</p>\r\n<p>I\'m freaking proud of myself. It wasn\'t easy working fulltime and going to school fulltime for the last two years but I had some help.  There were a few people at the school in particular that made it possible for me to achieve what I\'ve achieved.  Pedro Navarro and Karen Rege made it possible for me to manuever my schedule between class and work, allowing me to complete my course work.  Eric Wellington with his constant encouragement and ability to deal with 10,000 requests for substituted courses and overriding of placement tests.  Ann Marie Neary for her encouragement and inspiration when I was a know nothing jackass (When I was?).  And of course the never ending love and encouragement of Trish.  She prodded me to apply to Temple.  She forced me to sign up for classes on time.  She listened to me bitch and moan.  And she comforted me each time I had lost hope or direction.  I certainly couldn\'t have done it without her.</p>\r\n<p>The battle isn\'t over though.  I start at Temple in January.  I will be pursuing a <a href=\"http://www.mis.temple.edu/\">Bachelors of Business Administration in Management Information Systems</a> from <a href=\"http://www.sbm.temple.edu/\">Temple\'s Fox School of Business</a>.  I have read some of the course descriptions and I am in love with some of the classes they are offering.  I\'ll keep you all up to date on the developments as I start there.</p>\r\n<p>As a complete aside though I would like to make special note of the Fox website which is Web Standards compliant.  Makes me love it even more.</p>','Here goes everything!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','here-goes-everything','','','2004-12-24 23:31:09','2004-12-25 04:31:09','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2004/12/here-goes-everything/',0,'','',3),
	(92,1,'2005-03-10 23:41:32','2005-03-11 04:41:32','<img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/alifewithoutfacialhair.jpg\"/>\r\n\r\nA life without facial hair... seems like no life at all.  Tomorrow I will be shaving off my beard.  I have been thinking about doing it for a while now.  What\'s held me up though is that I didn\'t know what to do with all the hair I\'ve been saving on my face since August.  I was planning on going sideburnless.  I haven\'t been without sideburns since 1999.  A long time.  It sort of troubled me.  No sideburns?  Just sick.\r\n\r\nI\'ve decided to keep them though.  Tomorrow when I shave my beard I will retain a bit of said beard in a mean pair of sideburns.  I\'ve also decided to do something I have been thinking about doing for a while.  I\'m going to document the changes in my facial hair over the course of the summer.  There will no doubt be plenty of terrible shapes in them and I think that you should all get to enjoy them as much as I will.','A life without facial hair?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-life-without-facial-hair','','','2005-03-10 23:41:38','2005-03-11 04:41:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/a-life-without-facial-hair/',0,'','',4),
