	(95,1,'2005-03-11 10:51:32','2005-03-11 15:51:32','A few weeks ago Don sent me links to sites that will allow you to efile your taxes for free.  The federal tax program is from turbo tax.  It\'s a free version of the program you would buy in the store, but free.  \r\n\r\nDon explained that the Fed was going to develop a free efile site because its so much cheaper when you efile than paper file.  <a href=\"http://www.taxfreedom.com/\">TurboTax</a> threw a fit because it would destroy their business.  They came to an agreement that <a href=\"http://www.taxfreedom.com/\">TurboTax</a> would develop a free version instead of the government, then they just don\'t advertise it.  \r\n\r\nThe <a href=\"http://www.taxfreedom.com/\">TurboTax</a> page is a bit tricky though.  They do the federal return for free, but they will try to charge you for the state.  When I did my returns I accidently did my state on the <a href=\"http://www.taxfreedom.com/\">TurboTax</a> page and then it tried to charge me before I could ship my Federal return.  If it does this, go back to before you did the state return and skip the state and it will remove the charges and you\'ll be able to complete your return.  \r\n\r\nTo do your state return go to the <a href=\"https://pa.direct.file.state.pa.us/authentication.asp\">states website</a> to file.  It\'s free there.  I only have the Pennsylvania site though.  Sorry <a href=\"http://www.greasyvalley.com/\">Chad</a>.','eFile for free!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','efile-for-free','','','2006-04-30 22:10:23','2006-05-01 03:10:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/efile-for-free/',0,'','',10),
	(61,1,'2005-01-17 23:30:08','2005-01-18 04:30:08','<p>When my parents bought their house 30+ years ago they had a bug problem.  Roaches and water bugs wandered all over the place at night.  My mother wanted to spray insect poison around the house but my father asked to have a healthy shot at it first.  He went down to the field down the street and caught crickets, white spiders and something that we have called lions for as long as I can remember<a href=\"#footnote\">*</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem was solved.  This trio of bugs killed every other bug in the house.  When there was nothing else too eat they ate each other.  These canabalistic bastards helped my parents avoid  <a href=\"http://www.halfgiraffe.com/oldlady.html\">The Old Lady Who Swallowed a Fly</a> from being played out in my basement by controlling their own population.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, every spring they reproduce based on the supply of bugs which creep into the house.  When the supply dies down they control again.  It has worked very well for 30 years and we have never had to use pesticides in my house.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All is well right?  Until about a week ago when I father caught this terrifying little creature.  It jumped almost across the basement before it jumped into my father.  He caught it.  I photographed it.  It seems that the crickets and white spiders have mated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/spidercricket01.jpg\" alt=\"Spider Cricket\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/spidercricket02.jpg\" alt=\"Spider Cricket\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/spidercricket03.jpg\" alt=\"Spider Cricket\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/spidercricket04.jpg\" alt=\"Spider Cricket\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p id=\"footnote\"><strong>Footnote:</strong> I don\'t think that they are actually called lions.  They range from very tiny to nearly two inches long.  They look like they could be from the centipede family due to their googol legs, but their legs are long and look fuzzy.  Maybe I will catch a picture of them one day and you can help me identify them.</p>','Spiders, Crickets and lions',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','spiders-crickets-lions','','','2006-02-15 09:11:46','2006-02-15 14:11:46','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/spiders-crickets-lions/',0,'','',69),
	(63,1,'2005-01-14 12:10:45','2005-01-14 17:10:45','<p>I don\'t know how many of you know but Debbie left this morning for four and a half months in San Jaun, Puerto Rico.  She\'s gonna be continuing her studies in Spanish and hot sweaty Latino men.  Before she left I set her up with a blog so we can all be kept abreast to what she is doing.  So visit <a href=\"http://debra.veryraw.com/\">Debbie\'s Blog</a>.  Leave her a message.</p>','Puerto Rico Suave',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','','','puerto-rico-suave','','','2005-01-14 12:10:45','2005-01-14 17:10:45','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/puerto-rico-suave/',0,'','',4),
	(64,1,'2005-01-19 19:54:28','2005-01-20 00:54:28','<p>Let me preface this by reminding everyone that I am a big dude.  I\'m not enormously fat.  I have a gut.  As any man with a gut will attest, possesion of a gut results in a deeper belly button than the normal person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That said... everyday I come home from work, sit at my desk, change my socks, untuck my shirt and pick my belly button.  Everyday when I pick my belly button there is a large ball of belly button lint there.  I remove it, admire it and discard it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Today there was no lint.  Who the fuck stole my belly button lint?!?!?!</strong></p>','Who took it... give it back!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','belly-button-lint','','','2005-01-19 19:54:56','2005-01-20 00:54:56','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/belly-button-lint/',0,'','',6),
	(65,1,'2005-01-25 00:09:33','2005-01-25 05:09:33','<p>Whenever we go for coffee after 10:00 <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> drinks decaf.  I on the other hand refuse.  I have argued many times that for a coffee bean to give up its caffeine they must do something horrible and unholy to it. In this month\'s <a href=\"http://www.nationalgeographic.com/\">National Geographic</a> there is an excellent article about why we love caffeine.  In the article is the image which I have scanned and included below.  I don\'t know about you but that sure looks unholy to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The caption for the image reads...</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Here\'s whats missing from your decaf: A shovelful of caffeine and wax residues rises from the muck as workers decaffeinate coffee beans at a plant in Trieste, Italy</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/caffeinefoam.jpg\" alt=\"caffeine scum\" /></p>','Decaf Jihad',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','decaf-jihad','','','2005-05-05 06:03:46','2005-05-05 11:03:46','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/decaf-jihad/',0,'','',4),
	(69,1,'2005-01-31 20:34:43','2005-02-01 01:34:43','Every one has heard a million things about breast cancer awareness and how we all need to get mammograms.  I think there used to be a breast cancer awareness month out there but I can\'t find evidence of that.  It seems that everyone has given up on trying to restrict this to a month and they let it sread to an entire year.\r\n\r\nThe fact is thought that more men get prostate cancer than woman that get breast cancer.  I have read somewhere that <strong>every</strong> man, given he lives long enough, will get prostate cancer.  Call it the curse of the prostate. But you here very little about it.  I blame this on the fact that its worse to see a woman with no breasts than a man with no asshole.\r\n<p style=\"padding: 5px 0pt 5px 5px; float: right\"><a title=\"Click for large view of Rosebud Cufflinks for National Prostate Cancer Awareness Month\" style=\"border: 0pt none \" href=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/rosebud_cufflinks.jpg\"><img alt=\"Rosebud Cufflinks - for National Prostate Cancer Awareness Month\" src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/medium/rosebudcufflinks.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\nFebruary is \"<a href=\"http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3017091\">Go Red for Woman</a>\" month.  It\'s basically heart health awareness month for woman.  They give out little red dress pins and you wear them to support women\'s heart health.  This is a great idea.  A small, classy momento that gives you a reminder about heart health and woman.\r\n\r\nAs the <a href=\"http://www.prostate-cancer.org.uk/\">Prostate cancer charity</a> website tells me, March 21st through 27th is Prostate Cancer Awareness Week.  I think that all of March should be prostate cancer awareness <em>month</em>.  Men can then stand around and regale everyone with stories of the joy that there prostates have given them.  To raise money and awareness of prostate cancer we can make brown rosebud cufflinks and wear them proudly like the little red dress pin.\r\n\r\n<br style=\"clear: both\" />','Why not Prostate Cancer Awareness Month',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','prostate-cancer-awareness-month','','','2006-02-15 09:50:24','2006-02-15 14:50:24','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/prostate-cancer-awareness-month/',0,'','',5),
	(70,1,'2005-02-07 14:30:09','2005-02-07 19:30:09','<p>...another awesome thing.  Those people being the Internet community I suppose.  You\'ll have to bear with me because I am going to try to explain this properly but I\'m not sure how clear I\'ll be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For about a year now I have been looking for a way to manage links.  I spend a significant amount of time surfing, that is just reading random things on the web about stuff that may not pertain to anything in particular.  I want to save it, but how.  It\'s a common problem, I think.  How can I possibly organize my links so that I can find them later.  Furthermore, how am I supposed to access bookmarks at home that I have made at work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have tried many solutions to this, the most recent of which is extensive link lists on my blog.  This is equally as inefficient because I still have to remember what I wrote about them so I know what to search for when I look for them on my blog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter <a href=\"http://del.icio.us/\">http://del.icio.us/</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It\'s not just a cool looking URL.  It\'s a social bookmarks website. It allows you to bookmark web pages by storing them on your del.icio.us profile page.  Furthermore you can add descriptions and tags.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tags are the most interesting part.  Add as many as you want, they act as categories.  This allows you to keep track of the links the way you want.  In other words the way you think.  This makes finding them easier later.  It also groups them with other links that might be related.  It also shows you how many others have saved it and allows you to see all other links which have been saved using the same tag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tagging is known as folksonomy, a term coined by Thomas Vander Wal.  Basically its a taxonomic categorization system without the strict rules.  Its categorization by free association.  This concept has been used in several Internet applications including del.icio.us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have not experimented extensively with this application yet.  I have a few uses for it which I will share at a later date.  Go test del.icio.us out.  You won\'t regret it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folksonomy\">More on folksonomy from wikipedia</a>.</p> ','From the people who bring you awesome stuff...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','delicious-one','','','2005-02-07 14:30:39','2005-02-07 19:30:39','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/delicious-one/',0,'','',1),
	(72,1,'2005-03-05 12:13:47','2005-03-05 17:13:47','So after flaming <a href=\"http://del.icio.us/\">del.icio.us</a> when I told him about it <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/?p=47\">Mark admitting he was wrong</a> about it all along.  In fact, he found a use for it.  He\'s using it to help himself build a modular synth.  His application is interesting but for me lacks a personal, real world application.  Other than for retaining resources and links to stuff that I may want to come back to later, my primary use has been the link feed on the side.  A way to share the sort of information I am consuming.\r\n\r\nI have another application \r\n\r\nWhen applied to research this has great applications.  I just finished a presentation for my MIS class.  I have 10 white papers, 5 vendors, 35 news articles and 3 journal articles about the topic.  <a href=\"http://del.icio.us/timmyfury/rfid\">I save them all in del.icio.us and later I can see what I have saved</a>.  Giving them similar tags and describing them a bit I can sort through my sources later.  As you widdle down your sources you can delete them from your list.  If you find the particular part or information you want to use in each document you can add that as the extended description.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, this could also be applied to abstracts for books that you want to find later.  coupled with <http ://scholar.google.com\">Google Scholar, this becomes a mean tool in the beginning stages of research.  The stage where you just harvest large amounts of information for later combing (this assumes that everyone researches the same way as I do). \r\n \r\nLater when you have finished your paper and you are citing your works, you have a conveniant list of all of your sources and some bits about how and where they were used.</http>','more on social bookmarks.... An application',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','more-on-social-bookmarks-an-application','','','2005-03-05 12:14:11','2005-03-05 17:14:11','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/more-on-social-bookmarks-an-application/',0,'','',2),
	(74,1,'2005-02-10 22:41:08','2005-02-11 03:41:08','<p>August 3, 2004.  The day I registered for <a href=\"http://www.audioscrobbler.com/user/timmyfury/\">Audioscrobbler</a>.  What\'s Audioscrobbler you ask?   It\'s a service that creates a profile of your musical taste.  I registered shortly after properly tagging all of my (now 9,641) mp3\'s using <a href=\"http://musicbrainz.org/\">MusicBrainz</a>.  Initially I did it to be able to utilize the iPod which I had then not purchased.  Audioscrobbler was just an added bonus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I recently cracked 7,000 songs on my Audioscrobbler profile.  If you look at the profile you will notice a few things.  By the weekly statistics you will notice that I listen to the same bands over and over again.  I may have alot of music but generally I cycle through a lot of the same stuff.  The most notable thing that you\'ll see though is although I have a pretty varying taste in music, Tom Waits appears to be by far my favorite musician.  I suppose that although I am a whore for a good break beat, I can\'t get enough of this crooner\'s twisted melodies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am recommending to all who read my site and enjoy listening to music as they while away their youth, sign up for this service.  It\'s simple and fun, you can add people as your friends and get music recommendations.  You can create and join groups.  You can be like me, a slut for data and statistics.  I liked it enough I even donated and got the sexy little plus sign next to my name.  Go.  Do it.  And tell me what your profile name is so I can add you as my friend.</p>','Long Live Tom Waits !',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','long-live-tom-waits','','','2005-02-10 22:41:24','2005-02-11 03:41:24','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/long-live-tom-waits/',0,'','',1),
	(76,1,'2005-02-25 17:01:01','2005-02-25 22:01:01','A few months ago I wrote about <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/my-promotion/\">my most recent promotion</a>.  The results of this on my life have been amazing.  Trish has noted many times since how little I bitch about my job now.  The frustration level is so long in my new position that its more of a pleasure than a pain to go to work.  \r\n\r\nOne of the differences between this job and the previous is that I am no longer crawling around on floors.  I\'m either at my desk or meeting with people about projects that we are working on.  There is little physical exertion (outside of lifting my coffee cup).  So I have started to \"dress for success\".  That means shirt and tie - every day. I\'m actually enjoying it too.  I\'ve been buying new stuff pretty consistantly.  To a fault actually, I spend nearly my entire paycheck every two weeks now on shirts and ties and pants and shoes.  \r\n\r\nThe reason I mention this is because I have made one very important observation.  Take this to heart men.  If you are buying ties, you may not think that there is a difference between a $15  and a $60 tie, but there is.  When you tie a $15 tie, it may look alright at first but by the end of the day you have a tight knot at your neck.  Looks alright but not as good as it did when you first put it on.   When you tie a $60 tie, you get a nice meaty knot.  At the end of the day you still have that meaty knot.  The tie looks exactly the same at the end of the day.\r\n\r\nSo don\'t spare expense on your ties.  You can get cheap shoes, pants and shirts if your budget doesn\'t warrant expensive clothes.  You will still look good.  People don\'t notice these things.  People always notice your tie.  If you cheap out on your ties, everyone will know that you cheaped out on your ties.','$60 dollar ties',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','60-dollar-ties','','','2005-02-25 17:01:20','2005-02-25 22:01:20','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/60-dollar-ties/',0,'','',6),
	(77,1,'2005-02-14 02:16:12','2005-02-14 07:16:12','<p>I am attempting to set up a script that will pull my last 10 <a href=\"http://del.icio.us/timmyfury\">del.icio.us</a> links and drop them into a list on the side so you always get my freshest links (that\'s ill).  The <a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=getting+delicious+feed\">search that I performed</a> gave me some really good leads to what I am actually looking for.  It also gave me a site that is slightly disturbing...</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/babyfood2.jpg\" alt=\"disturbing results\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have said it a million times.  I do not care for children.  I know I work at a science museum. I know my job is with children.  Dealing with children as a large group is very different than dealing with children one on one.  I\'m not so good with the later.  The former I excel at because I\'ve learn that dealing with large groups of children is like dealing with a very large herd of sheep.  You push a few in a general direction and the rest will usually follow.  Then when all else fails if you talk really loudly and make broad gestures, they will try to get away from you.  Works well in my job because the parents think that you are really good with children when you are actually just really terrifying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My point is, if I may go as far as to say I have one, I was not searching for recipes for children.  Although this site leads me to believe that there is a book out there that provides you with that variety of information. I was going to quote parts of the page for you to prove it.  It\'s just better if you <a href=\"http://www.healthy-baby-food.com/baby_recipe.htm\">go there yourself</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n','Dear, why don\'t we have the children over for dinner?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','children-for-dinner','','','2005-02-14 02:16:25','2005-02-14 07:16:25','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/children-for-dinner/',0,'','',1),
	(78,1,'2005-02-14 09:54:35','2005-02-14 14:54:35','<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12075094/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/12075094_63c3926f59.jpg\" width=\"403\" height=\"500\" alt=\"Kim Jong Valentine\" /></a>','Happy Valentines from North Korea!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','vday-north-korea','','','2005-05-02 21:49:29','2005-05-03 02:49:29','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/vday-north-korea/',0,'','',1),
	(79,1,'2005-02-17 10:54:20','2005-02-17 15:54:20','<p>I was listening to <a href=\"http://www.whyy.org/91FM/RadioTimes.html\">Radio Times</a> on WHYY this morning and I heard the funniest analogy about the Middle East.  They were talking about the recent <a href=\"http://www.voanews.com/english/2005-02-17-voa15.cfm\">assination of the former Prime Minister of Lebanon</a> wich is being blamed in Syria.  I forget the name of the guest but here goes.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\nA frog and a scorpion are sitting on the banks of a river.  Scorpion says, \"Frog, can you swim me across the river?\" Frog says, \"No! you\'ll sting me!\" To which scorpion replies, \"I wouldn\'t do that, if I were to sting you we would both drown.\"  So as they are crossing the river, scorpion stings frog. As they are sinking into the river frog asks, \"Why did you sting me?\" \"Because its the Middle East,\" replies scorpion.\r\n</blockquote>','The Middle East: a joke?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','middle-east-joke','','','2005-02-17 10:54:41','2005-02-17 15:54:41','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/middle-east-joke/',0,'','',6),
	(80,1,'2005-02-20 22:52:25','2005-02-21 03:52:25','<p><a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> and I went to the Monster Truck Jam this afternoon.  It was supposed to be Trish and I but Trish is spending a week in Korea recruiting exchange students for the school.  Great seats they were.  Those trucks are so freaking loud.  I had forgotten how loud they were.  My father used to take me to those like every year it seemed when I was much younger and it seems that every single time I had to get out of there because it was far too loud.  We got two extra seats about 10 minutes in because the guy next to us had to leave with his kid.  </p>\r\n<p>There were three trucks there which deserve special mention.  The first is The Broker.  It was funny because on the side it had a skeletal hand writing \"Your policy has expired.\"  Second was the Safe Auto Minimizer.  What a funny name.  Like minimizing accidents.  Funny.  And then of course the truck that I loved when I was younger.  Grave digger.  I used to root for that truck all the time when I watched it on TV.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/thebroker02.jpg\" alt=\"The Broker sitting\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/trucks01.jpg\" alt=\"Gravedigger and The Minimizer sitting before a run.\" /></p>\r\n<p>There are some more pictures inside.</p>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/thebroker01.jpg\" alt=\"The Broker right before he pounces this purple van\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/thebroker03.jpg\" alt=\"The Broker way in the air!\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/madusa01.jpg\" alt=\"Madusa (the only chick driver) flying\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/madusa02.jpg\" alt=\"Madusa\'s rearend\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/hotwheels01.jpg\" alt=\"Hot Wheels up in the air!\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/maxd01.jpg\" alt=\"Maximum Destruction in the air.\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/madusa03.jpg\" alt=\"Madusa Jumps high!\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/raceoftrucks01.jpg\" alt=\"Grave Digger takes the Carolina Crusher!\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/gravedigger01.jpg\" alt=\"Grave Digger Jumps!\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/gravedigger02.jpg\" alt=\"Grave Digger Spins!\" /></p>','Monster Truck Jam',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','monster-truck-jam','','','2005-03-14 18:47:31','2005-03-14 23:47:31','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/monster-truck-jam/',0,'','',4),
	(84,1,'2005-03-04 00:24:15','2005-03-04 05:24:15','<p>This is my fifth year working Camp-in at the <a href=\"http://fi.edu/\">Franklin Institute</a>.  I noticed every year that I would spend a significant amount of time giving directions to campers to nearly no avail. The problem is this - your average person loses track of what you\'ve told them after about three rights and a left.  Myself, if you try to tell me the steps of a process, my brain takes a break after about five steps.  What would have helped in this endeavor is signs.  Nothing.  The signage in the museum was always dismal at best.  </p>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://www.sba.gov/test/wbc/docs/chart_courses/signs.html\">A visible, readable sign, can make the difference between profit and loss for your business. Many businesses attribute a large percentage of their business to their signs.<br /><a href=\"http://www.sba.gov/test/wbc/docs/chart_courses/signs.html\">Small Business Administration - Women\'s Business Center</a></blockquote>\r\n<img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/medium/tfisignage01.jpg\" style=\"float:right;padding:5px 0 5px 5px;\" /><p>This statement could be applied to the museum\'s environment.  The success of the museum depends on patrons getting to see what they came to see.  After five years working there I know the halls and stairs and elevators in  a coma.  That\'s after five years.  Every stairway and elevator leads to a different section of the building.  Third floor on this elevator takes you to staff only areas.  On that elevator third floor leads to exciting exhibits.  There was never a difference to visitors because nothing was there to notify them.</p>\r\n<p>That all changed this year.</p>\r\n<p>The signs started appearing slowly in the beginning of this Camp-in season and over the course of this year have taken over.  I don\'t think that I\'ve been asked for directions once; the signs take care of it. </p>\r\n<p>If you look at the first sign here (from the main elevator), there\'s a different color for each floor.  A trend that continues throughout.  They are basic and clean, simple and clear.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/tfisignage06.jpg\" /></p>\r\n<p>Whats more is they\'re modular.  The sign above is a perfect example of this.  On the third floor Moneyville is on the sign.  Moneyville is a traveling exhibit that will only be at the museum for a little while.  When <a href=\"http://www.bodyworlds.com/en/pages/home.asp\">Body Worlds</a> comes toward the end of the year, they\'ll be able to swap out Moneyville for Body Worlds.  The signs are built from many little signs.  Very ingenious.</p>\r\n<img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/medium/tfisignage04.jpg\" style=\"float:right;padding:5px 0 10px 5px;\" />\r\n<p>This principle is applied in other places like the observatory.  If it\'s closed they post the closed sign.  If it\'s open, the open sign.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/tfisignage05.jpg\" /></p>\r\n<p>If you\'ve ever given directions at the museum you know that they all involve the Pendulum Staircase.  Boldly labeled.  So important.  These stairs will take you anywhere.  So important to label them.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/tfisignage03.jpg\" /></p>\r\n<p>What I like most about the signs though is the iconography.  Every exhibit or area has its own icon.  They are simple, just white shapes and outlines, but they are descriptive.  I personally have a strong affinity for the sultry Ben Franklin icon used for the memorial.</p>\r\n<p>I asked around and the king\'s gold  goes to Jeanne Maier and Jacey Stroback for this excellent signage.  I haven\'t met either one of these marvelous designers but thought I would mention them and rave.</p>','Signage at the Franklin Institute',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','signage','','','2005-05-05 06:03:01','2005-05-05 11:03:01','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/signage/',0,'','',1),
	(82,1,'2005-02-24 01:03:59','2005-02-24 06:03:59','<p>Well, I have been offline at home for two days.  What a joke.  It\'s all gravy though.  Gave me some time to read and scan images.  Have you seen <a href=\"http://www.picasa.com/\">Google\'s Picassa</a>?  Amazing.  It\'s given me control over my image information that I never thought was possible.  Leave it to Google I suppose.  I really think I am just going to give up and turn my life over to Google.  More on this later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have had some time to think about the site though.  I have a ton of ideas for veryraw.  I am not sure how I am going to execute them yet.  I am going to add some new sections and shit.  I found the archives from timmyfury (for those of you who were here last year).  I am going to post that.  I think I am going to put up a section for some illustrations and animations from old.  Little more integration of other services (audioscrobbler, del.icio.us).  More frequent updates.  A portfolio which is slowly becoming something worthwhile. And finally a gallery area.  The galleries will probably be a passworded area.  I have alot of images that I would like to share but its really a controlled area.  Don\'t want the world seeing everything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The other major change will be the implementation of wordpress 1.5.  It looks pretty amazing.  I had wrestled with the idea of abandoning wordpress altogether and developing my own blogging software again but there\'s really no ROI on that.  The only reason to do that would be to build on my skills but I don\'t foresee it helping me expand on anything that I am currently focusing.  So I\'ll stick with wordpress.  When I do it the site is gonna be really messed up for a few days.  It\'ll still be functional though.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you hadn\'t noticed I have been playing with the right column.  I have added a running list of 15 links from my del.icio.us profile.  They are really just everything that I want to save.  You\'re getting everything there.  The nerdiest of the nerdy and the best of the best links.  I haven\'t decided how to deal with that yet but I was getting tired of having all those links lying around so there you are. Furthermore, there are alot of links over there.  Mark has complained but I\'m really paying attention to what I actually read and find most interesting and when I switch over to 1.5 I will narrow that a bit.  Again it\'s one of those things that I have been thinking about.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So this may, for many of you, be a completely superflous entry.  It was almost more of a gather my thoughts entry.  Free association and the like.   I have alot of ideas right now and I need to keep track or I\'ll lose it all.</p>','The future is veryraw',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','','','future-is-veryraw','','','2005-02-24 01:03:59','2005-02-24 06:03:59','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/future-is-veryraw/',0,'','',1),
	(138,1,'2005-04-27 00:54:20','2005-04-27 05:54:20','<p>I just finished <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0375400117/qid=1114579690/sr=8-2/ref=pd_csp_2/002-0835285-8996851?v=glance&s=books&n=507846\">Memoirs of a Geisha</a>.  It\'s good.  It\'s really good.  I had a hard time putting it down.  I don\'t read alot of fiction, but I\'ve taken several things from this book that should be noted.  The first few are strictly on a nerdy, I learned something so it wasn\'t a complete waste, level.  The book goes into great detail about the life of a geisha.  The rituals and the customs.  If you had asked me before I read the book to play word association and you said \"geisha,\" I would have replied, \"prostitute.\"  How wrong I would have been.  Arthur Golden\'s extensive research into the world of geisha is apparent and more than succeeded in destroying any preconceived notions I may have had.  Furthermore, it was a look into a culture that generally remains closed. </p>\r\n<p>The second thing that I took from the book was its look at the everyday life of the Japanese during World War 2.  The fact that the entire people were not gung ho intot he war and that they were forced to be so should be known.  It carries weight now for Americans.  Not all of us like the war we are fighting or the policy we are preaching.  I hope that the rest of the world sees this.  It\'s also poignant now in  Japan, where the Chinese are pissed about the glossing over of war discretions in Japanese textbooks.  <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/in-history-class/\">I\'m not saying that its okay to ignore those things</a>. What I am saying is that its important that the Chinese (in the textbook example) and the world as a whole (in the US example) realize that the entire country isn\'t neccesarily on the same page.</p>\r\n<h3>The book impacted me further though...</h3>\r\n<p>Sayuri, the main character, goes through several traumatic moments in her life and comes out all the better in the end.  The focus though is that with every change she never gives up. She keeps going.  The way she deals with death and loss and setbacks is stoic.  She lets go of things quickly. This allows her to pick up and go on.\r\n</p><p>\"Memoirs of a Geisha\" emphasizes that change is inevitable.  I feel like the book was enforcing the idea that you have to be able to bounce back.  You have to deal with change, confront it and try not to avoid it, try not to lose yourself in it.</p>\r\n','Memoirs of a Geisha',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','memoirs-of-a-geisha','','','2005-05-05 06:01:25','2005-05-05 11:01:25','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/memoirs-of-a-geisha/',0,'','',2),
	(91,1,'2005-03-10 22:12:18','2005-03-11 03:12:18','<p>This may be one of those hit or miss illustrations.  Inspired by my extreme distaste for the cold of late...<br />\r\n<strong>SpringComes!</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/16928034/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos12.flickr.com/16928034_280e27e306.jpg\" width=\"393\" height=\"500\" alt=\"springcomes\" /></a></p>','Spring Comes!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','spring-comes','','','2005-06-01 14:51:25','2005-06-01 19:51:25','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/spring-comes/',0,'','',0),
	(104,1,'2004-03-16 20:47:30','2004-03-17 01:47:30','So the other day I get home and my Mom hands me a fist full of mail.  There are two letters of minimal importance and then there is this letter from the DMV.  For those of you who know anything about my past, particularly in the vehicular sense, can probably guess that I am at this moment staring at the letter spreading peanut butter in my pants.\r\n\r\nThe envelope is about two inches thick.  I\'m like, \"This can\'t be good.\"\r\n\r\nI open it up and I find this letter from the litterbug hotline. I\'m reading it in complete disbelief for two reasons. First, there\'s a such thing as the <a href=\"http://www.dep.state.pa.us/dep/deputate/airwaste/wm/Litter/Facts/Report.htm\" title=\"The Litterbug Hotline Information Page\">litterbug hotline</a>. And second, who the fuck in their right mind would report me to the <a href=\"http://www.litterbug.org/index.htm\" title=\"the litterbug hotline website\">Litterbug Hotline</a>?\r\n\r\nMy first instinct was to blame one of my friends.  Naturally since just about everyone I know  is a complete jerk, this is not out of the realm of understanding.\r\n\r\nSecond accusation was for my father.  I called him this morning to tell him the story and   he was in the middle of teaching a safety course to a bunch of truckers, whom I might add I could hear chuckling in the background.  Actually, when I first called and said I got a letter from the DMV he said, \"Does the letter say that because of your recent speeding issue in Georgia,  we believe you should get your <acronym title=\"Commercial Drivers Liscense\">CDL</acronym>.\"  This got a good reaction   out of the drivers.\r\n\r\nSo anyway to round the story out and finish up. The reason why the envelope was so thick, was not because of a pack of septa tokens. There was a trash bag in the envelope too.\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/21028827/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos15.flickr.com/21028827_54cc864176_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Litter Letter\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/21028765/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos17.flickr.com/21028765_a299169c05_m.jpg\" width=\"174\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Litter bag\" /></a></p>','The Litterbug Hotline - 1.888.litterbug!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','litterbug-hotline','','','2005-06-23 14:17:05','2005-06-23 19:17:05','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/104/',0,'','',0),
