	(86,1,'2005-02-27 01:22:42','2005-02-27 06:22:42','Well I said I would wait for a little while to upgrade to <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/development/2005/02/strayhorn/\">Wordpress 1.5</a>.  The problem with that is that I was burning to test out a few new plugins for it.  Plus I had read a bit about the templating system in 1.5.  The theme system is amazing.  You make a theme and then it becomes transportable.  Pretty wild.  I\'ll be interested to see how it ports to the old versions of wordpress after I try to make a theme based on the old design. If I can get it to work then I can upgrade <a href=\"http://debra.veryraw.com/\">Debbie\'s</a> blog too without being forced to spend any time redesigning her\'s too.\r\n\r\nI was going to spend alot of time on this redesign.  I was going to attempt some amazing graphical feats.  I was.  But I got a little tired of sitting here working on it.  Plus I liked the minimalist thing that I\'ve got going on here.  I still have some things to address.  The comments are not looking nice. I think I want to address the way the side menus are looking.  I haven\'t even used the page part of wordpress 1.5 which is the part I was most excited about. So the point is this.  The sites not finished.  Anyone who has been following my blog for any amount of time knows that it changes like every 5 seconds.\r\n\r\nLet me know what you think.  Gimme feedback.  Tear it up.  Tell me what you love but more importantly what you hate.  Thanks.','A little redesign action',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','','','a-little-redesign-action','','','2005-02-27 01:22:42','2005-02-27 06:22:42','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/a-little-redesign-action/',0,'','',9),
	(87,1,'2005-03-02 01:40:24','2005-03-02 06:40:24','Michael, <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> and I were talking about great acronyms for technology systems.  Two of Michael\'s favorites are Digital Asset Management System (DAM) and Project Management System (PMS).  Conversation takes a turn for the worst and we come up with these further examples of wonderful systems.\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Standard Hub of Internet Technology System</li>\r\n<li>Closed Unification Network Terminal</li>\r\n<li>Asset Sorting System</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<acronym title=\"Standard Hub of Internet Technology System\">SHITS</acronym> is an example of a <acronym title=\"Closed Unification Network Terminal\">CUNT</acronym> which allows you to access your <acronym title=\"Asset Sorting System\">ASS</acronym>.\r\n\r\nI\'ll leave it up to y\'all to take it too far.','Acronyms: fun with jargon for the technically inclined.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','fun-with-jargon','','','2005-03-02 01:43:41','2005-03-02 06:43:41','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/fun-with-jargon/',0,'','',5),
	(89,1,'2005-03-07 19:44:56','2005-03-08 00:44:56','I must admit, when the election was wrapped up I <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/bush-wins-we-all-lose/\">flamed</a> about how stupid Bush voters were and how the country was going to fail.  I wasn\'t really mad, I was drenched in despair.  I was sad; very sad.\r\n\r\nFour months later the feelings of remorse are gone.  The things that I thought were going to happen haven\'t happened.  The war in Iraq (which was not one of my issues) has, at least for the time being, seemed to spark a near epidemic of Middle Eastern Democracy&trade;.  Nations we never though would embrace the flavor of Middle Eastern Democracy&trade; are jumping on the bandwagon like its full of free Kalishnakofs.  Some oposition groups in these countries have gone as far as to say that Bush\'s invasion of Iraq was the starting point for these reforms - in other words, without them there would be little change.  \r\n\r\nAs for social security, which is the only other big move that Bush has pushed since his inuaguration in January, I don\'t have a problem with what he\'s saying.  There have been minimal specifics but <a href=\"http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4525458\">Bush is touting his plan</a> like a superstar.  There are alot of problems and benefits but to be honest, the important thing is that he gets people talking about it.  With the exception of minor changes and modifications to who and how people can receive their benefits, no president has really touched Social security since its <a href=\"http://www.ssa.gov/history/history.html\">inception</a>.  I really don\'t think that Bush\'s major contribution to Social Security will be reform.  I think it will be rhetoric.\r\n\r\nWhat really bothered me about Bush\'s re-election was less about the next four years and more about the next thirty.  There was alot of talk about the chance for whoever was elected to nominate up to <a href=\"http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/justices/fullcourt.html\">four supreme court justices</a>.  This scared me because the impact of a judge spans a lifetime as opposed to the duration of a term.  Furthermore, they aren\'t elected so they can stay non-partisan&trade;.  \r\n\r\nThe popular interpretation of the system of checks and balances gives the Supreme Court a whole lot more power than the President or Congress.  They rule on the actions of both branches in a direct way and, whether or not its the way its supposed to be, they have final say in what happens in government.  This of course may be an improper interpretation but it is the way I see it and a trend that I have seen in conversations prior to and since the election.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.legalaffairs.org/issues/March-April-2005/review_strauss_marapr05.msp\">Legal Affairs</a> published a piece which corroborated my viewpoint.\r\n\r\n<blockquote>SHOULD THE SUPREME COURT HAVE THE LAST WORD on what the Constitution means? Among the justices, and probably the general population as well, the answer seems obvious: Of course it should. That is what it means to be governed by law. But among constitutional law scholars, one of the hot new ideas is \"popular constitutionalism,\" a theory that \"the people,\" acting through politics, should determine the meaning of the Constitution. According to the popular constitutionalists, either the Supreme Court should get out of the business of interpreting the Constitution or, more combatively, the people should retaliate against the court when it interprets the Constitution in ways with which they disagree.<br /><a href=\"http://www.legalaffairs.org/issues/March-April-2005/review_strauss_marapr05.msp\">Legal Affairs: Pop Con</a></blockquote>\r\n\r\nThis is a point that I have never thought and puts me a little more at ease.  The idea that after a law or action is shot down by the courts, it could be brought back to life in another way by the other branches is wonderful.  It gives some mortality to the decisions of the courts and puts less power in their hands. Perhaps this fact will help keep the Supreme Court impartial&trade; and non-partisan&trade;.\r\n','I was a Bush Nay-sayer.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','judicial-supremecy','','','2006-04-14 11:33:27','2006-04-14 16:33:27','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/judicial-supremecy/',0,'','',4),
	(119,1,'2005-04-21 21:50:52','2005-04-22 02:50:52','<p>When I was just a wee lad in elementary and secondary school I was more interested in sciences than I was in history.  I\'m kind of glad I was though because I wouldn\'t have learned much anyway. I was talking to my nephew yesterday when he found a coin that Trish had brought back from <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/sets/246823/\">South Korea</a> a few weeks ago. The information that he\'s missing about the History of the world astounds me.</p>\r\n<p>In school textbooks the history of the United States looks like this...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Christopher Columbus discovers North America</li>\r\n<li>Pilgrims land on Plymouth rock and befriend the Indians there.  The Indians love their new friends.</li>\r\n<li>Ben Franklin and George Washington lead the colonies to victory in the Revolutionary war against the Bristish</li>\r\n<li>Civil War</li>\r\n<li>Abraham Lincoln Dies</li>\r\n<li>Great Depression</li>\r\n<li>World Wars</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Thats it for the History of the United States.  Nothing else significant happened in over 500 years of history.</p>\r\n<p>I bring this up because I have been watching alot of <a href=\"http://www.historychannel.com/\">History Channel</a> lately.  Two shows in particular have been of particular interest.  \"<a href=\"http://www.historychannel.com/conquest/\">Conquest of America</a>\" and \"<a href=\"http://www.historychannel.com/global/listings/series_showcase.jsp?EGrpType=Series&Id=14304702&NetwCode=THC\">The Conquerors</a>.\"  These shows have really brought to my attention how many holes there are in my knowledge of US history. Now if I can say this with out sounding arrogant I\'ll be surprised. If someone as intelligent as I am can be so amiss of information than what is the state of things in the average uninquisitive American\'s brain?</p>\r\n<p>While I was watching \"The Conquerors\" last night I saw a parallel between the Conquest of Florida and our present day conquest of Iraq.  There are historical similarities where the White house tells the people and the world one thing when they have a completely seperate agenda at hand.  Perhaps if more of America knew about the past, they would have made better choices in the polls last November, or at least they would be as smart as Europeans are to question what is going on in the government.</p>\r\n<p>I get the feeling that the lack of real history education in American schools is not exactly unintentional.  Although this could be another one of my <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/efile-for-free/\">conspiracy theories</a>.  This same sort of thing is causing trouble in China right now over the Japanese leaving their past out of textbooks. I think that when you leave a bunch of stuff out and people question their own government a little less and the somewhat unsavory activities of a government are ignored. </p>\r\n<blockquote>Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it.<br /><a href=\"http://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/George_Santayana\">George Santayana</a></blockquote>','Shouldn\'t they teach me that in History class?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','in-history-class','','','2005-04-21 21:51:05','2005-04-22 02:51:05','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/shouldnt-they-teach-me-that-in-history-class/',0,'','',4),
