	(311,1,'2006-02-15 09:31:03','2006-02-15 14:31:03','<p>If you read this in RSS <a href=\"http://veryraw.com\">click on over</a> to the site, it\'s been completely overhauled.  I\'ve been working on the output of wordpress for a while.  Although I could have just downloaded a theme and skinned it, I decided not to.  I went from the ground up and built exactly what I wanted.  After mangling my site in attempts to be obnoxious after yet another insult for big fonts I thought it was time to finish off the work I\'d done and make veryraw look a bit cleaner and a little more professional. </p>\r\n<p>Although the site is best viewed in something larger than 1024x768, viewers of lesser resolution won\'t lose the content.  The left column is fixed width, but the right is not.  The right column will stretch to the edge of the browser window, and all the additional content in the right column will float to take up as much of the space as possible.</p>\r\n<p>There are a few other additions to the site that I am particularly excited about.  On the homepage, the top of the right column will be occupied by quick thoughts.  These are entries about links or ideas or news that don\'t warrant full out articles, but I still want to note.  I think I shyed away from posting these in the past because they took up so much real estate on the homepage.  So the hope is to increase posting by assigning these to a special area.</p>\r\n<p>The second biggest change is in the navigation of the site.  Across the top there are several links to external sites.  Some of these will eventually become content on veryraw.  I wanted to get the template up and running before I developed that content, but some of those links will change.  Furthermore, the floating bottom content in the right column is different depending on what page you are visiting.  In archives you get different lists than if you are reading an article.  The biggest benefit to all this is that I can target the content here to be as helpful as possible for the current content, rather than viewing the same additional content all the time.  Of note are the \"Similar entries\" column on the single article page, and the \"favorite entries\" in the archives area and on my 404 page.</p>\r\n<p>The <acronym title=\"Cascading Style Sheets\">CSS</acronym> was rough but it came together.  There are some details still to address which I couldn\'t address without the real content.  I have tons of stuff that I can add now that I have the flexible additional content areas.  Let me know what you think and if there is anything strange going on.</p>','Live for your redesigned pleasure.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','live-for-your-redesigned-pleasure','','','2006-02-15 09:31:03','2006-02-15 14:31:03','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/02/live-for-your-redesigned-pleasure/',0,'','',3),
	(111,1,'2005-03-29 01:13:18','2005-03-29 06:13:18','A few days after I wrote my last entry I received a comment from an old friend.  I was curious to see how they found me.  I searched for names they would have called me.  You know... derivatives of my name, not the names I am generally called on a regular basis (some too nasty to mention here).  \"Tim Crowe\", \"Timmy Crowe\"... nothing.  \"Timothy Crowe\"? Nothing? What? What the fuck happened?\r\n\r\nWell the last time I did a search for Timothy Crowe, I came up with four general results...\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Timothy Crowe the business professor in Auckland, New Zealand</li>\r\n<li>Timothy Crowe the stage actor</li>\r\n<li>Timothy Crowe the criminologist</li>\r\n<li>Timothy Crowe the web developer</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nThe last one being me.  Of course the nature of my profession gave me a higher standing in the results.  I came up all over the place.  Postings on forums, my professional page at the college, and a few of the other sites that I have profiles at.  This had caused some confusion in the past.  I have recieved emails from people looking for Timothy Crowe the criminologist.  Enough that I have a pre-formed email to send in response to help these poor souls find the proper Timothy Crowe.\r\n\r\nNow its like google doesn\'t even know me.  There are all these other Timothy Crowe\'s out there.  I\'m scared.  It\'s picked up my 43things profile (a site that tracks goals which I started playing with like a week ago) but has kicked veryraw off the front page altogether (and all subsequent pages as well).  I read an article about what happens to small business\' when google changes their algorithms.  They lose online traffic because they lose their places.  But seriously, Losing your own freaking name?  That\'s rediculous!\r\n\r\nSee also: <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/narcissism-101/\">Narcissism 101</a>','But Google, we had such a good thing going!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','but-google','','','2005-03-29 01:14:36','2005-03-29 06:14:36','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/but-google-we-had-such-a-good-thing-going/',0,'','',0),
	(217,1,'2005-06-01 21:39:31','2005-06-02 02:39:31','<p>There\'s nothing in the world I hate more then an animated gif, but I just had to make this one when I saw the two pictures on <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/bratacious/\">Michelle\'s flickr page</a>.  It\'s two images of me at South of the Border.  You know I can never turn down a chance to dry hump something.</p>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/things/hump.gif\" height=\"40%\" width=\"40%\" /></p>','Humping a big red dog',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','humping-a-big-red-dog','','','2005-06-01 21:41:35','2005-06-02 02:41:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/217/',0,'','',1),
	(113,1,'2005-03-29 19:31:05','2005-03-30 00:31:05','<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B000683IB4/ref=m_art_li_5/002-0835285-8996851?v=glance&s=music\"><img src=\"http://images.amazon.com/images/P/B000683IB4.01._SCMZZZZZZZ_.jpg\" style=\"float:right;border:1px solid #ccc;margin: 0 0 5px 5px;\" /></a>\r\n<p>I saw this album in the stores a few weeks ago and thought the cover was intriguing.  I wrote down the web address with the intent of checking it out.  Never did.  So the other day I picked up a copy of Details magazine and in the back read a review of <a href=\"http://www.kerenann.com/\">Keren Ann</a>. Something peaked my interest...</p>\r\n<blockquote>The lyrics feature enough stalkers, dysfunctional lovers, and grizzled freaks to populate a fistful of Tom Waits albums.</blockquote>\r\n<p>If you have read my site for a while you know I am a huge Tom Waits fan.  I know most of his later stuff and enjoy almost all of it.  It\'s some sorrow filled shit.  So I\'m all, \"Pffffft, they ain\'t no way that this shit could be as sad as Tom Waits.\"  So I buy the album.</p>\r\n<p>I was listening to it today at work and started feeling so sullen and surly that I could have downed an entire bottle of Old Crow.  Damn, this shit is good.</p>\r\n<p>The sound of her voice is soothing and whispery.  The lyrics are haunting.  The album will make you happy and sad at the same time.  Its amazing.  The album is sung partly in French (I love the French language).</p>\r\n<p>Buy this album or message me and we\'ll \"talk about it further\".</p>','Sorrow so good I could cry myself hysterical.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','kerenann-nolita','','','2005-05-02 21:53:08','2005-05-03 02:53:08','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/sorrow-so-good-i-could-cry-myself-to-hysterical/',0,'','',0),
	(135,1,'2005-04-25 11:47:59','2005-04-25 16:47:59','<p>On Morning Edition this morning I heard <a href=\"http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4618061\">a story about the music industry\'s latest attempt to curb file sharing</a>.  The dual disc.  A dual disc is a double sided disc that features the  music on one side and video features on the other.   The idea is that by offering additional content on the second side of the disc, people won\'t download the music rather than buy it.  The biggest benefit they think is that the discs use existing technology and the consumer will not need to buy anything to use them. </p>\r\n<p>There are two major drawbacks I see with this technology.  First of all the discs are thicker than a normal cd making it difficult for older cd player to read.  The second one is that the \"additional features\" that the music industry is offering are completely worthless to most consumers.  Personally I buy a cd for music.  I don\'t want video of my favorite band.  How many times can you possibly watch a video of a band?  How much value does this really add.  More over, the discs are more expensive which makes me want to buy them less.  </p>\r\n<p>They are basing their concept on that of the movie industry\'s bonus features concept for DVD\'s.  Bonus features on DVD\'s are lame.  I don\'t buy DVD\'s for bonus features.  In fact I avoid them at all costs.  If I have a choice between \"Maximum Overdrive\" and \"Maximum Overdrive: ultra-platinum super sweaty Emilio Estevez edition with 2 more hours of hot gas pumping action and outtakes\" I\'m not sporting the extra 10 bucks to see that hot piece of meat fill more trucks with gas.  I buy a DVD for the movie.  I buy a CD for the music.  All that extra crap is in the way.</p>\r\n<p>The worst thing about it is that some artists are embracing the idea of the dual disc.  Bruce Springsteen\'s newest album is being released exclusively on dual disc.  I\'d like to know if Bruce has really thinks that his aging fan base is going to embrace it along with him.  Besides that fact, what makes Bruce think that he\'s good enough to even try something new like this.  I would expect that this will hurt his sales.   I suppose we will have to wait and see.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=05/04/21/2058212&from=rss\">In other news, big business is trying to take ownership of more information</a>.</p>','Walmart sales figures at DVD players remain the same.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','walmart-sales-figures-at-dvd-players-remain-the-same','','','2005-04-25 12:11:24','2005-04-25 17:11:24','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/walmart-sales-figures-at-dvd-players-remain-the-same/',0,'','',3),
	(116,1,'2005-04-01 00:47:50','2005-04-01 05:47:50','<p>Last week at <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/\">the college</a> we unveiled the redesign that I have been working on for about two months.  The actual aesthetic was designed by an outside consultant.  The purpose of the redesign was to make the site more closely match the printed marketing propaganda that the college gives out.  Its branding, nothing new and I\'m not sure why it hadn\'t been done before. </p>\r\n<p>For Michael and I though the redesign offered us a chance to clean up alot of things that had been irking us for a while.  Here\'s a list of the goals that we made valient efforts to accomplish in this redesign, then I\'ll get to the point of the entry.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eliminate the javascript dropdown menus and replace them with a leaner, meaner web standards based menus.</li>\r\n<li>Simplify the logic in the template helping the page load faster by eliminating steps.</li>\r\n<li>Minimize the page size of the page by cutting images and bloated javascript files.</li>\r\n<li>Recode the site with xhtml and css to make it 508 compliant.</li>\r\n<li>Remove some static html pages and replace them with dynamic database driven pages managed by administrative modules.</li>\r\n<li>Unify identical information in multiple areas to draw from a single source creating more consistent content.</li>\r\n<li>Pay greater attention to semantics in markup by using tags for what they are intended (tables for tabular data, headers for headers, lists for lists) to improve access, searchability and indexing.</li> \r\n</ul>\r\n<p>So thats the short list.  In preparation, we changed about a thousand small things along with spreading content control across the college allowing everyone to maintain their own content. All in all, we cut the load size from nearly 1 meg to around 70k.  A sizable difference.</p>\r\n<h3>Get to the freaking point!</h3>\r\n<p>The graphic design consultant that designed the new site gave us a layered photoshop file with the artsy part of the site.  They failed to address things like links and headers and images.  I was given nearly full freedom to come up with these myself.  After careful consideration I chose the visual styles for the varying elements of the page that you see now. In addition, they didn\'t address the fact that a dark blue background makes for nearly unreadable copy.  This is what led to the severe difference in the appearance of the homepage and the subsequent interior pages.</p>\r\n<h3>Enter the criticism</h3>\r\n<p>Before telling you what our number one criticism was, I will say that even those who gave us this feedback did like the site overall.  The largest majority of the criticism was that the fonts were too large.  The headers of each page in particular.  The copy on the pages is 16 pixels.  Sixth level headers are also 16 pixels although bold.  From there the size climbs 4 pixels each level up.  This puts the second level headers (the pages headlines) at 32 pixels (a far cry from the 50 pixel font I use on veryraw).  My reasoning for selecting such large fonts is rooted in the fact that our institution markets itself to a widely varied age group.  Our 70 year old students may not be able to read the 8 point font that our 18 year old students can. </p>\r\n<p>I received an equal amount of i-can-finally-read-the-sites\'s as I did big-fonts-look-bad.  If I need to choose a camp to appeal to, I will pick the one that benefits based on greater functionality and usability rather than the one that losses based on a matter of personal preference.</p>\r\n<p>For more information on why you shouldn\'t use painfully small fonts, visit the <a href=\"http://usability.gov/guidelines/fonts.html\">US Department for Health and Human Services</a>.</p>\r\n<p>To sum it all up, small fonts suck.  I won\'t try to claim that this is the perfect design.  It\'s far from it.  There are at least 10 problems with the style that I can list off the top of my head which make the site difficult to use.  None of them is the size of the fonts.</p>','Eight point fonts are for losers!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','8-point-fonts-are-for-losers','','','2005-04-01 15:03:21','2005-04-01 20:03:21','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/8-point-fonts-are-for-losers/',0,'','',2),
	(117,1,'2005-04-01 16:32:29','2005-04-01 21:32:29','Okay so I don\'t know if anyone else has this problem.  I spend most of my working hours in command line on our linux servers.  I program directly on the server using <a href=\"http://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/emacs.html\">emacs</a> (yeah thats right I\'m an emacs man). Emacs is text editor (and more) that can be run nearly 100% using keyboard shortcuts.  I\'m a mere novice. Watch Michael in emacs and your head will spin at the rediculous proficiency.  Your all over the place.  <a href=\"http://www.utexas.edu/cc/docs/ccrl34.html\">Look at this list of shortcuts</a>.  I spend so much time in emacs now (40 hours a week) that I have started to try using them in windows.  God thats annoying.','The eternal battle of keyboard shortcuts.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-eternal-battle-of-keyboard-shortcuts','','','2005-04-01 16:32:32','2005-04-01 21:32:32','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/the-eternal-battle-of-keyboard-shortcuts/',0,'','',2),
