	(123,1,'2004-04-26 09:23:05','2004-04-26 14:23:05','<p>So I worked a <a href=\"http://www.fi.edu/tfi/programs/camp-in.html\">Camp-in</a> on Friday night at the Franklin Institute.  Exhausting yet rewarding, the night went really well considering there were 600 campers were seven to twelve years old. Oh yeah and they were all girls. I have this theory that I am purposely put on for these very strenuous nights as some sort of joke. Up until now I couldn\'t say this because the four managers made there own schedules in January. But this Friday\'s campin was given to me by Amy my boss when one of the managers broke his foot in Montreal. I am of the opinion that she gave me this one on purpose. Other than this particular Camp-in I can\'t blame her because, well, I picked the rest. Unless this is some cosmic conspiracy in which some evil diety forced me to choose those particular Camp-ins.</p>\r\n<p>In all seriousness these are the nights that I enjoy the most because the energy in the museum is so high that it makes the hair on your neck stand up. If you could bottle it, third world nations could run for years on a single container. Unfortunately then we would surely be forced to abide by child labor laws, and lets be honest now. Who wants to abide by child labor laws.</p>\r\n<p>The night was boat loads of fun and had one extra added bonus. I rode a <a href=\"http://origin.www.segway.com/segway/specs_iseries.html\">Segway</a>. For those who don\'t know what a Segway is here is an explaination from the <a href=\"http://origin.www.segway.com/\">Segway HT website</a>.</p>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://origin.www.segway.com/segway/introduction.html\">\r\n<p>Segway Human Transporter (HT) can self-balance because of a technology called dynamic stabilization. Dynamic Stabilization works in much the same way your own sense of balance does. Where you have an inner ear, eyes, muscles, and a brain to keep you balanced, the Segway HT has solid-state gyroscopes, tilt sensors, high-speed microprocessors, and powerful electric motors performing to keep it balanced. Working in concert, these extensively tested, redundant systems sense your center of gravity, instantaneously assess the information, and make minute adjustments one hundred times a second. Segway HT balances whether you\'re traveling at 10 mph, carrying a heavy load, slowly maneuvering in tight spaces, or standing perfectly still.</p>\r\n<p>Move forward. Go forward.</p>\r\n<p>The Segway HT intuitively balances the way humans do - moving forward and backward, responding to changes in your body\'s position. There is no accelerator and no brakes. Lean forward and you move forward. Straighten up and you stop. Lean back, and you move back. To turn, rotate the steering grip under your wrist in either direction. Operation is natural, intuitive, and one of the primary reasons Segway HT so seamlessly integrates into enterprise situations, pedestrian environments, and everyday life.</p>\r\n<p><em>source:</em> <a href=\"http://origin.www.segway.com/segway/introduction.html\">Segway | Introduction to Segway HT</a></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>It was the most fun I have had since I learned how to do spin outs on my Knight Rider <a href=\"http://bigwheelrally.home.att.net/obw/originalbigwheel-pg.htm\">big wheel</a> or donuts in my rear wheel drive eight cylinder. It is easily the greatest invention ever. It\'s like walking but not. Mark and I were trained on it by Kerry, all of which are in the pictures below. Thank god for training too cause I would have killed myself on that thing. Mark almost did kill himself when he was leaving the IMAX theater and smacked his head on the doorway on his way out. Thank goodness for helmets I suppose.</p>\r\n<p>In case anyone is feeling especially charitable, I have added a Segway to my <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/registry/1SXUQEDHC006V\">Amazon.com Wishlist</a>.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/segwaytimmy01.jpg\" alt=\"My first Segway ride.\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/segwaytimmycandy.jpg\" alt=\"Candy worrying that I\'ll kill myself and she\'ll have to take over for the night.\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/segwaymarkkerry.jpg\" alt=\"Kerry training Mark on the fashion of bike helmets.\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/segwaymark01.jpg\" alt=\"Mark on the Segway.  Lookin\' suave for all the ladies.\" /></p>\r\n<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/segwaymark02.jpg\" alt=\"Mark from behind.\" /></p>','A big day for dork!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-big-day-for-dork','','','2005-04-07 00:44:44','2005-04-07 05:44:44','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/a-big-day-for-dork/',0,'','',0),
	(124,1,'2004-04-28 17:40:21','2004-04-28 22:40:21','<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12580485/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/12580485_6f83d81b0c.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"94\" alt=\"4monitors\" /></a>\r\n<p>My current monitor count is two at home (19 and 17) and three at work (all 17). I have had up to four at work but the interference was so spectacular that, not only did my face burn when I sat in front of them but they twitched like I was a huge magnet.  I had to get rid of one.</p>','QuadMonitor Shuffle',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','quadmonitor-shuffle','','','2005-05-05 22:24:22','2005-05-06 03:24:22','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/quadmonitor-shuffle/',0,'','',0),
	(125,1,'2005-04-07 23:47:23','2005-04-08 04:47:23','<p>When google released <a href=\"http://maps.google.com/\">google maps</a> I was blown away.  They\'ve recently added high resolution satellite images.  It\'s pretty amazing.</p>\r\n<p>Some folks came up with the idea to do memory maps based on the satellite images from google maps in flickr.  You take a screenshot of the map the upload it to flickr and add notes to tell stories about your neighborhood.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8769296/\">Check out my memory map!</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8769296/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos5.flickr.com/8769296_0deb66eecb.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"327\" alt=\"My neighborhood. Collingdale, PA.\" /></a></p>','Memory Map - Collingdale, PA',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','memory-map-collingdale-pa','','','2005-05-02 21:42:21','2005-05-03 02:42:21','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/memory-map-collingdale-pa/',0,'','',7),
	(134,1,'2005-04-21 00:00:51','2005-04-21 05:00:51','<p>Ever had falafel?  Me either, until a few weeks ago.  Mark, Geoff, Dan and I met Burn at <a href=\"http://www.maoz.nl/about.html\">Moaz Vegetarian</a> on South Street.  It\'s amazing.  I can\'t get enough.  I\'ve been there like 3 times in three weeks and I\'m seriously addicted.  I nearly died the night I went on a bike ride with Dan one night.  I ate two falafels that night.  Then I tried to ride back to the car.   It was seriously like 30 blocks and I thought I would die for sure.  The whole way they were fighting and kicking like I had just eaten a jar of agave worms.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ve heard that there\'s no place like Maoz though for falafel.  If you haven\'t had one before you dont know what you\'re missing.  Check out these falafel pictures, they make it look fucking discusting.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10209866/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/10209866_ba2054153e_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"stuffed falafel\" /></a>  <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10210007/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/10210007_54914209a4_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"the toppings bar\" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10209892/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/10209892_903fa09cfe_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"addictive\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10209954/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/10209954_1b7be378cc_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"mark stuffs\" /></a></p>','That looks disgusting.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','that-looks-disgusting','','','2005-04-21 00:02:49','2005-04-21 05:02:49','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/that-looks-disgusting/',0,'','',3),
	(127,1,'2005-04-12 00:41:56','2005-04-12 05:41:56','<a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/223546/\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/8988845_ee530b0781_m.jpg\" style=\"float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px 0;\" /></a>\r\n<p>Trish and I spent Saturday trekking around New York City. It was a beautiful day and we needed to do something with ourselves rather than sit around all weekend while I wallowed around in the crushing depression that comes along with every birthday.  I turned 25 yesterday and its the first time in as-long-as-I-can-remember years that I didn\'t end up contemplating how to begin my dark memoirs. We saw <a href=\"http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4577331\">William Wallace\'s sword</a>, visited the <a href=\"http://moma.org/\">MoMA</a>, and walked around the city a bunch.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/223546/\">Check out my pictures from the trip on flickr</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Saturday was also my first experience with the <a href=\"http://www.mta.nyc.ny.us/\">New York City subway system</a>.  I was really impressed.  After spending the day traveling on MTA, with great ease, even with my learning curve, for only seven dollars, it was hard to return home to Philadelphia to our beloved El.  I love taking public Transportation.  Until my iPod broke, it was my prefered method of travel every Thursday to get to Temple.  But, New York is now the third city that has left me pondering the same question.  Why do we pay for this? Septa recently tossed around the idea of raising rates again and at the time I was all, \"so what.\" Now I have new feelings on the subject.</p>\r\n<p>In New York, they have clean, well stocked bathrooms.  Philadelphia has Bum piss.  New York has eager, helpful employees.  Philadelphia has sour grapes. New York, Paris and Boston all have expansive underground transportation systems that allow you to get nearly anywhere in the cities that you want to go.  Philadelphia has an ass slow bus system with windows so greasy you can\'t see out of them and piles of chicken bones in the corner.</p>\r\n<p>I like New York.  Third trip there in as many years and everytime I like it more.  MTA gave me one more reason to love New York and one more reason to forswear Philadelphia.  Raise the rates of public transportation? For what?</p>','Why do we pay for this?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','why-do-we-pay-for-this','','','2005-04-12 00:41:59','2005-04-12 05:41:59','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/why-do-we-pay-for-this/',0,'','',8),
	(128,1,'2005-04-12 23:49:53','2005-04-13 04:49:53','<p>In my attempts to pimp <a href=\"http://flickr.com/\">flickr</a> to every person I know, I have been thinking alot about photography and pictures.  One of the realizations I have come to is that I am not a photographer.  I like to take pictures.  I like to look at pictures.  I even like to show my pictures to people.  But I\'m not a photographer.  Although this is sort of a depressing realization for such a total wanna-be, its been sort of liberating.  I shoot and shoot and shoot and no matter how crappy the world may think the images are, I share them anyway.  You figure if I shoot a thousand pictures, eventually one of them has to catch someone\'s eye.</p>\r\n<p>I may not be a photographer, but sometimes an image just needs a little help to become something really cool.  Of course photoshop never hurt no one.  so a little doctoring may be in order.</p>\r\n<p>Below is one of those images.  This is an the Antonov cargo plane that came into Philadelphia International while I was working for USAir.  It was awesome.  Freaking huge.</p>\r\n<p>I removed some of the debris and sharpened the image a bit and I think it improved the image alot.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://veryraw.com/images/antonovedited.jpg\"><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/antonovedited.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://veryraw.com/images/antonovoriginal.jpg\"><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/antonovoriginal.jpg\" /></a></p>','Even a blind squirrel finds a nut once in a while.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','128','','','2005-04-12 23:50:55','2005-04-13 04:50:55','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/128/',0,'','',0),
	(129,1,'2005-04-14 19:06:00','2005-04-15 00:06:00','<p>A few days ago <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/why-do-we-pay-for-this/\">I sang the praise of the MTA and their spectatular subway system</a>.  Then I read a post on slashdot that says <a href=\"http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=05/04/12/0313204&tid=126\">MTA is adding another line which will be computerized</a>.  So let me get this straight, they are taking actions that could help keep costs down by adding lines that won\'t require as much staff to control <strong>and</strong> they are planning on computerizing more?  Amazing.  Wonder why Septa isn\'t doing that.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/why-do-we-pay-for-this/#comment-641\">Geoff brought up a great point</a> in saying that the employees are partially to blame for their lack of willingness to share the costs of healthcare.  But even better was his mentioning the misappropriation of funds.</p>\r\n<p>I was at the Wawa the other day after work and one of the guys up there told us that the Market Frankford El reconstruction project is going to take longer because they fired one of the contractors after they poured pillars that didn\'t withstand stress tests.  The other issue with the pillars they poured is that some of them are not just off by a few inches, they are off by feet.  This means that they will have to tear them down and repour them.  It\'s already taken too long, how much longer will this add?  an extra year. <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/mld/dailynews/news/local/11171252.htm\">Amazing!</a>  Scroll down to get the part about the El.</p>','Misappropriation and Public Transport.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','misappropriation-and-public-transport','','','2005-04-14 19:06:23','2005-04-15 00:06:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/misappropriation-and-public-transport/',0,'','',0),
	(130,1,'2005-04-16 13:08:58','2005-04-16 18:08:58','<p>A little over a month ago <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/more-on-social-bookmarks-an-application/\">I wrote about how Mark finally understood the benefits to del.icio.us</a>.  I had a similar problem with RSS.  I knew it was cool to have it but I really didn\'t understand why.  Apparently, I\'m <a href=\"http://37signals.com/svn/archives2/finally_getting_it.php\">not the only one</a>. Over the past few months, the amount of time I devoted to reading sites on tons of different subjects has grown longer and longer.  Most of this time can be attributed to just opening all of those sites up to find that they hadn\'t updated.</p>\r\n<p>I had been reading about different RSS readers, and asked Don a bunch of questions about how he uses RSS, and decided to give it a try.  I downloaded <a href=\"http://sage.mozdev.org/\">Sage</a>, loaded up all of my sites, and added their feeds.  After using it for about a week, I finally get it.  My time reading sites has been cut in half.  Not only that but I have added more sites without an increase in time.  I only load the sites that have been updated and don\'t waste time anymore.  This gave me the ability to remove the list from my site and widen the column and include more flickr images. Life is good.</p>\r\n<p>So if you notice at the top of the page I have added a <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/timmyfury\">syndicate</a> link.  I am experimenting with <a href=\"http://feedburner.com/\">feedburner</a>. It\'s a site that allows you to combine feeds from many sources to make one super awesome mega-feed.  If you are subscribed to my old feed, that will remain.  This new feed includes my del.icio.us links and my flickr images.  It\'s the total veryraw experience without hitting my site.</p>','Damn! I finally get it!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','i-finally-get-it','','','2005-04-16 13:17:52','2005-04-16 18:17:52','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/damn-i-finally-get-it/',0,'','',1),
	(131,1,'2005-04-18 23:28:32','2005-04-19 04:28:32','<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/9864643/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/9864643_f9319e25ed_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"164\" alt=\"My rubber face\" style=\"float: left;padding:0 10px 5px 0;\"/></a>\r\n<p>Okay(breath), anyone who has talked to me over the last month has been assaulted with talk about how amazing <a href=\"http://flickr.com\">flickr</a> is.  Well I haven\'t been able to sleep for a few nights because of the sheer amount of descriptive data that is attached to each photo.  I lay awake at night thinking about the possibilities this could have.  There are already applications that have been developed using flickr\'s API to do pretty cool things.  <a href=\"http://mappr.com/\">Mappr</a> is just one.  I theorize that at some point you will be able to order images and albums and posters and all sorts of things from flickr from the images you upload.</p>\r\n<p>So anyway, the reason I bore you all with another entry about my latest obsession is that I received an email from flickr and they have decided to reward those of us that signed up for pro accounts early.  My one year has been turned into two years.  My 1gb upload per month is now 2gb per month. <strong>and to top it off</strong>, as if it could get any better, in the next few days I will have two accounts to give to two lucky friends for free.  <strong>Two freaking free pro accounts.</strong> I am beside myself.  Freaking amazing.  I don\'t think I\'ll ever sleep again. This is too damn exciting.</p>','Oh my freaking hell!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','oh-my-freaking-hell','','','2005-04-18 23:33:23','2005-04-19 04:33:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/oh-my-freaking-hell/',0,'','',1),
	(132,1,'2005-06-10 10:25:16','2005-06-10 15:25:16','<p>For Christmas, my parents bought me a wireless keyboard and mouse.  Its awesome.  I have loved every minute with it. It makes it easier to keep my desk clear and lets me site nearly anyway I want in my room without being held back by my cables.  I digress.   The keyboard also has all these extra buttons to bring up email, messaging, control music.  There are five extra buttons on the left hand side of the keyboard.  They are able to be assigned to do anything you want them to do.  I have chosen to make them my sound buttons.  Using sounds from <a href=\"http://www.a1freesoundeffects.com/\">a1 free sound effects</a> I have assigned them to play a different sound each when I press them.  This comes in handy in conversations while I\'m at my computer.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>donkey</li>\r\n<li>canned laughter</li>\r\n<li>puke</li>\r\n<li>fart</li>\r\n<li>fog horn</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n','I have five extra buttons!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','i-have-five-extra-buttons','','','2006-02-15 09:25:42','2006-02-15 14:25:42','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/sounds/',0,'','',3),
	(133,1,'2005-04-19 22:40:52','2005-04-20 03:40:52','<p>I used to write my own blogging software.  After about two years, i got really burned out, mostly because there\'s only so much that I can do with the blog idea.  There are only so many things you can add.  In addition, I ended up spending all of my time on that and not as much on things that I really wanted to.  This is when and partially why I switched to wordpress.</p> \r\n<p>In the working world, you are constantly faced with the decision to build or buy.  There are alot of things to take into consideration when you are mulling over this decision (time, money, resources, urgency).  More often than not, unless you are working for a development firm or at a place with an extensive development team there is a good chance you are going to end up making the decision to buy.  If not for the reasons listed above, simply because you can purchase support and upgrades and increased functionality are added for you with little time.  Plus there is likely going to be a large community already using the software.  In other words, why reinvent the wheel?</p>\r\n<p>We have been discussing build or buy alot in my information systems class and we run into this issue at <a href=\"http://dccc.edu\">the college</a> alot.  Not only do we maintain the main website but we have also started to get involved in other business functions of the school.  We are at the beginning stages but there have already been several times when we needed to make the decision to build a system or buy a system.  It\'s about 50% build and 50% buy.</p>\r\n<p>My point here is this, the chances that you are going to buy software rather than build it is significant.  The ability to examine a system, figure out how it works, is a very important skill.  Anyone can build their own application from scratch.  Most people can even build a good application from scratch.  But when you walk into a place and you have to sit down at another person\'s code, the better you are at figuring out what is going on, the more valuable you will be. I\'m not saying its fun, I\'m just saying its a necessary skill.</p>','Build or buy?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','writing-your-own-cms','','','2005-04-19 22:41:14','2005-04-20 03:41:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/writing-your-own-cms/',0,'','',0),
	(136,1,'2005-06-07 11:12:05','2005-06-07 16:12:05','<p>Two months ago I wrote <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/but-google/\">But Google, we had such a good thing going!</a>.  I had been experimenting with 43 things the goal tracking site.  After about two weeks my ranking for google\'s favorite Timothy Crowe had disappear.  Veryraw was replaced with my 43 things page.  What a crock.  Not only that but my listing for veryraw had completely been removed.</p>\r\n<p>So after realizing that 43things was less about keeping track of goals and more about keeping track of failures, I deleted my account.  One week later I had returned to the top of the google rankings for Timothy Crowe.  It just goes to show the power of a site like 43things.  The entire site is made of of interlinking pages.  When google hit it, it found a way to get to my profile on thousands of pages.  Causing 43things to reference my name an immense amount of times and take over my spot.</p>\r\n<h3>Why does this matter</h3>\r\n<p>As I\'ve said before, the internet is what a good portion of my life is based on.   My income depends on it.  Someday I will go out looking for a new job and they will want to know what I\'ve done.  It would be great to be able to google my name and have my own site come up.  It would be great to show that I have been in the presence of the internet for long enough that I own my own name.</p>\r\n<p>It\'s the focus of a New York Times article<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/02/fashion/thursdaystyles/02GOOGLE.html?ei=5094&en=46d691e7971b0c87&hp=&ex=1117684800&adxnnl=1&partner=homepage&pagewanted=all&adxnnlx=1117674001-Eak8/V2%204BSLvGFbLAzCQQ&oref=login\"> , Loosing Google\'s Lock on the Past</a> (one that features <a href=\"http://www.dashes.com/anil/2005/06/02/defining_ones_\">a hilarious image of Anil Dash wearing the goatse tshirt</a>).  In the future details of everyone will be available on the internet and as Anil said in his article, <a href=\"http://www.dashes.com/anil/2002/12/17/privacy_through\">privacy through identity control</a>, the best way to ensure that the correct information about you is on the internet is to put it there yourself.</p>\r\n<p>I have spent alot of time over the last two year building an online persona and the day that my 43 things profile took over that spot I though that all my work had been poured down the drain.  Glad to see I\'m back on top.</p>\r\n<p><em>Slightly related and sort of interesting is that when you do a search for my name the article about google ditching veryraw comes up second to my site.  <a href=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/17215358_adf554fc4f_o.jpg\" title=\"Photo Sharing\">I\'ve saved a screenshot of it for prosperity sake</a>.</em></p>','Google and I are back on good terms.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','update-on-43things-and-google','','','2005-06-10 10:23:50','2005-06-10 15:23:50','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/update-on-43things-and-google/',0,'','',0),
