	(141,1,'2005-05-02 13:57:51','2005-05-02 18:57:51','<p>To follow up that entry which was horribly boring, I would like to offer a peace offering.</p>\r\n<p>If you could have any super power, what would it be?  Here are mine.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Background music and sound effects</strong> - No matter what I was doing everyone would hear music that matched the mood and sound effects that made everything I did more emphatic.  No one would be able to react to them (ie dancing or looking around trying to figure out where it was coming from) it would just be there.  Only for me.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Spit bees</strong> - I would open my mouth and bees would fly out with the pressure of a fire hose.  I would be immune but everyone would be subjected to the horror of my mouth bees.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>What are yours?</p>','My super dad could beat up your super dad!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','my-super-dad-could-beat-up-your-super-dad','','','2006-02-15 09:29:23','2006-02-15 14:29:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/my-super-dad-could-beat-up-your-super-dad/',0,'','',3),
	(142,1,'2004-07-19 21:53:18','2004-07-20 02:53:18','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12068348/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos11.flickr.com/12068348_d4a908b774_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"83\" alt=\"scream\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>I made this a few month\'s ago as part of a design I was working on. I have since abandoned that design but the graphic remains.  I like it alot and I thought I would share it with you after reading <a href=\"http://weblog.trivolt.com\">Brian\'s</a> friend Rob\'s blog last night and he did <a href=\"http://obnoxio.us/archives/2004/07/clones.php\">an entry with a collage</a> he did. I still may use it in the redesign I am currently working on but we will have to see how it fits.</p>\r\n<p>These are two pictures of me taken on the same day when I was a child.  I meshed them together to make them look like one and the girl in the background is my sister Marisa.  Although I removed alot of things from these images, I thought it would be appropriate to leave her in. I am calling this one \"The monster is us all.\"</p>','The monster in us all',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','monster-in-us-all','','','2005-05-02 21:06:04','2005-05-03 02:06:04','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-monster-in-us-all/',0,'','',0),
	(143,1,'2004-07-16 10:08:23','2004-07-16 15:08:23','<p>In the photography section of <a href=\"http://www.bordersstores.com/\">Borders</a> you can look at as many <a href=\"http://www.anseladams.com/\">Ansel Adams</a> books as you want, but as soon as you pick up that copy of <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/3936709033/qid=1089986588/sr=2-1/ref=sr_2_1/102-2709788-4295326\"> \r\nNaked Happy People</a>, everyone looks at you like you\'re a fucking pervert.</p>','What a double standard.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','what-a-double-standard','','','2005-05-02 21:08:49','2005-05-03 02:08:49','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/what-a-double-standard/',0,'','',0),
	(144,1,'2004-07-26 00:00:40','2004-07-26 05:00:40','<p>I\'m stting here reading &quot;Stiff&quot; by Mary Roach. An excellent book I must say. It reads like a dream and it makes me laugh and yearn to read on. The point is though that I am enjoying reading it. </p>\r\n<p>I haven\'t really been enjoying my blog. It\'s disjointed and I\'ve out grown my current design. Furthermore I haven\'t created a single design of which I like. I am uninspired. There are some features I want to add. There are some books that I want to read. There are some classes I want to pass. There\'s some life I would like to enjoy. None of which I am currently doing. This isn\'t because of the blog. There are several factors. But the blog is back there somewhere. </p>\r\n<p>So I am going to stop blogging for a little while. Maybe a week. Maybe a month. Shouldn\'t be too much longer than that. I\'ll let you know when I have a better Idea for myself. Thanks for reading. I hope I don\'t lose you between now and then. </p>\r\n<p>If you want to contact me, you should email me. See you shortly.</p>','timmyfury.com will return after these messages',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','timmyfurycom-will-return-after-these-messages','','','2005-05-02 21:11:27','2005-05-03 02:11:27','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/timmyfurycom-will-return-after-these-messages/',0,'','',0),
	(145,1,'2004-07-14 21:06:39','2004-07-15 02:06:39','<a style=\"padding: 0pt 5px 5px 0pt; float: left\" title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12070038/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"221\" alt=\"smellyhat\" src=\"http://photos8.flickr.com/12070038_f5fbe2479e_m.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\nYou\'ve been to alot of places with me. Munich, Paris, Venice and Boston. You were there with me in Texas three times. We\'ve had such good times. I consider you one of my best friends, nay, a brother. Who else would hold my hair all those times I puked out back of The Fort in Upper Darby.\r\n\r\nYou have served me well through the years. I remember the day when I bought you for three dollars at the I. Goldberg \"Going Out of Business Blowout\". What an exciting day that was. And now, four years later, your brim is tattered and your middle is saggy, but I see the way those other guys look at you with longing when they walk past wearing their \"pre-worn\" Abercrombie and Fitch hats. You may smell of petroleum and sweat. Your elastic band may be loose and you may not even really fit my head anymore, but I love you smelly hat and I look forward to many more years together.','Ode to Smelly Hat',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','ode-to-smelly-hat','','','2006-02-15 09:49:17','2006-02-15 14:49:17','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/ode-to-smelly-hat/',0,'','',0),
	(146,1,'2004-07-11 21:06:35','2004-07-12 02:06:35','<p>I have been agonizing over how to complete this illustration for months. Literally months. I added the line for the ground today. I think its done. I call it <strong>&quot;Broken Hearts Never Lie.&quot;</strong></p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12070841/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/12070841_c234b2f911_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"88\" alt=\"Broken Hearts Never Lie\" /></a>','Broken Hearts Never Lie',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','broken-hearts-never-lie','','','2005-05-02 21:23:50','2005-05-03 02:23:50','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/broken-hearts-never-lie/',0,'','',0),
	(147,1,'2005-05-04 07:13:05','2005-05-04 12:13:05','<p>Everytime I work an overnight at The Franklin Institute, after we get all the kids in bed, I take the main elevators down to the basement, walk through the program support shop and through the halls to the staff lounge where I keep my sleeping bag while I\'m working.  The museum is quiet.  The whole building is asleep save a few employees.  There isn\'t a soul around.  As I round the corner from the elevators I am startled by a very large black man standing in the shop.  It happens every single time.   Without fail this man will scare me.</p>\r\n<p>Who is he?  Its Tra Thomas of the Philadelphia Eagles.  At least it\'s a plastic likeness of him.  It used to reside on the third floor in the Sports challenge exhibit.  He used to hold a large cooler of gatorade in eternal plastic pour.  As you can see in the picture below the cooler has been removed and he has been tied to the pillar to keep him from tipping over while he\'s off of his stand.</p>\r\n<p>As I round the corner.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/11619163/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos8.flickr.com/11619163_cb6d56305c.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"Scary black man.\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>A closer look.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/11619256/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/11619256_89f11bebb9.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"A plastic Tra Thomas\" /></a></p>','Scary Black Man',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','scary-black-man','','','2005-05-04 07:15:48','2005-05-04 12:15:48','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/scary-black-man/',0,'','',3),
	(148,1,'2004-05-09 16:23:54','2004-05-09 21:23:54','<p>I was in Wawa this morning getting a cup of coffee.  A woman is standing at the coffee pots when I walk up to them and she asks the girl walking by behind the counter if she can get one of the fresh pots.  The girl starts in on this tyrade about how drinking coffee causes stomach cancer and how we shouldn\'t drink alot of coffee.  The woman who asked for the pot turns and looks at me.I took this to mean that I should speak up.</p>\r\n<p>I thought perhaps a proper thing to do was run down a list of the things in my life which could cause cancer.  Here is a list of causes and possible cancer types.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>smoking -> lung cancer.</li>\r\n<li>sitting in front of computer monitors -> face cancer.</li>\r\n<li>breathing -> lung cancer.</li>\r\n<li>going outside -> skin cancer.</li>\r\n<li>wearing deoderant -> armpit cancer.</li>\r\n<li>brushing my teeth -> tooth cancer.</li>\r\n<li>handling money -> wallet cancer.</li>\r\n<li>drinking beer -> stomach cancer.</li>\r\n<li>eating cheesesteaks -> stomach cancer.</li>\r\n<li>talking on a cell phone -> ear cancer.</li>\r\n<li>eating corn on the cob -> bowel cancer.</li>\r\n<li>shitting -> prostate cancer.</li>\r\n<li>watching TV -> eye cancer.</li>\r\n<li>walking -> foot cancer.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>I think worst of all would be the brain cancer that I will someday develope from hearing annoying bitches nag me about getting cancer.  Everything causes cancer.  Get over it. It\'s the way all the cool kids are dying these days.  Get with the freakin\' times already.</p>\r\n<p>Actually I didn\'t say all of that.  What happened was the woman looked at me and I was like, \"Shut up and get us some fresh coffee.\"</p>','Coffee-making Evangelist',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','coffee-making-evangelist','','','2005-05-03 07:41:30','2005-05-03 12:41:30','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/coffee-making-evangelist/',0,'','',0),
	(149,1,'2004-05-10 17:23:32','2004-05-10 22:23:32','I was working with one of the librarians at work this afternoon and I made a comment about how coffee rules my life.  She responded with a joke about a coffee enema.  Although she is into wholistic medicine she does not participate in such a thing.  I did some research.\r\n\r\nI have been interested in the whole concept of a daily enema and fasting regiment since I heard a piece on NPR about a guy who did it to see if fasting caused enlightenment. Regardless of whether I would ever do it or not, I think its interesting.\r\n\r\nHere\'s my favorite part from this website that I selected among the 7,000 some odd <a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=coffee+enema\">results on google</a>. I chose to read <a href=\"http://www.ineedcoffee.com/\">INeedCoffee.com\'s</a> information.\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://www.ineedcoffee.com/01/01/enema/\">The effects of a coffee enema are different than a saline enema. The most important difference between a saline enema and a coffee enema is the presence of caffeine in the coffee. Caffeine, theophylline and theobromine, combine to stimulate the relaxation of smooth muscles causing dilatation of blood vessels and bile ducts. The effects of having a coffee enema are not the same as drinking coffee. The veins of the anus are very close to the surface of the tissue. The caffeine is therefore absorbed more quickly (and in higher concentration) than it is in when coffee is drunk.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.ineedcoffee.com/01/01/enema/\">Coffee Enema (INeedCoffee.com)</a></blockquote>\r\nThis just may be what I am looking for.  An enema regiment which would clean me out and wake me up every morning.','This coffee tastes like shit!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','this-coffee-tastes-like-shit','','','2006-02-15 09:47:10','2006-02-15 14:47:10','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/this-coffee-tastes-like-shit/',0,'','',0),
	(150,1,'2004-06-08 08:16:24','2004-06-08 13:16:24','<p>I went out the other day and bought the new <a href=\"http://www.djdieselboy.com/\">Dieselboy</a> cd. It\'s called &quot;<a href=\"http://www.gracenote.com/xm/pcd/genelect/7c0cc849f2c59d0d97e89c94dab8cd15.html\">The \r\nDungeonmaster\'s Guide</a>,&quot; which we all assumed was a reference to <a href=\"http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/welcome\">Dungeons and Dragons</a>. Our theory was proven true when we read the insert to the cd.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The aesthetic for this CD is based on a love I have for a classic fantasy roleplaying game called \'Dungeons and Dragons\'. I want to use this small space to give proper respect to the friends who joined me on numerous late night \'junk food and jolt cola\' - fueled gaming sessions over ther years. 1981 - 1987: [a list of names I don\'t feel like typing] . 1987 - 1992: [another list which I don\'t feel like typing]. Thank you guys, I will always cherish the memories. Arctic Whitemace lives on!</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>He also goes on and on about how <acronym title=\"Dungeon Master\">DM</acronym>\'s are so talented and how they are so great and how they work so hard. Mark\'s theory is that he is just fishing for a game. He\'s kissing the DM\'s of the world\'s asses to get them to invite him to the game. Good theory. But either way it\'s great to see that all the fame that he has gotten from his mad <acronym title=\"Drum and Bass\">D&amp;B</acronym> spinning skills hasn\'t gone to his head and that his dork roots remain intact. Good man.</p>\r\n<p>On a slightly seperate note and the album is amazing. It is right up there with Dieselboy\'s &quot;<a href=\"http://www.gracenote.com/xm/pcd/drumnbassjungle/fde7fae4b1e3725b8c2ad37e2e0ad9b8.html\">The 6ixth Session</a>. &quot; Hopefully this one won\'t suffer the same fate as &quot;The 6ixth Session.&quot; I have to date owned four seperate copies of that particular album and lent each one to different people and have never gotten back.</p>\r\n<p>Go buy it. It\'s worth the money. It\'s freaking amazing.</p>','Dungeon Master',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','dungeon-master','','','2005-05-03 07:48:14','2005-05-03 12:48:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/150/',0,'','',0),
	(151,1,'2004-03-30 16:05:38','2004-03-30 21:05:38','<p><strong>the query</strong></p>\r\n<p>I was at Trish\'s one morning reading the back of a box of <a href=\"http://www.cheerios.com/about/berryburst.asp\">Cheerios Berry Burst</a> with Strawberries and Bananas and there was a fact that I found relatively amazing.</p>\r\n<blockquote>The average American eats about 28 pounds of bananas per years</blockquote>\r\n<p>Good lord man! 28 pounds is a huge amount of bananas. I couldn\'t get over it. \"Thats too much,\" I say. So after about a week of babbling endlessly about how I couldn\'t get over how much 28 pounds of bananas was, I decided to take the scientific approach. So follow with me now. I will try to do this in a logical order.</p>\r\n<p><strong>the methods</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Bananas at <a href=\"http://www.wawa.com/\">WAWA</a> cost 79 cents a pound.</li>\r\n<li>For five days I bought a banana at WAWA. The prices of these bananas 28 cents, 24 cents, 26 cents, 29 cents and 24 cents. For an average of 26.2 cents per banana</li>\r\n<li>Therefore I conclude that one banana is approxiamately a third of a pound.  (79 cents divided by 3 bananas equals 26.3333 cents per banana.)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>the findings</strong></p>\r\n<p>My findings were surprising. At 3 bananas per pound, you would only have to eat 84 bananas in one year.  Thats only 1 banana every 4.34 days or 1.6 bananas per week.  Thats only 7 bananas per month.  Thats amazing.</p>\r\n<p>In fact, if you are a 1 banana a day person, in other words you eat 365 bananas per year, you don\'t consume 28 pounds of bananas per year.  You consume 121.6 pounds of bananas per year.  Dear lord.</p>','Bananas: an unofficial study',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','bananas-an-unofficial-study','','','2006-02-15 09:08:22','2006-02-15 14:08:22','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/bananas-an-unofficial-study/',0,'','',0),
	(152,1,'2005-05-05 05:59:09','2005-05-05 10:59:09','<p>Stop saying that.  It\'s 2005, not 1994. For god\'s sake, its the internet. Oh, and while I\'m at it stop saying \"computer guy.\"  I don\'t walk into a hospital and call everyone working there the \"body guy\" do I?  There\'s a big difference between my job and Mark\'s job and Burn\'s job and Don\'s job.  I am a web developer, Burn is a <del>java developer</del> software developer, Mark is a <del>systems admin</del> systems admin and Don is a <del>Network admin</del>  multi-system administrator / technology integrator / slavelaborer / project manager.  There\'s a difference and none of them are simple enough to be broken down to \"computer guy.\"  If you can\'t understand the differences, sign off of AOL, unplug your computer and return it to Walmart.  </p>','Information superhighway',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','information-superhighway','','','2005-05-06 13:36:29','2005-05-06 18:36:29','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/information-superhighway/',0,'','',5),
	(153,1,'2003-10-10 00:00:40','2003-10-10 05:00:40','<p>I\'ve been following the Democratic presidential primary relatively closely this year.  It\'s sort of important considering the winner of that race will be the only chance we have of removing a man from office who last week I heard say, \"The Israeli\'s must do everything in their power to defend themselves against suiciders.\"  Yes you read right suiciders.  Regardless, I was elated when Wesley Clark joined the race.  His politics are relatively unscathed and his opinions match mine about as closely as one could hope.  And in my opinion he\'s already won the race just because all the other candidates have started ripping him.  As for the other candidates\"; well let\'s just have the inauguration for Bush right now so he can finish fucking the world\'s ass and we don\'t have to deal with an entire year of mudslinging and bullshit promises (which I must say anyone who thinks that the things that are said in a campaign should actually be counted on are fucking drunk).</p>\r\n<p>Howard Dean, the former front runner reminds me of a mix between Al Gore and Deputy Dog.</p>\r\n<p>Clark, Dean and Lieberman are the only three that have a chance so they are the only three that I really pay attention to.  I must say though that Al Sharpton hasn\'t a chance.  He\'s a Reverend and an idiot.  But if he could get like 75% of the black population to vote He may actually win.  Fat chance though.  In the <a href=\"http://www.census.gov/prod/3/98pubs/p20-504.pdf\">1996 Election only 50.6% of the black population voted.</a>  Good luck with the primary.  Ambassador Carol Moseley Braun has good politics and she\'s very intelligent and I firmly believe that she would have the country\'s best interests in mind.  Here\'s the thing though; black and female.</p>','the Burning Bush',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-burning-bush','','','2005-05-10 07:34:43','2005-05-10 12:34:43','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-burning-bush/',0,'','',0),
	(154,1,'2003-10-29 00:00:29','2003-10-29 05:00:29','<p>So I was listening to the radio the other day and the commentator said, \"Something-something-something-burgled-something-something.\"  Burgle being the act of a burglar.  What the hell kind of word is that really.  I mean do you really think you would be able to take a police officer seriously if you came home, saw a bunch of police action out front of your house and then the officer says, \"Ma\'am or Sir, your house has been burgled.\"  Really now.</p>\r\n<p>This leads me to a theory that I have.  Perhaps if we renamed all the crimes in the world with silly names, they wouldn&#8217;t seem so terrible.  We could call rape snorklebonking.</p>','renaming crimes makes PC queers like rape',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','renaming-crimes','','','2006-04-14 11:34:35','2006-04-14 16:34:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/renaming-crimes-makes-pc-queers-like-rape/',0,'','',0),
	(155,1,'2003-11-06 08:26:19','2003-11-06 13:26:19','<p>I heard the greatest quote on NPR last night on my drive home.  \"In most cases, when I murdered these women, I did not know their names. Most of the time, I killed them the first time I met them. I do not have a good memory for their faces. I killed so many women; I have a hard time keeping them straight.\"  This is Gary Leon Ridgeway, the Green River Killer.  Fucking amazing.  He looks like a fucking psycho.  His neighbors were like, \"He seemed so normal.\"  My fucking ass.  If you look at the guy you can see he\'s not normal and if you say that\'s normal then, you\'ve got a really skewed sense of normal.  Here\'s a new state motto for Washington, Washington State: <a href=\"http://images.google.com/images?hl=en&lr=&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&q=Gary+Ridgway\">Where this is normal</a>.</p>\r\n<p>I am thinking about joining some sort of organization that encourages voting.  Bush needs to be removed from office next year.  It\'s important.  He just signed into law a bill that makes partial birth abortion illegal.  I think that\'s fucked up.  Honestly it\'s not even a matter of pro-life or pro-choice.  There are so many other issues wrapped up in that one law.  First and foremost is the right to choose.  I mean I\'m all for keeping it in your pants or wearing protection but these are the same conservative retards that oppose condom distribution in schools.  I\'m not saying that I think abortion is right, I\'m just saying that you should have the choice of whether or not to ruin your life.</p>\r\n<p>In addition, When Bush signed the bill the other day, his statement was, \"For years, a terrible form of violence has been directed against children who are inches from birth while the law looked the other way, today at last the American people and our government have confronted the violence and come to the defense of the innocent child\"; This right to life cannot be granted or denied by government, because it does not come from government -- it comes from the creator of life.\"  You fucking oil sniffing terrorist.  You have gone so far right that you have fallen off the plane.  The creator of life?  Yes.  The creator of life.  The mother and father happen to hold that title last time I checked.  And second of all you are fucking contradicting yourself.  You just signed a bill that does give life. Then you say it can\'t be granted by government?</p>','Abortion is right... I mean... A right.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','abortion-is-right-i-mean-a-right','','','2005-05-10 07:40:01','2005-05-10 12:40:01','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/abortion-is-right-i-mean-a-right/',0,'','',0),
	(156,1,'2004-05-18 12:45:46','2004-05-18 17:45:46','<p>I think I need to lighten the mood a bit after two relatively dorky updates.  So I will give you all, what seems to be becoming, your weekly <a href=\"http://www.wawa.com/\">Wawa</a> update.</p>\r\n<p>We were at <a href=\"http://www.wawa.com/storelocator/storeloc-results.asp?StoreNumber=293\">our Wawa</a> the other night and the night manager says to Mark that she thought someone was going to leave without paying for gas.  Mark heroically bounds out the door for pump 11.  As the woman gets in her car Mark throws himself in front of the car.  She screams, \"Get the fuck out the way,\" and tries to leave.  Mark doesn\'t budge.  Mom, the manager walks out and says, \"You didn\'t pay for yourgas.\"  What an amazing and selfless act.</p>\r\n<p>Later that night after a trip to Borders we wen back for a nightcap and there was a woman broken down at the pump.  Mom again calls on us and we get her out of there with a jump.  The woman must have been terrified though.  Three relatively large men walking to her car with a middle aged Lebonese fellow.  Tony made her cry I think.  We got free coffee.</p>\r\n<p>I have been talking to Larry Fish of the Philadelphia Inquirer about my obsession with Wawa.  It\'s sort of like therapy.  He\'s writing about Wawa.  I told him about the Wawa 500 and he was excited.  So looks like we will have to amass a list of Wawa\'s.  They wouldn\'t give me one but I found a way to get one myself from the website.  I\'ll get back to you on that one.  Now all we need is for Code to come home from Qatar.  If you see this code give us an update and we will get the plans going.</p>','Wawa heroism',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','wawa-heroism','','','2005-05-10 07:42:28','2005-05-10 12:42:28','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/wawa-heroism/',0,'','',0),
	(157,1,'2004-05-15 12:25:32','2004-05-15 17:25:32','<p>Recently Drew at <a href=\"http://www.allinthehead.com\">all in the &lt;head&gt;</a> wrote about his ipod \r\nand a concept that I think is relatively awesome.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Everywhere you go, you always take the weather with you &#8211; according to Crowded House at least. I don&#8217;t know about you, but I associate different types of music with different weather conditions. I noticed this particularly the other day when driving along listening to my <a href=\"http://www.apple.com/ipod/\"  title=\"Apple digital music player\">iPod</a> in the car. It was a really bright sunny morning, and each song selected by the iPod&#8217;s shuffle-play seemed to fit perfectly. Chirpy, upbeat music for a chirpy, upbeat morning.</p>\r\n<p>This got me thinking &#8211; if I could categorise each song in my music collection with a weather type, all iTunes would need to do is grab a local weather feed in XML from <a href=\"http://www.weather.com/\">weather.com</a> (just like <a href=\"http://www.1976design.com/blog/\"  title=\"1976design.com\">Dunstan</a> does) &#8211; and a customised playlist could be constructed to match the conditions outside.</p>\r\n<p><em>source: <a href=\"http://www.allinthehead.com/retro/208/take-the-weather-with-you\">Take the Weather With You</a></em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Although I find the concept interesting I don\'t know if I would use this.  I mean its interesting and it certainly presents a challenge from a strictly programmatic point of view but I had another idea which I have thought about for a while. I think adding catagories based on <strong>mood</strong> would be a more appropriate way of going about catagorizing music.  Then when you pick up your iPod or sit down at your computer, you could just pick a mood and the computer would assemble a playlist for you.  Songs could fall into multiple mood categories.Would save alot of time and avoid you the annoyance of assembling a playlist everytime you sit down.  The problem of course is, as Drew mentions, categorizing 40gig of mp3 is a torture which no man should ever endure.</p>\r\n<p>For a long time I have been thinking about how to approach this task.  In the hayday of download, when the cup of <a href=\"http://www.napster.com/\">Napster</a> runneth over and <a href=\"http://www.audiogalaxy.com/\">Audio Galaxy</a> was as extensive as the Milky Way, I used to scrap all of the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metadata\">metadata</a> attached to the songs which I downloaded.  Had I just tagged these songs properly when I downloaded them I may not be in the situation I am now.  Many gigs later I finally found the program to accomplish this goal.</p>\r\n<p>Call me <a href=\"http://www.pantheon.org/articles/s/sisyphus.html\">Sisyphus</a>.  I have been working now for almost two months.  I am now using MusicBrainz meta-tagger to properly tag my large collection of mp3 which Mark fondly named <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/things/alexandria/\">The Alexandria project</a> (after the <a href=\"http://www.bede.org.uk/library.htm\">Great Library of Alexandria</a>), aka Operation Jail Time, In which we rip our Cd\'s (using <a href=\"http://www.mp3-converter.biz/buzzsaw-cd-ripper/\">Buzzsaw</a>).</p>\r\n<p>Although this has taken an egregious amount of time, I suspect that the mood tagging would not take nearly as long since there is no research involved, it is merely personal opinion.</p>\r\n<p>All this being said, I will go home and pack my bag and wait for the RIAA to come and get me.</p>','Operation Jail Time',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','157','','','2005-05-10 07:46:06','2005-05-10 12:46:06','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/157/',0,'','',0),
	(158,1,'2004-06-30 09:22:46','2004-06-30 14:22:46','<p>About three weeks ago I was on my way to work from Trish\'s house and the sun was sort of covered with clouds. It was covered enough that it wasn\'t blinding but I could still see it pretty clearly when I looked at it. In the bottom right side of the sun <a href=\"http://analyzer.depaul.edu/paperplate/Transit%20of%20Venus/sohomdi.jpg\">there was a black dot</a> that was just about to disappear from the face of the sun. Later I was reading the <a href=\"http://www.google.com/googleblog/2004/06/oodles-of-doodles.html\">Google blog</a> (which on a completely separate note I feel they should be calling &quot;The Bloogle&quot;) from the guy who does all the <a href=\"http://www.google.com/holidaylogos.html\">holiday Google logo\'s</a>. There was a logo where one of the o\'s was replaced with a sun with a black dot in front of it similar to the way I had seen the sun earlier in the morning. </p>\r\n<p>Based on <a href=\"http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/transit/venus/city04-2.html\">this time table</a> in comparison to where I was when I saw what I thought I saw, it turns out that I saw the <a href=\"http://www.transitofvenus.org/\">transit of Venus</a>. The phenomenon only happens once every 122 years or so and I actually got to see it. The transit of Venus is almost like an eclipse. <a href=\"http://www.transitofvenus.org/faq.htm#what\">It happens when</a> Venus moves across the disk of the sun showing a black dot in front of the sun. I suppose I shouldn\'t have been staring at the sun. You can keep up to date with solar phenomenon at <a href=\"http://www.spaceweather.com/\">spaceweather.com</a> and <a href=\"http://www.transitofvenus.org/safety.htm\">make yourself a safe viewing device</a> (or <a href=\"http://skyandtelescope.com/observing/objects/sun/article_101_1.asp\">buy one</a>) so you can view said phenomenon.</p>\r\n<p>Also very exciting is the Cassini spacecraft which has been heading for Saturn for about seven years is about to begin its study of the ringed planet. Cassini will be sending back pictures from Saturn and it\'s 31 know moons at resolutions unimaginable. I am looking forward to some of the images. You can follow what it finds on the <a href=\"http://saturn.jpl.nasa.gov/home/index.cfm\">Cassini-Huygens</a> page. I would love it if they offered an RSS feed so I could add this to my blogroll so I would always know when they updated the pictures. Hear that <acronym title=\"Need Another Seven Astronauts\">NASA</acronym>? I want an RSS feed on your site.</p>\r\n','Venus and Saturn',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','venus-and-saturn','','','2005-05-10 07:49:14','2005-05-10 12:49:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/venus-and-saturn/',0,'','',0),
	(159,1,'2004-07-06 09:08:12','2004-07-06 14:08:12','<p>The last time <a href=\"http://weblog.trivolt.com\">Brian Mac</a> was up here from Midland, Texas, we got into several heated debates over the pluses and minuses of digital and film camera\'s. It irritated me to think that someone so enthralled with all things binary would say that digital was inferior to old school and shall I say out of date. <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/history/venusandsaturn/#comment261\">He recently commented</a> on my <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/history/venusandsaturn/\">last entry about Saturn</a> that its a shame they aren\'t using real film for the images of Saturn (which I should note I have been more than dissapointed with so far). Never-the less, film would be impossible to use because NASA will no doubt end up losing the Cassini spacecraft in Saturn\'s gassy body. The comment he made when he was here thought which sticks out most in my mind is this. &quot;In ten years, all of your digital images will be thumbnails. I will still be able to enlarge my film.&quot; I hate you so much.</p>\r\n<p>I have recently been agonizing over what insanely priced digital camera to purchase. I am not sure what resolution to go with and what camera has the fastest write time. All together there are about 10 different features which I have decided are most important. All at the same time having an interface as dumb as my first <acronym title=\"Single Lense Reflex\">SLR</acronym> the <a href=\"http://www.vivitar.com/Products/SLRprog/slr.html#V4000-50mm\">Vivitar V4000</a>. All this agonizing while in the back of my head this comment keeps ringing over and over again. &quot;In ten years, all of your digital images will be thumbnails... In ten years, all of your digital images will be thumbnails... In ten years, all of your digital images will be thumbnails.&quot; </p>\r\n<p>So the question now is. Do I spend a ton of money on an 8<acronym title=\"megapixel\">MP</acronym> digital or do I spend half the money and get a film camera which does nearly twice as much and has a simple interface?</p>\r\n<p>The answer. Both. I will probably end up buying a new slightly flashier film <acronym title=\"Single Lense Reflex\">SLR</acronym> <strong>and</strong> a fancy high megapixel camera. They both have their benefits and it doesn\'t hurt to have different cameras for different circumstances.</p>\r\n','film v. digital',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','film-v-digital','','','2005-05-10 07:51:42','2005-05-10 12:51:42','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/film-v-digital/',0,'','',0),
	(160,1,'2005-05-10 12:50:53','2005-05-10 17:50:53','<p>I had this conversation with an Inquirer salesman at work today. I don\'t think he saw this coming.  I really shot every point he made down immediately.  No hesitation in my voice.  No pausing.  It was a straight up back and forth between a smooth talking salesman and a cocky nerd.</p>\r\n<blockquote class=\"conversation\">\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: Hey sir, I\'m from the Inquirer and I wanted to talk to you about getting the paper delivered to your house.</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: That\'s very nice of you sir, but this is a college.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: Oh well perhaps your college would like to have the paper delivered.</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Well we already do in the library.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: What about your department?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Don\'t think we need it.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: What about in your breakroom? Bet you don\'t have one in there.</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Don\'t have a break room.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: Well how about at home? When you want the newspaper you have to go out to the store to buy one. Wouldn\'t it be nice to have one on your doorstep every morning when you wake up?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: I don\'t read the newspaper.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: How do you get your news?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Online.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: Oh but sir that\'s time consuming. You have to search all over for your news and you have to sit there for so long. The newspaper collects all of that information in one place and you can take it with you.</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Well, I really hate the ink and besides google news collects all of the highlights for me and I use RSS to collect everything that google news doesn\'t.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: RSS?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Real Simple Syndication. It\'s very conveniant. Besides I\'m a web developer. I sit in front of a computer all day. Nothing could be more conveniant than online news.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: I see. Well what about sports news?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Online.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: Entertainment?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Online.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: I\'ve got you on this one. TV Guide.</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Don\'t watch TV.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: You don\'t watch TV?</p>\r\n<p class=\"me\">Me: Rots the brain.</p>\r\n<p class=\"them\">Inquirer guy: I give up. Thanks for your time. *click*</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Normally I would have hung up on the guy from the start but I thought I would indulge him.  I have some thoughts on this conversation that I will cover in part two.</p>','The future is grim for print: Part 1',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-future-is-grim-for-print-part-1','','','2005-05-10 12:51:00','2005-05-10 17:51:00','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-future-is-grim-for-print-part-1/',0,'','',6),
	(161,1,'2005-05-12 08:48:55','2005-05-12 13:48:55','Amazing how Burn led directly into the point I wanted to make in part 2.  Burn happens to be one of the most internet savvy people I know.  Like myself he probably uses the internet for most things.  Most of my friends do.  But with as much information as I have, I also have a very closed word view.  My friends are people who have, use and love technology.  I read the blogs about and by people who have, use and love technology.  I work in an environment which is soaked in, uses and loves technology.  There\'s a big world out there of people who do not embrace it like I or Burn do.  \r\n\r\nRecently I was talking to my very internet savvy sister about flickr.  I was trying to tell her about the benefits of it.  Outside of the whole sharing and viewing other people\'s pictures, what happens to your images when your harddrive blows up.  My god the horror.  If you use flickr you are backed up.  And your information is cataloged and dated and explained.  No dice.  She says, \"I\'d still keep it local too.\"  This is a bit far from the original subject, but my point is that its difficult to get people to change the way they do things.  \r\n\r\nI am certainly not trying to say that Geoff is in the wrong career.  His career choice is no worse than mine.  When I say \"The future is grim for print,\" I am talking in the longterm 80 years from now sense.  When you still hear in the news that the internet is an amazing \"new\" technology, you can be sure that the greatest portion of the country (world) is still on the \"haven\'t touched it\" end of the spectrum.  I may have given up on newspapers, but its more for a lack of time.  I must admit that there\'s something sensorially pleasing about a crisp newspaper and a cup of coffee.  Furthermore, its gonna be a long time before I can fathom reading a book on the computer.  \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-future-is-grim-for-print-part-1/\">I gave the salesman a hard time</a> mostly because its fun.  I think that news organizations need to evaluate the way they use the internet for their product delivery, but I don\'t think that the internet will replace printed newspapers anytime within the next 100 years.  ','The future is grim for print: part 2',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-future-is-grim-for-print-part-2','','','2005-05-12 08:52:53','2005-05-12 13:52:53','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-future-is-grim-for-print-part-2/',0,'','',5),
	(162,1,'2005-05-12 23:07:14','2005-05-13 04:07:14','<p>I\'ve written many times that I would sell my soul to google in an instant to work there.  Yahoo too for that matter but thats beside the point.  Recently Google released <a href=\"http://webaccelerator.google.com/\">Web Accelerator</a>.  Basically, while you are reading a website, it secretly clicks every link on the page and downloads all your possibilities ahead of time.  Then when you actually click on the page, its already on your computer.  Simple enough concept, the problem is that it teared web applications to shreads.  <a href=\"http://37signals.com/svn/archives2/google_web_accelerator_hey_not_so_fast_an_alert_for_web_app_designers.php\">37 signals reports</a> that it will cick all the links on the site, even the delete links on web applications, ignoring confirmation messages and effectively remove all the data from a web app.  At this point if you have no interest in web development, you may want to check out <a href=\"http://www.monkeywire.org/\">some news about monkeys or something</a>.</p>\r\n<p>So when you are building an application and you want to add a delete link you might make the link something like this...</p>\r\n<code>&lt;a href=&quot;/code/deleting/actions.php?action=delete&amp;entry=17&quot;&gt;delete&lt;/a&gt;</code>\r\n<p>Then when you click the link, it will go to the page which is programmed to delete the entry 17.  Simple enough.</p>\r\n<p>This is the quick and easy way.  I have on occasion dealt with this in what I see as a better more appropriate way.  I use a form instead of a link.  My code ends up looking like this...</p>\r\n<code>&lt;form action=&quot;/code/deleting/actions.php&quot; method=&quot;post&quot;&gt;\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;entry&quot; value=&quot;17&quot;&gt;\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;action&quot; value=&quot;delete&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;/form&gt;</code>\r\n<p>This code will achieve the same thing as the link above but I believe is more secure and won\'t allow things like spiders and web accelerators to hump your applications to death.</p>','Dealing with the failout of Google Web Accelerator',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','dealing-with-the-failout','','','2005-05-12 23:21:04','2005-05-13 04:21:04','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/dealing-with-the-failout/',0,'','',5),
	(163,1,'2003-07-14 00:00:55','2003-07-14 05:00:55','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8466759/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\" style=\"float:left;margin:0 10px 5px 0;\"><img src=\"http://photos5.flickr.com/8466759_42c964c94a_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" alt=\"Trish makes it up\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Trish and I got back from Boston last night.  It was a wicked good weekend.  Eveything was hela fun.  I loved castle rock near Salem.  We of course climbed to the top and took a bunch of pictures.  actually we took tons of pictures.  Trish loves to take pictures of bizarre stuff.  Bulldogs. Railings. Tons of scenery.Then we got a bunch of pictures of us being sute. Sitting on rocks. Swinging from lamp posts.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.pem.org/yinyutang/\">www.pem.org/yinyutang</a></p>\r\n<p>That\'s me and Trish kickin it on top of Castle Rock near Salem.  That place is cool.  The little hispanic guy in the shorts to the left is from Puerto Rico.  He didn\'t speak very much English but I turned him onto the delight which is Dunkin Donuts.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8467070/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\" style=\"float:right;margin:0 0 5px 10px;\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/8467070_74cad09c70_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"158\" alt=\"Whale Tail\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Rockport, MA is a really great city too.  Lots of artists.  Trish bought a rockin glass painting of Einstein and I bought this mega cool box that was made in Mexico.  They are awesome I think I am going to get a few more just like it.</p>\r\n<p>I can\'t wait to go to Venice, Italy with her over Christmas.  Trish is super awesome to travel with.  We like to do all the same things and we have an overload of fun. We didn\'t sleep enought though so I am mad tired.  Oh and we definately saw a woman that looks like that guy that drove herbie the lovebug in the movie.</p>\r\n<p>The whole point to the trip was the whale watching cruise.  Six hours on a boat and like a third of the people nearly vomited. We saw alot of whales though.</p>','I want to move to Boston!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','i-want-to-move-to-boston','','','2005-05-13 05:48:36','2005-05-13 10:48:36','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/i-want-to-move-to-boston/',0,'','',0),
