	(165,1,'2004-02-04 00:00:15','2004-02-04 05:00:15','<p>After recently releasing <a href=\"http://www.weirdhead.org/\">Weirdhead.org</a>,  I was browsing this page for a, well actually I don\'t remember what the hell   I was looking at. What I was looking at was a mute point. I was looking at this   page and I am fascinated by the concept of a guest book. Of course calling it   this is so old school that it makes me sick. A guestbook brings instant picture of JavaScript banners and rollovers and waving email links. Regardless, on this   page the guy touts being an artist. In his guest book he has all these equally terrible artists who have left him messages about how great he is and how much they like him, the usual cock sucking misogyny. They also all leave links to their pages. So I follow them. The point to my story is this. If you are going   to make a website, make a fucking website. Don\'t make a homepage. No one cares   about you or your favorite links. Furthermore, If you claim to be an artist   your page better not have some fucking bullshit lame ass design that wouldn\'t even appeal to an orangutan surfing the fucking web in 1993. Last, if you are   one of those Neanderthals that still think that <a href=\"http://triangulardmensions.net/3D.html\">pop-up   windows</a>, <a href=\"http://www.pjbuchanan.com/\">roll-overs</a>, animated gifs, <a href=\"http://jpgrdnr.netfirms.com/\">counters (not work appropriate)</a>,   <a href=\"http://www.stephenkasner.com/\">splash pages</a> and <a href=\"http://www.portpak.com/daten/seite01.html\">frames</a> are acceptable, it\'s time to turn in your domain. By the way, <a href=\"http://triangulardmensions.net/3D.html\">disabling the right click</a> should be punishable by castration. Call me a snob, go ahead,   my page will <a href=\"http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.timmyfury.com\">pass validation</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Do you think that Janet flashed her boobs to take the spotlight off of her   brother for a bit. I don\'t know but I have heard a lot about Janet and very   little about Michael. Just a though.</p><p>So there was a message in my last update about the WAWA500. Let me fill you all in. The WAWA500 is a brainchild of Mark\'s and mine. The idea is to go to   every Wawa in the fives states that there are <a href=\"http://www.wawa.com/\">Wawa</a>\'s in one 72 hours period. Then we rate them and get pictures. I have sent a message to Red Roof to get a list of all the locations of Wawa. From there we will examine   the plausibility of going to every Wawa in three days. The plan may change slightly   but the idea remains the same. I believe that we will try to schedule it for   some time when Code comes home from Qatar and Geoff is in the area. This way   everyone may participate. I\'ll update you as plans come together.</p>\r\n<p> The current obsession with dieting in the life of everyone around me is sort   of scary. Christ I\'m fucking fat and I still get kissed. <a href=\"http://www.theonion.com/4004/infograph.html\">The   Onion will show us how ridiculous it is!</a></p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.meph.eu.org/\">a game from Debbie</a>...</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.defense.gouv.fr/terre/orga/orga_gds_serv/rattaches/shat/shat_ie.html\">the French historical society</a>...</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://money.cnn.com/2003/09/10/technology/pirates/index.htm\">why I\'ll be going to jail soon</a>...</p>\r\n<p>Jay-Z has the greatest lyric in one of his new songs. I think it\'s new. He\'s   all, \"If you got girl problems I feel bad for you son, I got 99 problems   but the bitch ain\'t none.\" </p><p>Last on the agenda this week is corporate babble. A while back I ran into the add-on to Microsoft Office called <a href=\"http://www.dc.com/insights/bullfighter/index.asp\">Bullfighter</a>. It basically reads your document and finds the bullshit corporate words. This   update had an 8.8 on a scale of 1-10 (ten being good). I don\'t know how accurate that is though cause we all know everything I say is bullshit. For those of   you who don\'t know what I\'m talking about I\'ll explain. At work I don\'t fix computers, I maintain systems. I don\'t walk across the school to talk to Eric;   I attend an important meeting on a special project. Committee. Policy. Procedure.   We don\'t move computers around. We cascade them. Well anyway If you don\'t get it get an office job. Regardless, I read a story that I ran into on <a href=\"http://slashdot.org/\">Slashdot</a>   that some wiseass had used corporate speak to fuck with people. And I finally   got to use his line at work in our all-staff meeting. Someone asked, \"What   should we do with the two computers by the door?\" I reply, \"Redeployment through strategic <a href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/search?q=defenestration\">defenestration</a>.\"   This led me to come up with another good way of moving computers around. \"In the next fiscal quarter we will institute a strategic cascading policy where   personnel will acquisition redeployed computing hardware through strategic celiac deposition\" Basically we are will be giving everyone new computer\'s then   ramming them up their ass.</p>','Turn in your domains!!!!!!!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','turn-in-your-domains','','','2006-04-20 07:30:40','2006-04-20 12:30:40','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/turn-in-your-domains/',0,'','',0),
	(166,1,'2004-03-08 00:00:25','2004-03-08 05:00:25','<p>President Bush has set aside, not millions, but billions of dollars in the   war on terror. People don\'t call it the war on terrorISM. They call it the war   on terror. This concept is redicukous to me. President Bush and his monkeys   have changed the word from <a href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/search?q=terrorism\">terrorism</a> to <a href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/search?q=terror\">terror</a> because it sounds more marketable. <a href=\"http://www.defendamerica.mil/\">The War on   Terror</a>. It sounds so very cool. </p>\r\n<p>But on my ride into work I was thinking of all the things he has waged war   on in the name of this War on Terror. <a href=\"http://images.google.com/images?hl=en&lr=&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&q=osama\">Osama bin Laden</a>, <a href=\"http://www.usdoj.gov/ag/trainingmanual.htm\">al Qaeda</a>,   <a href=\"http://images.google.com/images?hl=en&lr=&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&q=saddam&sa=N&tab=wi\">Saddam Hussien</a>, Afganistan and Iraq, the Roadmap to peace. All of these monsters are targeted and I have not seen one bit of money dedicated to the real monsters   of the world.</p>\r\n<p>Every night millions of children around the world are stricken with terror  by the real monsters under their beds and in their closets. When will Bush have   the common sense to extend the War on Terror to those who need it most, the children. Bush\'s selfish motives have kept federal funding out from under the beds of American children and they continue to suffer while Bush goes after   low level terror suspects like Osama bin Laden.</p>\r\n<p>It\'s high time Bush sees the real source of terror. Closet monsters, bed monsters and boogiemen.</p>','What is terror really?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','what-is-terror-really','','','2005-05-13 05:56:52','2005-05-13 10:56:52','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/what-is-terror-really/',0,'','',0),
	(167,1,'2004-05-14 11:46:13','2004-05-14 16:46:13','<p>About 5 months ago I read a few things about search engine optimization or SEO.  I went on a SEO campaign on both <a href=\"http://www.weirdhead.org\">Weirdhead.org</a> and <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com\">Timmyfury.com</a> in an attempt to siphon some extra hits from people who do searches for things that might lead them to my page.  This also coincided with my new found addiction to <a href=\"http://www.webstandards.org/\">web standards</a>.</p>\r\n<p>My main source of inspiration, if I should call it that, Was an article on <a href=\"http://www.alistapart.com/articles/seo/\">A list apart</a> and this checklist from <a href=\"http://www.submit-it.com/subopt.htm\">Submit-it</a>.</p>  \r\n<p>Never the less, I am still waiting for some evidence of the benefit of my SEO campaign and its relevance in the area of search. In fact, Weirdhead.org has not benefitted in the least.  This is made apparent in the fact that it doesn\'t even come up on the first three pages when you do a <a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=weirdhead\">Google search for weirdhead</a>.  Furthermore, when you search for <a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=link:http://www.weirdhead.org\"> backlinks to weirdhead</a> nothing at all comes up and I have certainly linked to it being that it is my other site.  What I find most interesting though is that timmyfury.com appears on the first page, twice, when you do this search.</p>\r\n<p>I have only noticed one difference relating to Google since I went on my campaign.</p> \r\n<p>In the five month period since I started SEO campaign my <a href=\"http://toolbar.google.com/\">google toolbar</a> page rank has gone from a 0/10 to a 4/10.  I was curious as to if these two facts were correlated in anyway.  It turns out that they are not.  In <a href=\"http://www.iprcom.com/papers/pagerank/\">Ian Rogers article about Google page rank</a>, he explains that the page ranking is solely based on back linking.</p>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://www.iprcom.com/papers/pagerank/\">\r\n<p>PageRank is one of the methods Google uses to determine a page\'s relevance or importance. It is only one part of the story when it comes to the Google listing, but the other aspects are discussed elsewhere (and are ever changing) and PageRank is interesting enough to deserve a paper of its own.</p>\r\n<p>PageRank is also displayed on the toolbar of your browser if you\'ve installed the Google toolbar (<a href=\"http://toolbar.google.com/\">http://toolbar.google.com/</a>). But the Toolbar PageRank only goes from 0 - 10 and seems to be something like a logarithmic scale:</p>\r\n<table title=\"google page rank\">\r\n<tr><th>Toolbar PageRank(log base 10)</th><th>Real PageRank</th></tr>\r\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0 - 10</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>1</td><td>100 - 1,000</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>2</td><td>1,000 - 10,000</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>3</td><td>10,000 - 100,000</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td>4</td><td>and so on...</td></tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><em>source: <a href=\"http://www.iprcom.com/papers/pagerank/\">The Google Pagerank Algorithmand How It Works</a></em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>It turns out that my Google page rank has more to do with the amount of content on my site then my SEO campaign or my seemingly painful obsession with web standards.  Although Google page rank has only slight bearing on your Google listing overall it does show the importance of frequenting other blog sites like this one and commenting.  Getting your name out there seems to be the best way to improve your Google page rank.  A small site like mine depends mostly on the word of mouth of other small sites in my overall Google listing.</p>\r\n<p>As an aside to this, I noticed that Google itself has a 10/10 google ranking on the Google toolbar. Yahoo and MSN both have 9/10 ratings. I am curious as to why this is. If Google page rankings are based on links, and if as Ian Rogers said the Google page rank is based on backlinks, then since Yahoo and MSN have a far greater amount of countent shouldn\'t they have a higher page rank? I may be jumping to conclusions about MSN and Yahoo having more content, but they seem to. This fact makes me question <a href=\"http://www.google.com/googleblog/2004/05/some-disturbing-results.html\">Googles statements in their blog</a> about not being swayed. <a href=\"http://www.google.com/explanation.html\">They stated that their results are based 100% on their algorithms.</a> I am curious.</p>\r\n<p>Keep in mind that Google was the only search engine I used for my obsrervations; half because I am obsessed with Google and the other half because I am lazy.  Try some searches out.  Let me know what you find. See if any of my most frequently discussed topics come up in Google.</p>\r\n<p><em>I would like to note that my statistics class has come back to bite me in the ass.  I worked pretty hard in the class and got a \"C.\"  Some may say that sucks.  I was so excited because I thought I would fail for sure.  Now I don\'t have to take the course again.  In this entry I linked to some pages that used some statistical concept and terms that I had on many occasions said, \"I will never use this crap.\"  I would like to apologize for these statements.  I used to say the same thing about certain classes in high school and was promptly proved wrong the day I started programming.  I would like to be able to say that I will never make a statement like this again.  That will never happen.</em></p>','My SEO campaign: In doubt.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','seodoubt','','','2005-05-13 06:00:02','2005-05-13 11:00:02','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/my-seo-campaign-in-doubt/',0,'','',0),
	(168,1,'2004-05-31 02:55:09','2004-05-31 07:55:09','<p>The Friday before Trish left I met her at West Chester for lunch while she was on break from her class.  When she went back to class I had about 4 hours to kill until she was done class so we could go out to dinner.  I shot down 202 South to go to the mall and snag a pair of jeans.  It took me forever to get from West Chester to Route one on 202 South.  It\'s about a 6 minute drive; It took about 25 mintues.  Luckily though I was alright with this due to the fact that when it comes to large trucks and trains and construction equipment I have the mentality of a five year old.  I was stuck behind this crane and another related truck.  It took up nearly two lanes.  I got a picture as I passed when they went to turn onto Route one.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13608391/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/13608391_868be05e2a_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Crane Close up\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13608444/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/13608444_c6959388ad_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Crane Driving away\" /></a></p>','Big Ass Crane!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','big-ass-crane','','','2005-05-13 06:03:05','2005-05-13 11:03:05','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/168/',0,'','',0),
