	(178,1,'2004-02-11 00:00:10','2004-02-11 05:00:10','<p>I was reading <a href=\"http://www.slashdot.org/\">slashdot</a> the other day. And I ran over this article about <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/2004/02/08/agenda_detection.html\">meetings</a> on this guy\'s blog. But I found this entry too on <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com/archives/2003/07/10/nadd.html\">N.A.D.D.</a> before you read this I would like to give you my rundown. Winamp full of Dead Can Dance, Dreamweaver where I am writing this update, my music library, three   instant messenger conversations, the websites to two of my online classes, my email, and as if it weren\'t enough I also have a two perl manuals open on my   bed and I have my psyche book in my lap from which I am taking a break to write   this. Completely separate from this topic except for the fact that it has to do with slashdot, I hate when people talk about slashdot but they don\'t type it out they just type \" /.\". It\'s fucking queer, stop doing that.</p>\r\n<p>I was sitting at work on Monday and one of my co-workers walks past and asks how I am and I answer what I am supposed to answer, like a good little drone   I tell her I am doing fine. Then I realixze that its Julie and I can tell her how I really am. I mean come on its monday freaking morning. How am I supposed   to be when I have only had 4 cups of coffee. Regardless, I said, \"Actually, I am horribly fine.\" She likes the the connotation of this and responded, \"Well I am excrutiatingly okay with that.\" We went back and forth   for a few moments and came up with a bunch of these. Julie defined them as The   Hyperbole followed by The Mediocre. Give em the grandeur, then give em the expected.</p>\r\n<p>I worked Camp-in again this weekend. It was rather fun. I\'m really into it   this year. I wish I could work more of them. Perhaps a death plot for one of   the other three managers. Hmmmm. um... okay... well it was an interesting evening. It was the night of the <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/mld/dailynews/news/local/7927690.htm\">   incident at the library</a>. This wasn\'t an issue for us although I was worried   early in the night that it may get passed to one of the parents and we would have a bunch of histerical mothers on our hands. There were 600, yes 600, girls   and mothers in the museum on Saturday night. The only 7 guys there were staff.   Damn. Here\'s the poin though. The craziest part of the night was when I was woken up at 4:20 in the morning and the security guard tells me that there is   an alarm clock going off in the store right next to an exhibit that has 77 girls   sleeping in it. It took me a good five minutes to figure out what the hell he   was talking about. I went down to the exhibit and knew right away I was going   to have to call like everyone in the museum at home at 4:30am. This alarm clock   was playing some whack ass disco music and singing and shit. It was crazy. I   ran around the museum for about 30 minutes finding phone numbers and calling   people to try to find a key to the store. No one had one and all the while more and more girls were stirring and my boss was doing all this crazy talk about   moving 77 girls to another place to sleep at 4:30 in the morning. At about 4:45am,   the alarm had been doing its middle-eastern love cry for about 45 minutes now, it just turned off. And thank god cause I do believe that I had about 10 more   minutes before I was forced to walk the plank on the ship in Kid Science.</p>\r\n<p>Idea of the year... I think it is. You know those stickers on bussiness cars   that say, \"How\'s my driving? Call 1-800-PHONE-NUMBER ID-OF-DRIVER\"   okay so I think that I want to get one of those made up but put my cell phone number on it. Then I\'ll go out driving like a complete retard. Someone will   naturally call to report it and I\'ll be like \"What are you a fucking five year old. You fucking taddle-tail!\" then hang up. Or even better I could   be like, \"Describe what he\'s doing.\" Then start driving back and forth   across the road. Drive into oncoming traffic. Wow. That would be great.</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.rythospital.com/\">don\'t believe everything you read</a>...</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.magic-cone.com/animation1.htm\">magic cone</a>...</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.heavensfantasy.com/cool/\">a pleasant surprise</a>...</p>\r\n<p>It could be worse. <a href=\"http://jackflannel.org/lotr/\">This</a> could be you.</p>\r\n','How\'s my Driving now?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','hows-my-driving-now','','','2005-05-13 06:51:34','2005-05-13 11:51:34','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/hows-my-driving-now/',0,'','',0),
	(179,1,'2004-02-18 00:00:38','2004-02-18 05:00:38','<p>I spoke to one of the librarians at work the other day following her gathering   which revolved around the infamous \"virus protection.\" What she,   and I for that matter, found to be most entertaining about it was the insinuation that the viruses that have been taking down systems in the country over the   past year had something to do with the ever sinister and devious Al Qaeda. The   fact of the matter is that I have not been able to find any real proof that any of the most recent virus proliferation has anything to do with terrorism   or an attack on the much sought after \"national security.\"</p>\r\n<p>I read <a href=\"http://news.com.com/2100-7349_3-5158496.html\">something very interesting last night</a> which is the root to why I am giving all of you this   information. As you may know Linux is an open-source operating system. It is   free in most cases and there is a strong following in the hacker/web design/server   administration sector of the information technology industry for Linux. It touts   a highly secure environment mostly due to the fact that the source code or the   programming behind how it works is open to everyone, including hackers. This   gives everyone the ability to examine the code and find possible security holes   and exploits. This is a very different approach than our good friends at Microsoft take. Their source code is highly protected. In fact recently about <a href=\"http://news.com.com/2100-7349_3-5158496.html\">1/10th of 1 percent </a>of the code behind Microsoft\'s Windows 2000 professional   was leaked and within a week there were already two highly damaging exploits shared on the internet; in other words two gaping security holes.</p>\r\n<p>  There is a company called SCO which makes server operating system software. They claim that the creators of Linux have stolen a chunk of their code and   they have vowed to sue a large-scale Linux user by today, November18th. Many think this user will be Google. Yes, that\'s right, our long time friend   and ever gracious searching savior. Google is rumored to have somewhere close to 10,000 servers running Linux. </p>\r\n<p>Now here\'s where it gets a little tricky and I\'m not sure if the logic of this and the connection to all of you will come through here.</p>\r\n<p>The myDoom virus was written to attack SCO and Microsoft specifically because of this lawsuit. Microsoft is involved because they want to take Linux out of the operating system game. </p>\r\n<p>Now for the reason that you care. \"And Microsoft, which has been accused of conniving with SCO in its march against Linux, is slated to enter the search   market and compete against Google. The widgetry, which is supposed to retrieve all kinds of file types, both structured and unstructured, and all kinds of   storage systems, beginning with the user\'s own drive, will be integrated into its operating systems like the anticipated Longhorn.\"</p>\r\n<p>This is important and I believe you should all be interested because the ever evil, corporate whoring, monster which is Microsoft could be changing your search in a big way sometime in the near future. In addition, if Microsoft were to include this searching capability in their OS which included searching your personal PC there could be some very serious ramifications. Just imagine if   you had say 7,732 mp3 files on your PC and the RIAA decided to search for them.   Big problem thats a $1,159,800,000 fine you have on your hands there my friend. It\'s enough to make me go Mac or Linux.</p>\r\n<p>Just to wrap it up I think maybe I should point out the point to this rant   because I believe I strayed a bit while I was trying to show you the connection   of this information to us. Viruses are not targeted toward national security. They are targeted toward greedy corporations who try to hinder the development of computing. Secondly, not all hackers  are bad. Some have the security of computing   in mind. And last, Google could be in trouble so keep them in mind in  your bed-time   prayers.</p>\r\n<p>A final thought on the subject from that article on <a href=\"http://www.linuxworld.com/\">LinuxWorld.com</a>, \"Meanwhile, industry wags are saying that God invented SCO to give people a company to hate more than Microsoft.\"</p>','How Microsoft is trying to ruin search',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','how-microsoft-is-trying-to-ruin-search','','','2005-05-13 06:54:04','2005-05-13 11:54:04','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/how-microsoft-is-trying-to-ruin-search/',0,'','',0),
	(180,1,'2004-02-22 00:00:16','2004-02-22 05:00:16','<p>This November we will have an election that pits George Bush against either   John Edwards or John Kerry. Bush currently stands with a <a href=\"http://www.pollingreport.com/BushJob.htm\">48%   job approval rating</a>. In comparisons between Bush and the Democratic prsidential hopefuls Bush stands very close to ebing able to pull an upset and keep the   White House. I think an upset would be if Bush was really low in the polls and   he came back but in this context I am refering to what I will be if Bush wins   this year... UPSET. Regardless, Bush stands within only a few points of Kerry   for the White House in November and Bush and Edwards would be <a href=\"http://www.pollingreport.com/wh04gen.htm\">neck   and neck</a>. All this information aside let\'s take a look at the <a href=\"http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/2000presgeresults.htm\">2000   election</a> for president that brought Bush into power. Al Gore, who regardless   of the fact that he may have very well simply been the lesser of two evils,   lost in both Florida (by less than 600 votes) and New Hampshire (a less dramatic   8000 votes). These are both significant states in the election and had Gore   won either of these states he most likely would have won the election. Our next   observation is that Ralph Nader has similar mores as the Democratic party. Therefore   if he didn\'t want the far right Republican bovine to remain in power you may   think that he wouldn\'t want to take votes from the Democratic candidate in November   like he did in 2000. How many votes did Nader get in Florida and New Hampshire?   97,488 and 22,198 respectively. One might think that with as close as the platforms   that Nader and the Democrats (a really politcally charged name for an anti-Republican   punk band) run on Nader may have decided not to run this November. If this is   what you thought, you would be <a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/02/22/elec04.prez.nader/index.html\">wrong</a>.   I think that Kerry and Edwards are gonna have to team up on this one and run   together. </p>\r\n<p>Next on the adgenda is the comment left to me by \"A Person\" on last the <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/history/microsoftruinssearch/\">February 18th</a> update. A Person says, \"<a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/comment/microsoftruinssearch/\">Your obsessed with directories.</a>\" You are obviously new to the web design   world and I bet you think that all of the directories actually exist. Using   directories makes you URL\'s very managable. By putting these fake directories   into a database it also makes your updates very managable. Then if one day I decide to go from PHP to ASP (god rest my soul on that day) or maybe Coldfusion   (if I had an enormous amount of money to waste on a crappy blog) then it would   make the transition smooth and effortless. This is called forethought. In addition   if you were to read the <a href=\"http://www.weirdhead.org/mission/\">mission statement on Weirdhead.org</a> you would be clued in a bit more to my current drive in web design. You wanna see alot of directories go to Weirdhead.org. Let me know if you have anymore quips about my design style. If you are in fact   new to the scene (I\'m a loser) try reading up on <a href=\"http://www.w3.org\">web   accessibility and standards</a>. </p>\r\n<p>That guy who does <a href=\"http://www.randsinrepose.com\">Rands in Repose</a>   also apparently has something to do with <a href=\"http://www.jerkcity.com/jerkcity1965.html\">this</a>.</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.artweb-market.com/yonilab.htm\">hotties</a>...</p>\r\n<p>...<a href=\"http://www.newscientist.com/news/news.jsp?id=ns99994685\">I can\'t   find the right words to tell you</a>...</p>\r\n<p>Finally I have bought floors for my Buick. I am super excited about this. I haven\'t really done anything with my car in like a million years (10 months).   I ordered $415 worth of floor pans. I keep you up to date on the progress. A big shout out to Alex from <a href=\"http://www.opgi.com\">OPGI</a> for helping me order the right shit.</p>\r\n<p>It could be worse. <a href=\"http://www.thecostumer.com/store/product.cfm?prodID=1058\">This</a> could be you.</p>\r\n','Ralph Nader - the anti-consumer advocate',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','ralph-nader-the-anti-consumer-advocate','','','2006-04-14 11:35:50','2006-04-14 16:35:50','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/ralph-nader-the-anti-consumer-advocate/',0,'','',0),
	(299,1,'2006-01-24 13:32:10','2006-01-24 18:32:10','http://msnbc.msn.com/id/10856867/site/newsweek/\r\n\r\nhttp://www.apple.com/trailers/disney/ratatouille/pop_apple.html?size=large','anti-anti-french',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','anti-anti-french','','','2006-06-09 14:09:31','2006-06-09 19:09:31','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/01/anti-anti-french/',0,'','',0),
	(183,1,'2005-05-16 22:38:13','2005-05-17 03:38:13','<a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/14081063/\" style=\"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;\"><img src=\"http://photos12.flickr.com/14081063_c1de01c214_m.jpg\" alt=\"the view is amazing\" /></a>\r\n<p>I had an amazing weekend.  The synopsis and a bit of detail in bulleted form with a multitude of accompanying links...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dinner at Jarrod\'s - <a href=\"http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/recipes/recipe/0,,FOOD_9936_27966,00.html\">pork chops</a> and beer.  <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/345210/\">Jarrod ate an apple for us</a>. <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/67493834@N00/\">Michelle</a>, <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/\">Trish</a>, Allison, <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> and Lee were also present.  <a href=\"http://www.victorybeer.com/Beers/SunriseWeissbier.htm\">Beer was consumed</a>.</li>\r\n<li>Stop over at the <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/14081770/\">Embassy suites</a> to check in and change for dinner.  Part one of my birthday present. The view from the hotel was awesome as you can see next door.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.zanzibarblue.com/pa/menu.htm\">Zanzibar Blue for dinner</a>.  I ordered duck, Trish ordered chicken.  I had the chicken, Trish had the duck.  If you\'ve never eaten with us its quite an experience.  Trish had a Parisian Salad.  After dinner we saw <a href=\"http://www.dianeschuur.com/content/bio.htm\">Diane Schuur</a> with <a href=\"http://members.aol.com/plabjazz/caribjazz.html\">Caribbean Jazz Project</a>.</li>\r\n<li>A nice romantic site in <a href=\"http://www.ushistory.org/lovepark/\">Love park</a>. <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/14081618/\">Then back to the hotel</a>.</li>\r\n<li>Up in the morning and off to <a href=\"http://www.philamuseum.org/information/index.shtml\">The Art Museum</a> to see the <a href=\"http://www.virtualdali.com/\">Dali Exhibit</a>.  So amazing.  I\'ve seen Dali\'s work before when I was in Venice, but it was just amazing.</li>\r\n<li>Back out of the city.  A stop at Jarrod\'s house puts <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/342564/\">Trish and Michelle on the trampoline</a> for about an hour.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A satisfying weekend to say the least.  Feel free to talk amongst yourselves about how interesting and awesome my life is and I will moderate as I see fit.</p>','Weekend of Awesome',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','weekend-of-awesome','','','2005-05-16 22:41:21','2005-05-17 03:41:21','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/dinner-hotel-dali/',0,'','',1),
	(184,1,'2003-11-03 21:59:35','2003-11-04 02:59:35','<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8468485/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\" style=\"float:left;margin: 0 10px 5px 0;\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/8468485_a754d0adc1_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"arms up\" /></a>\r\n<p>This weekend Trish, Jarrod, Mark, Code, Crissy, Michelle and I went to <a href=\"http://www.worldchampionshippunkinchunkin.com/\">punkin chunkin</a>.  Hella fun.  Jarrod rode the mechanical bull.  He looked like he was drunk while he rode the thing.  Oh wait.  One of the catapults launched a pumpkin into the crowd.  didn\'t get anyone though, unfortunately considering how retarded everyone below the mason-dixon is.  We actually saw a guy with a huge swastika tattoo on his arm.</p>\r\n<p>The new site design is done as you can see.  Inspired by <a href=\"http://weblog.trivolt.com\" class=\"blog\">brian mac</a>.  He turned me onto design with CSS which I owe himn greatly for.  I will be finishing up the site sometime this week.  the graffiti board works but the cartoons and the history don\'t.  Gimme time.  Never fear.  Check out <a href=\"http://www.weirdhead.org/\">weirdhead.org</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Don\'t forget to vote tomorrow.  I know it\'s not a big election but if you don\'t vote then not only do you give up your right to talk about politics and the state of the nation, but you also give up your right to oppose chemical castration as punishment for those who shirk their civic duties.</p>\r\n\r\n','flying Pumpkins and the new look',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','flying-pumpkins-and-the-new-look','','','2005-05-16 21:46:27','2005-05-17 02:46:27','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/flying-pumpkins-and-the-new-look/',0,'','',0),
	(185,1,'2004-03-08 00:00:33','2004-03-08 05:00:33','<p>Every morning I wake up and go into the bathroom and take a shower. When I   am finished and am heading to my room to get dressed the cat is sitting on the   floor about three feet from the door outside of the bathroom. He waits until   I leave the bathroom then he strolls in. </p>\r\n<p>I came to the realization this morning that the cat has a full-time job. There\'s no other reason for him to be awake that early. I mean come on, he\'s a cat.   Why else does a cat get up that early and wait for the bathroom. He needs to shit and shower before work. I think one of these days I am going to wait around   instead of leaving for work as soon as I am ready. I want to see him stroll   out of the house in his suit carrying his briefcase. He\'ll probably be scarfing down a quick breakfast as he rushes out to an important bussiness meeting. </p>\r\n','Business Cat',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','business-cat','','','2005-05-16 21:48:56','2005-05-17 02:48:56','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/business-cat/',0,'','',0),
	(186,1,'2004-03-23 21:13:42','2004-03-24 02:13:42','<p>The following is a conversation, or a paraphrase thereof, which I had at work today with a girl in my lab.</p>\r\n<p>\"Do you work here?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"I do.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Can you help me?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"I can.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"I\'m having trouble with this laptop.  The screen is all widgy on the right side.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Is it one of the school\'s laptop\'s?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"No.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"I\'m sorry I can\'t help you.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Please just look at it from far away.  Maybe you would have a suggestion for me.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Okay, no problem but I am not allowed to touch your computer.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"That\'s fine I just need some advice.  My screen is all widgy.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Define widgy.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"You know, widgy.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Oh I see.\" No idea.</p>\r\n<p>She turns the laptop on after struggling with the electrical outlet for about 5 minutes.  I look at the screen of this laptop and it is destroyed.  It looks like someone hit the thing with a baseball.</p>\r\n<p>\"Do you see what I mean?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Yeah, it\'s broken alright.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Yeah it is.  I don\'t know how it happened.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Did you by chance... drop it?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Yeah.\"</p>\r\n<p>I stare at her and cock one eyebrow.  Scrunching my face slightly like I had just swallowed a gulp of coffee which had been sitting on my desk for a few days.</p>\r\n<p>\"So it\'s not fixable is it?\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Yeah of course.  For the price of a new laptop you could buy a new screen.\"</p>\r\n<p>So at this point she is pissed off at me because apparently I was supposed to pull out my magic wand and poof make it better.</p>\r\n<p>\"Well if I buy a new laptop is there anything that I can do to prevent this from happening?\"</p>\r\n<p>A dramatic pause for emphasis...</p>\r\n<p>\"...Don\'t drop your laptop.\"</p>\r\n<p>It really honestly seemed like common sense to me, but I think at that point she was on the verge of punching me in the stomach.  And so it goes another day through in the world of a community college library helpdesk technician.</p>\r\n','The ongoing helpdesk saga',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-ongoing-helpdesk-saga','','','2005-05-16 21:51:11','2005-05-17 02:51:11','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-ongoing-helpdesk-saga/',0,'','',0),
	(187,1,'2004-04-04 13:44:16','2004-04-04 18:44:16','The other day I helped my father and mother move my older sister into her new house.  My father and I took off work to do so and my Mom and Dad were hapy that I helped because they aren\'t exactly in the proper shape to lug heavy boxes up and down stairs.  It took us all day because my sister didn\'t have anything packed.\r\n\r\nWe get home and my father says, \"We know you don\'t have to help us but we really appreciate it.  And we let you live here and all that nice stuff so it\'s nice that you pay us back in favors.  And I know I don\'t have to do anything to repay you but I feel it would be nice.\"\r\n\r\nSo he lays four lottery tickets out on the table.  There were three scratch and win and one pick your numbers tickets.\r\n\r\n\"All four of these tickets have a dollar value.  You may pick one.  you get to keep the one you pick.  But you are stuck with it once you pick it.\"\r\n\r\nSo I sit and agonize over which one to pick. I was inclined to pick the one that was a pick-your-numbers ticket but after about five minutes I chose one of the three dollar scratch and wins.\r\n\r\nI look at the ticket and its the most complicated ticket ever.  He looks over my shoulder and says, \"Thats the ninety dollar ticket.\"\r\n\r\n\"Sweet. What were the others worth?\"\r\n\r\n\"Twenty-five, thirty-five, and twenty-one.\"\r\n\r\nWhat luck.  I picked the good ticket.  So anyway he says to me, \"You see Tim, sometimes when you gamble - you lose.\"','Lottery ticket lottery!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','lottery-ticket-lottery','','','2006-02-15 09:46:05','2006-02-15 14:46:05','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/lottery-ticket-lottery/',0,'','',0),
	(188,1,'2004-06-18 13:13:07','2004-06-18 18:13:07','<p>I was reading this article on BBC News about <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/3811785.stm\">teleportation</a>. Apparently scientists have teleported atoms successfully for the first time.  In the article though it says, \"Experts say being able to do the same with massive particles like atoms could lead to new superfast computers.\"</p>\r\n<p>By <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom\">wikipedia\'s</a> account, \"An atom is the smallest portion into which a chemical element can be divided while still retaining its properties.\" Looking at the weight of a molecule of iron (which is made up of atoms)at 55.845 amu or 55 grams at one mol, I begin to wonder.  If an atom is considered massive, what hope does a 250lb bastard like me ever have of being teleported to Wawa before I die?</p>\r\n','What hope do I have?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','what-hope-do-i-have','','','2005-05-16 21:54:37','2005-05-17 02:54:37','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/what-hope-do-i-have/',0,'','',0),
	(189,1,'2004-03-15 13:00:09','2004-03-15 18:00:09','<p>Trish and I went this weekend to see the <a href=\"http://www.harlemglobetrotters.com/\" title=\"The Harlem Globetrotters Homepage\">Harlem Globetrotters</a>. It was so fun. Probably one of the most entertaining things   I have seen in a long time. They did the old confetti trick. This is where they   pretend to throw a bucket of water on the audience but its full of confetti. I think one of the funniest things was when they were running down the court   and they threw the ball to the ref. I could be one of the refs on that show.   Mr. Popular, one of the players, came out in the beginning and said, \"before   we get started, we would like to thank our sponsor, Burger King, for allowing   us to eat delicious Whoppers.\" I thought that was funny. </p>\r\n<p>There was this group of High school age kids that performed a dance thing at   half time. It was certainly interesting. There\'s nothing quite like half clothed   high school girls throwing themselves around and rolling on a basketball court.   Each one slightly out of step. None of them really knowing what the hell is   going on.</p>\r\n<p>The other group that was there was this acrobatic group <a href=\"http://www.capitolint.com/mapapavarietybio.htm\" title=\"The Flying Mapapas Information page\">The Flying Mapapas</a>. They were awesome. They reminded both Trish and I of this   acrobat group, <a href=\"http://www.hebei-acrobatic.com/english/f_jianjie.htm\" title=\"Hebei Acrobatic Troupe of China Hompage\">The Hebei Acrobatic Troupe of China</a> that performed in the <a href=\"http://www.ringling.com/explore/133/\" title=\"the Ringling Brothers Hompage\">circus last year</a>. They were freaking awesome. They built these huge towers out   of themselves. Tres Bueno. Stacking ontop of each other and jumping through each other\'s legs. I thought they were amazing.</p>\r\n<p>In other stuff, I have made some changes to the site. They are small and you   may not even notice them. They are purely logistic. Although I have added the   ability to give your homepage when you comment.</p>\r\n','Basketball can be fun!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','basketball-can-be-fun','','','2005-05-16 21:57:29','2005-05-17 02:57:29','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/basketball-can-be-fun/',0,'','',1),
	(190,1,'2004-06-09 09:15:43','2004-06-09 14:15:43','<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/14273022/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\" style=\"float:right;margin:0 0 5px 10px;\"><img src=\"http://photos14.flickr.com/14273022_dd7d20dde8_m.jpg\" width=\"223\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Reparations man\" /></a>\r\n<p>Trish and I were driving down route 82 in Delaware the other day. The road goes back and forth over this set of tracks and just as Trish finishes saying, \"Do you think they use these anymore?\" We pass this.</p>\r\n<p>As for the illustration... well, the man is supposed to be blind.  You can\'t see that in the illustration but he\'s a blind man pushing that cart down those tracks and up and into the water he goes. Geoff\'s idea, I only illustrated it for the masses</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/7275462/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos8.flickr.com/7275462_8d5738475a.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"Tracks twisted and rubble piled\" /></a></p> \r\n<p>The entire collection is <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/181478/\">available on flickr</a></p>','I don\'t work for no man!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','railroadtracktwist','','','2006-02-15 09:09:11','2006-02-15 14:09:11','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/i-dont-work-for-no-man/',0,'','',0),
	(191,1,'2004-07-07 22:44:57','2004-07-08 03:44:57','<a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10341409/\"><img width=\"500\" height=\"347\" alt=\"Biking after dressing myself\" src=\"http://photos8.flickr.com/10341409_d2c5a2976b.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere is a large number of shows on TV right now which mock the habits and phrases and trends of yesteryear. Most of these shows are on VH1 such as \"<a href=\"http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/i_love_the_80s/series.jhtml\">I Love the 80\'s</a>\" and the soon to premier \"<a href=\"http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/i_love_the_90s/series.jhtml\">I love the 90\'s</a>\", which premiers soon . These shows are great because not only do they make me feel all weepy nostalgic but they mock everything about those times. I know one thing though. I will never be on one of these shows because I have never quite been able to get a grip on style.','I dress myself',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','i-dress-myself','','','2006-02-15 09:47:47','2006-02-15 14:47:47','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/i-dress-myself/',0,'','',0),
	(192,1,'2004-03-18 22:03:28','2004-03-19 03:03:28','For about three months they have been working on this construction site which   it turns out they are building a storage place on. I have noticed every single   time I drive past that there is this giant chainsaw on the construction site.   So yeah, you\'re like, \"A giant chainsaw, whatever.\" But I\'m definately  like, \"Look at the damn pictures.\" That\'s a god damn giant chainsaw.\r\n\r\nThis thing mystifies me. It looks freakin\' awesome. It\'s apparently made by <a title=\"the Case corporate website\" href=\"http://www.casece.com/index.asp?RL=NAE\">Case</a>, I believe its actually a <a title=\"an example of a trencher\" href=\"http://www.toro.com/professional/sws/loaderattach/trencher/22447.html\">trencher</a>. But it certainly looks like a giant chainsaw to me. I mean come on. Look at the picture of Mark right next to it. He\'s near six foot and he looks like a <a title=\"a site about little people\" href=\"http://mikesundance.com/midgets.htm\">midget</a>. The blade on this thing is like thirty feet long and five foot high.\r\n\r\nI will now offer you a few simple scenerios for reasons that you would need to own on of these enormous chainsaws...\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\"Honey, that tree in the backyard really sizzles my nipples.  Do you think that we could remove it this weekend?\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"I\'m installing these beautiful new French doors in my house but this dang sawz-it-all just won\'t make it through the walls.\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"My wife is pregnant, traffic is terrible and my monster truck is broken down.  Can I borrow your car?\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"I\'ll show those bloody neighbors for playing there music loudly\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"I\'m performing a nation wide survey. Do you have five minutes to answer a few short questions?\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"Hey John, my carving knife seems to have gone missing.  Could you please offer me some sort of turkey carving implement?\"</li>\r\n	<li>\"Oh great and wise moat digger.  The Visigoths are advancing on the western stretches of our vast kingdom.  His royal highness has requested you by name.  He desires a moat around the shire.  Can you do it?\"</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou see? The giant chainsaw has tons of useful household applications.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13223396/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"In front of a trencher\" src=\"http://photos11.flickr.com/13223396_93a33f2f91_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13223317/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"Mark in front of a trencher\" src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/13223317_854802ff36_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13223196/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"The trencher alone\" src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/13223196_386e4b1887_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13223066/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"Trencher\" src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/13223066_21a49b9380_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13222943/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"Down the barrel of the gun\" src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/13222943_c3806a3174_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/13222810/\"><img width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Rusty trencher\" src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/13222810_4548c8fe9c_m.jpg\" /></a>','Hold on, I have a tool for that.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','giant-chainsaw','','','2006-02-15 09:46:00','2006-02-15 14:46:00','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/hold-on-i-have-a-tool-for-that/',0,'','',0),
	(193,1,'2005-05-21 11:31:30','2005-05-21 16:31:30','<p style=\"float:left;margin: 0 10px 0 0;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/11256976/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/11256976_fbf5e23d46_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"164\" alt=\"toilet paper on the wall\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Back in tenth grade of high school I went on a trip with my high school to Madrid, Spain and Paris, France.  It was a great trip and I still have contact with several of the people that I was on that trip with.  Many of them I see on a regular basis (whether or not it has anything to do with the trip).  Worthless reminiscing aside, there were 36 students on the trip total, 6 of which were guys.  Pretty sweet odds, although I was far too nerdy back then (back then?). When we got to the hotel in Madrid, we were given two rooms for guys.  We split up into two groups of three.  The first group went to their room.  The view was amazing.  You could see the entire city from that room.  So I went over to my room and opened our windows and only found a wall.  The wall you see in the picture next door.</p>\r\n<p>There were four walls and a pit at the center.  In the bottom of the pit was an enormous air conditioning unit.  We were a little bit disparaged, but as they say, \"when the world gives you lemons... you throw them as hard as you can at the air conditioning unit at the bottom of the pit outside of your hotel room.\"  Actually, we threw way more than that down there that week.  Oranges and apples and ashtrays.  Each time they would hit the unit and make a terrible bang and you would here people open the other windows up and down the pit and scream at us in various languages.</p>\r\n<p>The most fun thing that we threw out the window was wads of toilet paper that had been soaked in water.  They hit the wall and explode, then they would peel from the wall and fall to the bottom of the gourge and strike the air conditioner.</p>\r\n<p>There\'s not a man on earth that hasn\'t done this.  Its almost a guarentee if you ask a guy what you do with toilet paper in a junior high bathroom, he\'ll say soak it in water and throw it at a wall.  I mentioned toilet paper to Michael the day i told the Spain story to Trish and the first thing he asked was, \"did you ever soak it in water and throw it against a wall?\"  Try it, it\'s really fun and you\'ll laugh so hard you\'ll be glad you\'re already in the bathroom.</p>\r\n<p>As for the wall in Madrid, I\'d love to go back there one day and see if the air conditioner is stil dented and the toilet paper is still stuck to the wall.</p>','The other great use for toilet paper.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-other-great-use-for-toilet-paper','','','2005-05-21 11:32:01','2005-05-21 16:32:01','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-other-great-use-for-toilet-paper/',0,'','',2),
	(194,1,'2004-04-30 15:03:46','2004-04-30 20:03:46','<p>I have previously created a few VR applications in both <a href=\"http://www.apple.com/quicktime/\">Quicktime</a> and in <a href=\"http://www.macromedia.com/software/flash/\">Flash</a>. I think they are cool but I have never had a real application for them. No reason to really do them for real (really). I did one of the <a href=\"http://www.fi.edu/tfi/info/fels.html\">Fels Planeterium at the Franklin Institute</a> and one of the outside of hall in front of <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/library/\">the library and my office at DCCC</a>. You can <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/things/vr/\">take a look at both of them</a> on the same page.</p>\r\n<p>Regardless of this fact I read a blog by <a href=\"http://www.1976design.com/blog/\">a guy named Dunstan</a> in England. I am fond of his photography and his design. But I stole this idea from an entry he did a few weeks back. <a href=\"http://www.1976design.com/blog/archive/2004/04/01/home-photos/\">He made a panorama of his bedroom</a>. I have done the same with <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15404822/\">my room</a>.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15404822/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos14.flickr.com/15404822_474ffd397a.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"192\" alt=\"panorooma\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Take special notice of these things.  They are my favorite things in the room</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>computer with two monitors</li>\r\n<li>bull skull</li>\r\n<li>the abomidable snowman</li>\r\n<li>collection of simpsons toys</li>\r\n<li>gas mask</li>\r\n<li>cowboy hats</li>\r\n<li>clay sphinx</li>\r\n<li>British Airways rug</li>\r\n<li>my boots</li>\r\n<li>The map with pins to mark places I\'ve been</li>\r\n</ul>','A peek inside my life...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-peek-inside-my-life','','','2005-05-23 23:12:33','2005-05-24 04:12:33','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/a-peek-inside-my-life/',0,'','',0),
	(195,1,'2005-05-24 22:00:38','2005-05-25 03:00:38','http://www.davidsanger.com/stock/facial-hair.html\r\nhttp://explorers.whyte.com/presbeards.htm\r\nhttp://www.melvindurai.com/facialhair.htm\r\nhttp://ifoughtthelaw.cementhorizon.com/archives/000538.html\r\n\r\n','facial hair club',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','facial-hair-club','','','2005-05-24 22:00:38','2005-05-25 03:00:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/facial-hair-club/',0,'','',0),
	(196,1,'2005-05-24 22:51:09','2005-05-25 03:51:09','<p>If you are like me, you hate adobe acrobat.  PDF\'s are such a flaming hassle that when you see one, you don\'t even want to deal with it.  I would rather just not read some important information than load Acrobat to view a PDF.  It is widely accepted that a two page PDF can bring a quad-processor 20,000 ghz computer with 4,000,000 megs of RAM and a 256,000 meg video card to its knees in seconds and leave it begging for it\'s Mommy.</p>\r\n<p>I recently installed this firefox extension called <a href=\"http://www.rabotat.org/firefox.html\">PDF Download</a>.  When you are cruising along the internet and you inadvertantly click a link to a PDF, PDF Download prompts you, do you want to open in a new tab, download to the desktop or cancel.  This way you can go on with your day rather than spend the rest of time waiting to regain control of your browser all the while contemplating how awesome Chinese water torture must feel.</p>\r\n<p>All that said, although we have made a very valiant effort to eliminate PDF from the college website altogether, we have been forced to use it in some instances.  I recently downloaded acrobat reader 7.  What a difference.  Load time is down significantly.  Seriously like Captain quick launch. It\'s nearly immediate, with no splash screen. They still haven\'t done anything about the entire document being redrawn every time you move the document though so it will still lame your computer.  You\'ll just have to wait less time for the laming.</p>','An acceptable upgrade to a piece of crap.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','an-acceptable-upgrade-to-a-piece-of-crap','','','2005-05-24 22:52:01','2005-05-25 03:52:01','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/an-acceptable-upgrade-to-a-piece-of-crap/',0,'','',2),
	(197,1,'2004-05-24 14:04:21','2004-05-24 19:04:21','<p>I dropped Trish off at the airport at 5:30 this morning. She\'s on her way to <a href=\"http://www.ambergriscaye.com/pages/town/facts.html\">Belize</a> for two weeks. She is <a href=\"http://learn.dccc.edu/~saquilan/belize03.html\">taking a class</a> down there. I sure am proud of her for venturing off into the jungle for two weeks by herself but I sure will miss her. No phones. No communication with home. </p>\r\n<p><em>...Sniffle...</em></p>\r\n<p>She\'ll be <a href=\"http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap001127.html\">somewhere</a> out there tonight. I\'ll be thinking about her.</p>\r\n\r\n','Patricia-less',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','patricia-less','','','2005-05-24 22:53:59','2005-05-25 03:53:59','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/patricia-less/',0,'','',0),
	(198,1,'2004-06-06 21:19:32','2004-06-07 02:19:32','<p>Trish arrives at 11:13 tonight <a href=\"http://www.timmyfury.com/history/patricialess/\">from Belize</a>. There is a pit in my stomach that makes me feel like I am on the <a href=\"http://pws.chartermi.net/%7Ecsai/models/gravitron.html\">Gravitron</a> at the greatest carnival on earth. Until 7:00 tonight, it had been thirteen days since the last time I have talked to her. I am nervous to see her. Nervous like I haven\'t been since I first fell in love with her. I have missed her so much. I am glad she went away and I didn\'t have any contact with her though. When someone is gone you really learn how much you love them. You really learn what it means to miss someone. </p>\r\n<p>It\'s amazing the things that you miss. Those pokes in the side as you are driving. The incorrectly worded clich&eacute;s (&quot;Wallow in your pities&quot;). Those times when she says something really bizzarre that doesn\'t really make sense and isn\'t really appropriate for the situation, you both stop and look at each other and she\'s all, &quot;shut up&quot; (Oh no! My pink frilly). It\'s been thirteen days since I\'ve kissed her or hugged her or told her I love her. She\'s in big trouble when she gets off that plane. I\'ma get her.</p>\r\n','She\'s back! She\'s back!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','shes-back-shes-back','','','2005-05-24 22:59:00','2005-05-25 03:59:00','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/shes-back-shes-back/',0,'','',1),
	(199,1,'2004-03-22 21:26:01','2004-03-23 02:26:01','<p>So I was walking around my house tonight making suction cup noises with my mouth as I walked. I thought it was really funny. I mean imagine if I had suction   cups on my feet. It would obviously rule. You could totally walk up walls and   pick things up without bending over. I mean some people can already do this   but I mean you could do it without being called awful names like \"Crazy Long toe McGee\" or \"Finger Foot\". </p>\r\n<p>Then this made me think back to the good old days. Back when my house was rockin\' an <a href=\"http://members.chello.at/theodor.lauppert/computer/ps2/9556.htm\">IBM   PS/2 486</a>. Man did we rule. We bought this shareware game, called \"<a href=\"http://www.3drealms.com/cosmo/\">Cosmo\'s Cosmic Adventures.</a>\" Circa March 1992. I loved that game. In fact I loved it so much that I still have it. It originally came on one 3.5\" floppy and took like 3 minutes to load. That was on <a href=\"http://www.logicalsky.com/Windows31_FAQ.htm\">windows3.1</a>. Now I have moved up in the world and I have me this fancy pentium2.3ghz with close to a gig of RAM driving around with a full load of software on Windows XP Pro. Only took me three days to install on this machine and close to 25 minutes to get the damn thing running but man is this sweet.</p>\r\n<p>Look at this guy. It would rule. You could drink as much as you want and never drop your glass. You could climb buildings and shit. You would rule the window   washing business. I do suppose there would be downfalls though. There\'s no way in hell you could manage driving without some sort of special apparatus. Changing   your spark plugs may be difficult. Certainly you would have extreme trouble with your girlfriend\'s extra-curriculars. Although I suppose it would make a <a href=\"http://www.cloudforest-mexico.org/183.htm\">serious penis enlargement system</a>. It could also make a great portable cereal bowl. But not at the   same time I suppose.</p>\r\n<p>To sum up what I am trying to say, giant suction cups have benefits and fallbacks just like hands do.</p>\r\n<p>On a completely seperate note, Like two years ago when I did a search for Cosmo there was nothing. Now there is like a damned <a href=\"http://www.rds-celle.de/cosmofansite/\">fan club</a>(\"Please notice: My English is not perfect and this site is a project in its early state. There might be a lot of mistakes or broken links.\"). There are <a href=\"http://home.online.no/%7Ep-olstad/apogee/cosmo.html\">extra levels</a> now. There are <a href=\"http://www.student.tue.nl/u/a.f.smeijers/sfp/fram/cosmo.htm\">cheat codes</a>.You should seriously go to the <a href=\"http://www.3drealms.com/cosmo/\">Cosmo site</a> and download the shareware vesion of the game. Here\'s a <a href=\"http://personalwebs.oakland.edu/%7Elcmatero/cosmo/\">synopsis of the game</a>(I stole that picture from this guy). In <a href=\"http://www.masagames.f2s.com/cheats/cosmo.php\">Russian</a>.<a href=\"http://cheaty.idnes.cz/c/cosmoscosmicadventure.html\">Czech</a>.<a href=\"http://www.lexigame.de/de/system/cosmo.htm\">German</a>.<a href=\"http://www.portan.co.il/oldies4ever/game1.asp?code=470\">Arabic</a>.<a href=\"http://digilander.libero.it/pccheats/cosmoscosmicadventure.html\">Italian</a>.<a href=\"http://www.gamersnet.nl/cheats/cheat.php3?id=565\">Dutch</a>.<a href=\"http://www.ddj.com.br/dicas/dicas.php?jogo=891\">Brazilian</a>. Everybody loves Cosmo. Okay I\'m done.</p>\r\n','Everybody loves Cosmo',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','everybody-loves-cosmo','','','2005-05-24 23:04:55','2005-05-25 04:04:55','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/everybody-loves-cosmo/',0,'','',2),
	(200,1,'2004-03-25 21:31:54','2004-03-26 02:31:54','<p>I talked to my dad last night for 27 minutes and 43 seconds.  I know this because he informed me.  You would have to know my father to really understand that thats probably a calculation he did in his head.  You see my father is a robot.</p>\r\n<p>It\'s nice to talk to him now and then during the week cause <a href=\"http://www.qualitydistribution.com/\">his job</a> keeps him away most weeks and I only get to see him on the weekend.  He\'s great to talk to though.  He always has good insight for me on things and unlike me he gets to see the country, at least the northeastern part of it.</p>\r\n<p>I\'m rambling again.  I went up to <a href=\"http://www.weirdhead.org/\">my sister\'s</a> room and I found her pushing a box from <a href=\"http://www.buildabear.com/\">build a bear</a> across the floor towards her bed.</p>\r\n<p>The box was closed and I say, \"Hey Marisa, whats in the box.\"</p>\r\n<p>\"Cat,\" she responds.</p>\r\n<p>Sure enough I look in that box and there\'s the cat.  Now if you met Marisa you would be enchanted by her charm.  She\'s incredible, nicer than anyone you have ever met in your life.  But to be honest she is in less the peak physical condition.  She has several physical ailments which make it hard for her to manuever without a helping hand.</p>\r\n<p>How the hell did she manage to stuff this poor cat into this box?</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12858417/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos11.flickr.com/12858417_ae04d39871_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"Given a fighting chance\" /></a> <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/12858280/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/12858280_d4e0abf66e_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"Marisa looks on\" /></a></p>','Cat in a box!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','cat-in-a-box','','','2005-05-24 23:15:56','2005-05-25 04:15:56','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/cat-in-a-box/',0,'','',0),
	(201,1,'2004-05-27 10:03:38','2004-05-27 15:03:38','<p>I have been on <a href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/wordoftheday/.\">Dictionary.com\'s word of the day email list</a> for about eight months now. I don\'t go to extra lengths to memorize the word I am sent everyday but I occasionally pick them up and stuff them in my daily vocabulary sachel. I was reading through them the other day and I thought that I should offer you all a list of my 10 favorites.</p>\r\n<dl>\r\n<dt>troglodyte</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\n1. A  member of a primitive people that lived in caves, dens, or holes; a cave dweller.<br />\r\n2. One who is regarded as reclusive, reactionary, out of date, or brutish.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>hullabaloo</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nA confused noise; uproar; tumult.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>ken</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\n1. Perception; understanding; knowledge.<br />\r\n2. The range of vision.<br />\r\n3. View; sight.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>flibbertigibbet</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nA  silly, flighty, or scatterbrained person, especially a pert young woman with such qualities.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>defenestrate</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nTo throw out of a window.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>crabwise</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\n1. Sideways.<br />\r\n2. In a cautiously indirect manner.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>bailiwick</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nA person\'s specific area of knowledge, authority, interest, skill, or work.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>abecedarian</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nOne who is learning the alphabet; hence, a beginner. One engaged in teaching the alphabet.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>malapropism</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\nThe   usually  unintentionally  humorous  misuse  of  a  word, especially  by  confusion  \r\nwith one of similar sound; also, anexample of such misuse.\r\n</dd>\r\n<dt>neologism</dt>\r\n<dd>\r\n1. A new word or expression.<br />\r\n2. A new use of a word or expression.<br />\r\n3. The use or creation of new words or expressions.<br />\r\n4. (Psychiatry) An invented, meaningless word used by a person with a psychiatric disorder.<br />\r\n5. (Theology) A new view or interpretation of a scripture.\r\n</dd>\r\n</dl>\r\n<p>All of these definitions are courtesy of <a href=\"http://dictionary.reference.com/\">dictionary.com</a> I visit there alot and like I said, I get email from them everyday.</p>\r\n<p>So I had this entry written like three days ago based entirely on what was in my inbox. Then this morning I was reading <a href=\"http://www.robotjohnny.com/\">RobotJohnny</a> and the guy had <a href=\"http://www.robotjohnny.com/archives/2004/05/mind_your_langu.php\">already done</a> this sort of entry. Well not really but close. He did have a good link to an article about a <a href=\"http://cnn.netscape.cnn.com/news/package.jsp?name=fte/favoriteword/favoriteword\">survey done by Merriam-Webster about favorite words</a>.  I had two that were the same.</p>\r\n<p>see also: <a href=\"http://www.robotjohnny.com/archives/2003/08/language_is_che.php\">dasypygal</a> </p>','A few good words...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-few-good-words','','','2006-03-08 18:56:34','2006-03-08 23:56:34','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/a-few-good-words/',0,'','',0),
	(202,1,'2005-06-27 11:52:50','2005-06-27 16:52:50','<p>There has been alot of hype about blogs in the news over the last year or so.  There has been some very much deserved  credibility given to blogs in the news and on TV.  Some very \"famous\" bloggers are making some very good money and receiving notoriety for their opinions and their work.  Problem is that with the fame and fortune of some many others have tried to jump on the wagon.  The effect is that since applications such as Blogger and livejournal have made it so easy to voice your opinion, every seems to think that now their opinion matters.  We all know that this is not true.  Every opinion does not matter.  I\'m not saying that opinions which differ from mine are worthless.  This is not a commentary in the guise of telling you how enormous my ego is.  I\'m saying that opinions which have no backing arguments or opinions which are not thought out are worthless.  People who cannot back up what they say, people who don\'t know what they are talking about, people who give up on their opinion when you offer just a few measley reasons why they are wrong and don\'t try to defend their stance should stop having opinions.  People who cannot accept their opinions being criticized should not display them in a public forum.  (Steps off soap box and continues with entry)</p>\r\n<p>My point is that although every person <em>can</em> have a place to display their thoughts and opinions into the public forum, not every example of this is the same.  I feel that the label \"blog\" is too freely placed on every single person\'s online presence regardless of what content is contained there.  There is a classification that I feel should be established so when I hear someone talk about their online presence, I know exactly what the nature of their presence is.</p>\r\n<dl>\r\n<dt></dt>\r\n<dt></dt>\r\n<dt>blog</dt>\r\n</dl>\r\n<p>I will now attempt to introduce a new term.  A new classification for  \r\n<dl>\r\n<dt>POP</dt>\r\n<dd>Personal Online Publication</dd>\r\n</dl></p>','The internet hierarchy of public forum',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','pop-personal-online-publication','','','2005-06-27 13:03:18','2005-06-27 18:03:18','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/pop-personal-online-publication/',0,'','',0),
	(203,1,'2003-11-17 07:42:27','2003-11-17 12:42:27','<p style=\"float:left;margin: 0 10px 5px 0;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15613888/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos11.flickr.com/15613888_f1b29d4432_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"pfk3\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>About three months ago I posted a picture that my dad had sent me from a bussiness trip that he was on in Quebec, Ontario. It\'s right here. A picture of a Kentucky   Fried Chicken sign. Instead of KFC its called PFK (Poulet frit Kentucky). It appears to be the only place on earth where the restaurant\'s moniker is in <a href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/news/indepth/language/\">a foreign language</a>. I was looking for what PFK actually stood for and although   I mean what the acronym itself stands for I found out what KFC aka PFK does stand for. They stand for chicken addiction. It turns out that there is a chemical additive in KFC that makes their chicken irresistable. Thats pretty sweet. I need to inject some of that shit into my web design skills. Then maybe I could get a fucking job.</p>\r\n<p>Then there is this site which is apparently run by retards. The title is funny though, \"<a href=\"http://www.kfccruelty.com/\">Kentucky Fried Chicken does chickens wrong</a>.\" I mean seriously, come on people, do you really love chickens that much that you would devote that much of your time and money to saving them?  Go ahead, try to deny that they are deliscious. I dare you. What a dumb thing to devote a website to. For all those of you that are thinking the same thing about me, SHUT UP!</p>\r\n<p>Okay so I went and saw <em>ELF </em>yesterday. Very funny. But here\'s the reason I\'m telling you this. <em>Brother bear</em> and <em>Looney Tunes: Back in Action</em> are also playing. So the movie theater reeked of children. I had gas (for something new right?). I found a new really funny game to play. Eat a bunch of foods that give you gas. Then go somewhere thats mobbed with children. Then... I bet you saw this coming... fart... alot. They are all right at ass level and they get slapped in the face by your ass. It\'s fucking great. Try it. No really, try it, it\'s fun.</p>\r\n','Poulet frit Kentucky: Nous faisons le francais de poulet',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','poulet-frit-kentucky-nous-faisons-le-francais-de-poulet','','','2005-05-25 07:12:10','2005-05-25 12:12:10','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/poulet-frit-kentucky-nous-faisons-le-francais-de-poulet/',0,'','',0),
	(204,1,'2004-04-20 22:41:59','2004-04-21 03:41:59','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15613492/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/15613492_956bc04ab3.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"bigtrashpile\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>It is now 10:33pm. All is quiet in Collingdale. Everyone is in bed in my house and here I sit, procrastinating when I should be doing stat homework. The cat mills around my room looking for something to entertain himself with. A train whistle wails in the distance. Huh? What could that rattling-banging-breaking noise outside be? I believe Jim Bob and Clara Sue are back for their third trip on this street. It\'s like a goldmine.</p>\r\n<p>My brother fondly calls it \"Collingdale Christmas.\" Yes children it\'s that time of year again. Bulk trash pickup is here again. The day of bulk trash pick up isn\'t the fun part. The extra fun time is the evening and the night before.</p>\r\n<p>All evening people have been cruising the 6th precinct looking through each others big rubbish and hauling it to their houses to become there own big rubbish. It\'s entertaining really. It\'s really the only time of the year that you can watch all the hicks in your town fight over each others trash.</p>\r\n<p>Collingdale Christmas, damn that\'s funny.</p>','The most wonderful time of the year!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-most-wonderful-time-of-the-year','','','2005-05-25 07:15:25','2005-05-25 12:15:25','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/the-most-wonderful-time-of-the-year/',0,'','',2),
	(205,1,'2004-05-03 00:15:39','2004-05-03 05:15:39','<p style=\"float:right;margin: 0 0 5px 10px;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15613575/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos13.flickr.com/15613575_c0f2166d78_o.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"401\" alt=\"wawabusinessmodel\" /></a>\r\n</p><p>As all of you know I am obsessed with <a href=\"http://www.wawa.com/\">Wawa</a>. I drink at least two cups of Wawa coffee everyday and only buy Wawa gas. It has recently come to my attention that they are building three Wawa\'s within reach of my normal trek to and from work and to and from Trish\'s house in West Grove. This is good news for me due to my aforementioned obsession. regardless I am curious of what the Wawa business model looks like. I offer my illustration.</p>\r\n','What is Wawa up to?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','what-is-wawa-up-to','','','2005-05-25 07:18:03','2005-05-25 12:18:03','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/what-is-wawa-up-to/',0,'','',0),
	(206,1,'2004-05-25 11:40:43','2004-05-25 16:40:43','<p style=\"float:left;margin:0 5px 10px 0;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10339487/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/10339487_dbbb79d47d_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" alt=\"underworld concert\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>I have pretty much listened to nothing but <a href=\"http://www.dirty.org/underworld/\">Underworld</a> for about three weeks. I really don\'t think I will ever get bored of them. For those of you who have never heard of them, they are close to my favorite band. They make the most amazing, emotion inspiring music you have ever heard. (Just short of the <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B00005BJ2O/002-9615771-0650406\"> Moulin rouge soundtrack</a>, eh Mark?) Don, Jenny, Trish and I went to see them in New York City almost two years ago and it was the most amazing show. It was even better than <a href=\"http://www.u2.com/lite/\">U2\'s Popmart tour</a>. The fucking show just built and built for nearly two hours until they played <em>Born Slippy</em> and the whoop drops and its all <em>dent,dent,dent,dent... dent,dent,dent,dent... boh,boh...</em> Gives me chills just thinking about it. I danced my arse off that night and still get mocked occasionally for looking like a doof when I dance. Here was the playlist for the night.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Skyscraper</li>\r\n<li>Cowgirl / Rez</li>\r\n<li>Two Months Off</li>\r\n<li>Dinosaur Adventure 3d</li>\r\n<li>Twist</li>\r\n<li>Dirty Epic</li>\r\n<li>Mo Move</li>\r\n<li>Dark Train</li>\r\n<li>Improvisation</li>\r\n<li>Jumbo</li>\r\n<li>Born Slippy NUXX</li>\r\n<li>Push Upstairs</li>\r\n<li>Pearl\'s Girl</li>\r\n<li>Moaner</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>If you have not had the pleasure of hearing Underworld perhaps you will instant message me (MyMouthIsAToilet or TimmyFury on AIM) and I will share with you.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><strong>...knock...knock...knock...</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Who is it?</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Let us in we\'ve read your website and I think we have some things to discuss with you.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Oh god no, Jahovah\'s witnesses!</em></p>\r\n<p><em>No sir, it\'s worse than that.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>The RIAA?</em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"float:right;margin:0 0 5px 10px\";><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/10339476/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos6.flickr.com/10339476_f0d8b5d573_m.jpg\" width=\"180\" height=\"240\" alt=\"underworld concert\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>The last thing they release was <em><a href=\"http://www.dmcworld.com/backtomine/underworld.asp\">Back to mine</a></em>, a remix album. There is perhaps will be some new material on a <a href=\"http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story?id=5936100\">DJ Sasha compilation</a>.  I am dying to have some new Underworld to listen to.  I would love to go see them again too. Check them out.  They are freaking good.</p>\r\n<p>The pictures of the concert itself are not mine. The only reason I have them is because they were so good and I wanted them for memories sake. I put them here at risk of retribution from the blogging gods. I couldn\'t help myself though. Go see the <a href=\"http://sullen.org/gallery/underworld\">entire gallery</a>. I think that the site is run by a girl named <a href=\"http://sullen.org/\">Aimee at Sullen.org</a>. These pictures can also be viewed on the <a href=\"http://www.dirty.org/underworld/reviews/2002_newyork.htm\">review of the concert at Hammerstein Ballroom</a>.</p>\r\n','Underworld in New York',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','underworld-in-new-york','','','2005-05-25 07:23:12','2005-05-25 12:23:12','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/underworld-in-new-york/',0,'','',0),
	(207,1,'2004-05-26 16:51:00','2004-05-26 21:51:00','<p style=\"float:left;margin:0 10px 5px 0;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15686862/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos13.flickr.com/15686862_d88ca29623_m.jpg\" width=\"234\" height=\"240\" alt=\"First Haircut\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Every Friday morning I get up at the buttcrack of dawn and drag myself over to the barber shop to get my haircut. The same guy has been cutting my hair since my first haircut almost twenty-two years ago. </p>\r\n<p>Regardless of this fact, every once in awhile someone who I work with will say, &quot;You got a haircut.&quot; They don\'t say, &quot;Did you get your haircut?&quot; They say it like &quot;You [finally] got a haircut.&quot; As if I don\'t get one every single friday. The weirdest part about it is it\'s not on Friday when my head is still moist from the morning dew. They\'ll say it on a Wednesday afternoon, a mere five plus days after my haircut.</p>\r\n','Noticing haircuts.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','noticing-haircuts','','','2005-05-25 17:31:27','2005-05-25 22:31:27','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/207/',0,'','',2),
	(208,1,'2004-06-29 10:52:44','2004-06-29 15:52:44','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/8033327/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos7.flickr.com/8033327_866302bd32.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"Sandals\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Back again. Nine days since my last update. Seems to me that I actually have like seven people that read my site. Amazing really. I really enjoyed Mark\'s attempt to excuse me for no updates. Although my real life for the days prior really just consisted of coffee at Wawa, studying for my accounting final, getting ready for St.Thomas and <a href=\"http://www.nick.com/games/nick_games/spongebob/sb_collapse.jhtml\">Spongebob Collapse</a>. I am also agonizing over a few ideas that I have for a new design for the site. I know I redesign like once every four months and I know I probably said that the next redesign wouldn\'t be for a while but I have ideas and besides that the orange is making me want to kill. Regardless, I am offended by the anonymous comment about Bush telling the truth more frequently than I update. The last time Bush told the truth was like three months ago. </p>\r\n<p>St. Thomas was fucking awesome. I have about 2,000 things to write about St.Thomas and non-St. Thomas related matters so check back a bunch in the next few days. In addition I will be setting up some galleries once I get my pictures developed and scan them. Check back.</p>\r\n','Welcome back!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','welcome-back','','','2005-05-25 17:34:30','2005-05-25 22:34:30','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/welcome-back/',0,'','',0),
	(209,1,'2004-06-01 18:33:54','2004-06-01 23:33:54','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15613460/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos13.flickr.com/15613460_de9083d2ba.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"Foam Darts\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Jarrod, Mark, Geoff, Michelle and I were rolling around yesterday in my parents van (the beast) because my driverside window is broken. Gets fixed tomorrow hopefully and all will be well. Thats not why I write though. We went to one shopping center and spent four hours there. How I don\'t know, but four hours none the less. Three stores. The third of which was the best. This new store is called <a href=\"http://www.fivebelow.com/\">fiVeBELoW</a>. I swear to you that whent hey were building it Trish and I suspected that it could be a nice restaurant or something. Nope. Been wrong before, I\'ll be wrong again. It\'s like a dollar store but not. It\'s easily the greatest store ever. Tons of candy. Tons of cheap toys. A <a href=\"http://www.arcadegames.com/ctgy/CocktailTableGame/prod/classic020\">table top Pac-Man</a>. Here\'s what they say...</p>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://www.fivebelow.com/aboutFiveBelow.html\">\r\n<p>Five Below is a new retail concept positioned to become the leading extreme-value retailer to the teen market and beyond. Five Below offers thousands of trend-right products for teens, as well as pre-teens and other value-minded consumers, all of which are priced from $1.00 to $5.00.  <em>source: <a href=\"http://www.fivebelow.com/aboutFiveBelow.html\">About Five Below</a></em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>The greatest thing that we got there was <a href=\"http://www.fundexgames.com/products/?c=22&amp;g=710\">these foam darts</a>.There\'s a thick rubber band through them.  You put your finger through a loop at the end of one of the rubber bands and pull it back like a slingshot.  They fly like mad.  They were two for a dollarat fiVeBELoW.  I bought four and it was the best two dollars I have ever spent.  We used them for like 5 hours total yesterday.  Get some of them.  You won\'t regret it. </p>\r\n','Five years old again...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','five-years-old-again','','','2005-05-25 17:36:15','2005-05-25 22:36:15','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/five-years-old-again/',0,'','',0),
	(210,1,'2005-05-25 20:18:38','2005-05-26 01:18:38','http://37signals.com/svn/archives2/tips_for_getting_good_customer_support.php\r\n\r\nlook for the presentation from libraries in computers.','Learn to receive help',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','learn-to-receive-help','','','2005-05-25 20:18:38','2005-05-26 01:18:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/learn-to-receive-help/',0,'','',0),
	(211,1,'2004-04-23 12:38:46','2004-04-23 17:38:46','<p>Hey ya\'ll, I have just soft launched my newest design.  I call it Iteration Four: Two Gradient Column Watoosy.</p>\r\n<p>Everything is theoretically functional but you never do know do you.  I am working out some bugs in the administrative pages that I have running.  In addition there are a bunch of things missing that need to be here.</p>\r\n<p>I have a ton of ideas for expansion and this new design lets me do that without shitting up the structure of the page.</p>\r\n<p>Notice that I have added a section on the menu called \"Meanderings.\"  This is where I will post the pages that I visit that I think you should see.  Then there is the \"Recent Comments\" section of the menu which will allows you to see if there are any comments that you haven\'t seen.</p>\r\n<p>Let me know what you think.</p>\r\n','World Release - Iteration Four: Two Gradient Column Watoosy',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','worldreleasetfi4','','','2005-05-25 20:45:23','2005-05-26 01:45:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/world-release-iteration-four-two-gradient-column-watoosy/',0,'','',0),
	(212,1,'2004-07-09 20:34:51','2004-07-10 01:34:51','First I would like to preface this by saying that parasailing is alot of fun. I mean don\'t get me wrong regardless of what I tell you here, parasailing is wonderful. Just look at the view in these pictures taken by Jarrod and Michelle while they were up there.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15709877/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"160\" alt=\"Family Jewels\" src=\"http://photos12.flickr.com/15709877_09bac22e1c_m.jpg\" /></a> <a title=\"Photo Sharing\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/15709870/\"><img width=\"240\" height=\"160\" alt=\"Dipped\" src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/15709870_04c101e395_m.jpg\" /></a>\r\n\r\nLet me also preface this by saying that I am certainly not the most coordinated or sports oriented person you will ever meet. So, Trish and I strap into the harnesses as Debbie and Jonathon are up in the air, oh I don\'t know... 600 feet? When they come in, Trish and I move to the back of the boat and the two of us are hooked up to the parachute. They tell us when and we shoot up. As soon as we get in the air we both fly forward and were hanging upside down. As we right ourselves, I can hear the other four in the boat laughing their asses off. The guys driving the boat dip us in the water because at this point I am just hanging in my harness. You can see this in the picture here.\r\n\r\n<img name=\"parasailingtimmytrish02cut.jpg\" />\r\n\r\nBack in my harness they zip us up into the wild blue yonder. It was one of the most awesome experiences. You are just floating there, 600 feet up. It\'s amazing. It\'s peaceful. It\'s humiliating when you slide out of your harness and the straps around your legs pull up and start strangling your wedding tackle. Which I did. Now at 600 feet I am just hanging from the harness laughing and in pain. Trish starts to try to kick me in the \"ding-ding.\" This happened about half way through the ride so I stayed up there like that a good 6-7 minutes.\r\n\r\nThey brought us back in for another dip in the water to fix the harness so I can get back on the boat. What a flight. I\'m sure these lovely pictures will cause me years of humiliation.','Parasailing Retard',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','parasailing-retard','','','2006-02-15 09:48:17','2006-02-15 14:48:17','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/212/',0,'','',0),
	(213,1,'2005-05-25 21:48:24','2005-05-26 02:48:24','<p>Tonight I finished putting what archives I still had from timmyfury.com on this site.  If you look at the history page of the site, you will notice that the very first entry was on May 26, 2003.  That makes today my two year anniversary.  I have been blogging for two years.  Timmyfury was around for longer than that, but the entry which I have named as the official start of my blogging days was the first one ever stored in a database and the first entry that ever offered comments.  Way back when I was first starting to learn how to program.  So go back and read some of the archives, particularly the archives in the timmyfury category.  They are recently added from the old blog, for nostalgia sake.  It\'s interesting to see how my writing style has changed (and improved i think) and how the topics I wrote about changed and how frequently I write changed.</p>\r\n<p>For those of you who have been reading since back in the days of bad animation thanks for sticking around and humoring me for this long.  For those of you who I have never met, thanks for reading, you make my ego bigger everytime I see a comment or referer I\'ve never seen before.</p>','Happy anniversary to blogging',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','happy-anniversary','','','2005-05-25 21:48:38','2005-05-26 02:48:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/happy-anniversary/',0,'','',3),
	(214,1,'2005-05-31 21:34:41','2005-06-01 02:34:41','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/16693167/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos10.flickr.com/16693167_c9ee8e21c1.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"Goons in a sombrero\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>This weekend we took a trip to Fayetteville, NC to visit Code and Crissy.  Nearly 1000 miles of driving and a court summons in Virginia later, we return with more fireworks then any three idiots should ever have in their possesion.  There are pictures abound. <del>Trish and Michelle still have to upload and name theirs and when they do I\'ll add a link to them so y\'all can check \'em out.</del>  <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/400721/\">Here are mine</a>. <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/sunflowerseed/sets/404497/\">Here are Trish\'s</a> and <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/bratacious/sets/413626/\">here are Michelle\'s</a>.</p>','Someone\'s gonna lose a finger!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','someones-gonna-lose-a-finger','','','2005-06-14 00:10:13','2005-06-14 05:10:13','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/someones-gonna-lose-a-finger/',0,'','',0),
	(215,1,'2005-06-04 13:18:39','2005-06-04 18:18:39','<p>Although I am not quite ready to shave them off, I felt that I should share with you my latest creation.  They are in fact the bushiest sideburns that have ever graced my face and they come in two styles...</p>\r\n<h3>modest</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/17424935/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos9.flickr.com/17424935_f8b603219c.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" alt=\"modest\" /></a></p>\r\n<h3>extra fancy</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/17424936/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos13.flickr.com/17424936_37e737890f.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" alt=\"extra fancy\" /></a></p>\r\n<p>Sideburns this awesome and I don\'t even use <a href=\"http://perfectsideburns.com/prolook.mov\">perfect sideburns</a>.</p>','The bushiest sideburns that have ever graced my face.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-bushiest-sideburns-that-have-ever-graced-my-face','','','2005-06-04 13:18:51','2005-06-04 18:18:51','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/sideburns/',0,'','',1),
	(216,1,'2005-07-06 23:23:30','2005-07-07 04:23:30','<p>Mark calls it meatspace.  I think its funny.  That\'s where I\'ve been, meatspace.  My updates have not only been sporatic but a little non-sequitor over the last week or so.  For that I apologize (I think there are readers out there), but thats the story of life.  It\'s summer and it\'s beautiful.</p>\r\n<p>A few weeks ago <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/apartment-hunt-advice/\">I mentioned that Trish and I were searching for an apartment</a>.  Well we\'ve found one.  In preperation for the big move I have been preoccupied and have thought little about the blog.  Michael is on vacation renovating his new house.  So I am holding down the fort on my own.  Not that it takes much work to do. Furthermore, I am in process of working on a few projects which I am very excited about.  More on those later though.  I don\'t want to talk about them before I have made any significant progress.</p>\r\n<p>So the moral of my story is that meatspace is calling me.  I\'m enjoying my bike, my friends, my woman and my work.  I\'ve got alot going on right now and you\'ll all have to be patient over the next few weeks until life settles down to a nice slow pace again.</p>\r\n<p>For those who are interested in this sort of information, my brother\'s child collection has increased by one.  My new nephew was born at 23:00 last night.  Xavier Michael Crowe.  Healthy and with any luck a strong resemblance of his mother and not his father.  More info and a picture when it comes.</p>','Living in meatspace',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','living-in-meatspace','','','2005-07-06 23:24:38','2005-07-07 04:24:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/living-in-reality/',0,'','',0),
	(220,1,'2006-06-22 10:00:27','2006-06-22 15:00:27','<p>For those of you out there who suffer through your life with <acronym title=\"Nerd Attention Deficiency Disorder\">NADD</acronym>, you are probably all too aware of my struggle to aquire enough information to quench my thirst.  Occasionally I go on binges that would test the patience of the most understanding girlfriend, as I am lost to books and magazines and blogs.</p>\r\n<p>Feng shui is a term used to describe the arrangement of object in your space.  <a href=\"http://www.answers.com/?tname=feng-shui\"><cite>Answers</cite> defines feng shui</a> as <q>The Chinese art or practice of positioning objects, especially graves, buildings, and furniture, based on a belief in patterns of yin and yang and the flow of chi that have positive and negative effects</q>, though in the ever increasing bastardization of language, it can be applied to information as well.  I think of the feng shui of information sources as the reliance on a variety devices and sources for aquiring the information you need to survive.</p>\r\n<p>I wrote before that I\'m always searching for <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2004/11/alternate-information-sources/\">alternative information sources</a>.  The key is to vary it and make it worth your while.  I\'ve trimmed my feed reader down to only the important ones.  The blogs or sites that give me the highest quality information.  I keep a few good magazines at the toilet.  I have recently started taking the train to work and I have been reading novels and technical manuals with a fury.</p>\r\n<p>The most important thing though is that you learn how to evaluate the information that you consume.  There is nothing worse than poor information gathering ability.  Information is increasingly easier to gain access to, although, at the same time, it becomes increasingly difficult to find.  Information literacy is quickly becoming one of the most important skills that a person can develop.</p>\r\n\r\n','Striving for feng shui of information sources.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-feng-shue-of-information-sources','','','2006-06-23 10:32:35','2006-06-23 15:32:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/06/the-feng-shue-of-information-sources/',0,'','',0),
	(218,1,'2005-06-01 18:28:32','2005-06-01 23:28:32','http://www.csmonitor.com/2005/0525/p11s02-lifp.html\r\n\r\nblocking the internet to save children from its horror...\r\n\r\nhttp://www.zephoria.org/thoughts/archives/2006/03/01/the_disappearan.html\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Nfyw2KYHWw','Won\'t somebody think of the children?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','wont-somebody-think-of-the-children','','','2006-04-01 13:42:23','2006-04-01 18:42:23','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/wont-somebody-think-of-the-children/',0,'','',0),
	(222,1,'2005-06-17 16:08:05','2005-06-17 21:08:05','<p>A few days ago <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/\">Mark</a> asked me to write a php script for him that would iterate through a directory and list all of the files for a project he is working on.  I enjoy exercises like this.  Makes me use my brain a bit and its good fun to practice with file and directory manipulation, something that doesn\'t get used very frequently in my world of add/modify/delete database apps.</p>\r\n<p>So the script just recursively trolls through the directory specified and dumps out a nested list of the file and folder structure.  Mark has modified it to output links to the files, which I invite him to post.  I have dropped my original script though.  Other improvements could be some classes with css to pretty up the output or group the items.  Also a function that would evaluate each file for MIME or even extension to set a class to display an ison with css would be special too.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s the code.  If you want to post some improvements to this feel free I would love to see it.</p>\r\n\r\n<code>\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;?php\r\n\r\n $directory = &quot;/the/directory/to/troll/&quot;;\r\n\r\n troll($directory);\r\n\r\n function troll($directory){\r\n  $handle = opendir($directory); \r\n  echo &quot;&lt;ul&gt;\\n&quot;; \r\n  while(false !== ($hit = readdir($handle))){ \r\n   if ($hit !== \'.\' &amp;&amp; $hit !== \'..\' &amp;&amp; is_dir($hit)){\r\n    echo &quot;&lt;li&gt;$hit\\n&quot;;\r\n    $new_directory = $directory.\'/\'.$hit;\r\n    jump_directory($new_directory);\r\n    echo &quot;&lt;/li&gt;\\n&quot;;\r\n  } elseif ($hit !== \'.\' &amp;&amp; $hit !== \'..\') {\r\n   echo &quot;&lt;li&gt;$hit&lt;/li&gt;\\n&quot;;\r\n  }\r\n }\r\n  echo &quot;\\n&quot;;\r\n}\r\n?&gt;\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</code>','Directory troller',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','directory-troller','','','2005-06-17 16:08:10','2005-06-17 21:08:10','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/directory-troller/',0,'','',3),
	(223,1,'2005-06-21 13:21:15','2005-06-21 18:21:15','<p>I posted <a href=\"http://wilcoworld.net/wired/\">this link</a> a few weeks ago.  Its a talk given by Jeff Tweedy and Lawrence Lessig called <em>Who Owns Culture</em> given at the New York Public Library.  Download it.  If you can\'t get a good seed message me and I will send it to you.  It\'s a good talk.  There are some visuals that I totally missed because I listened to it in the car but if you have time I\'m sure the video is good too.</p>\r\n<p>Regardless they make some great points and some wonderful discussion.  They discuss the fact that the movie industry and music industry and publishing industry have taken control of, or attempted to take control of creativity and culture at large.  They discuss how copyright is stiffling creativity. It\'s control is against the spirit of art where creativity builds on creativity and influences the future and the way people think and feel.</p>\r\n<p>I was just going to leave it as a link on the side, but then I heard a piece called <em><a href=\"http://www.autistici.com/petsounds.htm\">hippocamp ruins pet sounds</a></em>.  I was led to the project from who knows where and I downloaded the album.  It\'s the 25th anniversary tribute to the Beach Boys album <em>Pet Sounds</em>.  It\'s amazing.  I really enjoyed it.  A couple weeks later I saw <a href=\"http://downhillbattle.org/node/view/505>this post on downhill battle</a>.  Autistici was forced to take this work offline for copyright reasons.</p>\r\n<p>It was infuriating to me.  It\'s crap.  Why stiffle a work that, if you read the bit about it on the <a href=\"http://www.autistici.com/petsounds.htm\">autistici</a> page they are obviously paying tribute to and encouraging purchase of the album.  But they were forced to take it down.  This brings forward the rediculous nature of the beast.  The lack of forward thinking and the control of the greedy suits who control the industry.</p>\r\n<p>I liked the opinions of Lessig and Tweedy.  I think that technology will lead to a future more like the vision of these two forward thinkers.  Download <em><a href=\"http://wilcoworld.net/wired/\">Who Owns Culture</a></em>, download <em><a href=\"http://downhillbattle.org/node/view/505\">hippocamp ruins pet sounds</a></em>.  They are worth it and these two pieces together are really shine an enormous beacon on the problems in the copyright world.  Oh and if these downloads don\'t work I have both at home; contact me and I\'ll send them to you.</p>','Why do we let suits own us?',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','why-do-we-let-suits-own-us','','','2005-06-21 13:21:18','2005-06-21 18:21:18','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/thoughts-on-who-owns-culture/',0,'','',2),
	(224,1,'2005-06-14 00:10:51','2005-06-14 05:10:51','<p>A few weeks ago when we went to <a href=http://veryraw.com/history/2005/05/someones-gonna-lose-a-finger/\">South of the Border</a> we took a trip up into <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/16690617/in/set-400721/\">the big sombrero</a> there. As we came down in the elevator Michelle snapped picture after picture.  She put them into a set and I thought it was pretty rad.  So go to the <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/bratacious/sets/413653/show/\">slidshow</a> and set the speed to 1 second.  It\'s pretty cool how the pictures ended up looking like a stop motion film.</p>','Going down',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','going-down','','','2005-06-14 00:14:14','2005-06-14 05:14:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/going-down/',0,'','',2),
	(225,1,'2005-06-20 11:11:29','2005-06-20 16:11:29','<p>I don\'t know if this happens to anyone else.  It\'s been an issue for me all my life and I apologize for it ahead of time because this is perhaps too much information.</p>\r\n<p>Sometimes I\'ll go into the bathroom and I\'ll lift the seat. As I am sitting down my leg will touch the cold  edge of the porcelin bowl.  I\'ve lifted both the cover <strong>and</strong> the seat.  This really shouldn\'t be an enormous issue but there\'s something way back in the back of my brain that totally freaks and my whole body spasms and I arch my back and stiffen up and stand at attention.  My body involuntarily does anything it can to avoid putting my ass on that bowl rim.</p>\r\n<p>It was never really a problem when I was younger because I was young and limber.  Things are different now though.  I\'m old and large, stiff and out of shape.  I hurt myself everytime.</p>','Toilet panic',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','toilet-panic','','','2005-06-20 11:11:35','2005-06-20 16:11:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/broken-back-on-the-toilet/',0,'','',0),
	(226,1,'2005-06-15 20:12:22','2005-06-16 01:12:22','<p>As mentioned before, I was on vacation last week.  Amidst all the sun and fun with the Ellers in Orlando I managed to get through an entire book.  I mentioned this fact to Mark the other night in Borders and when I tld him what my <em>fun</em> reading on vacation had been he nearly passed out from laughing.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/1400045509/qid=1118880773/sr=8-1/ref=pd_csp_1/102-3675225-1108125\">Electric Universe : The Shocking True Story of Electricity</a> was a great book. I\'ll give you a minute.</p>\r\n<p>Although I enjoy science, I am not much of a scientific reader.  That is, I don\'t buy books on scientific theory because if the science is too heavy I lose interest too quickly.  I read <em>A Brief History of Time</em> but I got more out of <em>Who\'s Afraid of Schrodinger\'s Cat</em>.  Not because it was better, just because it was written in chunks that were more easily digested.  Regardless, this is partially a science book.</p>\r\n<p>It\'s also a history book.  This is the reason I bought it.  The delicate weave between history and science is very enjoyable.  It reminded me alot of <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0393324826/qid=1118881976/sr=8-1/ref=pd_csp_1/102-3675225-1108125\">Stiff</a> (which is one of my favorite books all time)(although this one didn\'t really come close).  The best part about this book though was that it had a third layer that history/science books haven\'t had in the past for me.  Electric Universe had personality. I mean personality of the books subjects. </p>\r\n<p>I have always wanted to know more about the figures in my history.  I\'ve always wanted to know what these guys were like.  Who were their friends and enemies.  What did they do for fun.  Insecurities? Fears? Ultimate goals and interests.  Electric Universe offered that extra piece of the puzzle that I yearn for. Pick it up, read it, enjoy it and thank me later.</p>','Some fun reading on vacation.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','vacation-reading-for-fun','','','2005-06-22 22:35:33','2005-06-23 03:35:33','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/electric-universe-the-shocking-true-story-of-electricity/',0,'','',2),
	(227,1,'2005-06-14 20:04:26','2005-06-15 01:04:26','<div style=\"float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/18805286/\" title=\"photo sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos12.flickr.com/18805286_aad72d3c36_m.jpg\" alt=\"\" style=\"border: solid 2px #000000;\" /></a>\r\n <span style=\"font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 0px;\">\r\n  Originally uploaded by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/people/timmyfury/\">Timmy Fury</a>.\r\n </span>\r\n</div>\r\nI spent last week in Florida.  Some of you may not have noticed since, as a dedicated nerd, I prewrote a few entries to post while I was down there.  I checked my email twice.  Amazing.  That\'s my average per second check usually.  I barely thought about anything.  It was wonderful.  Trish and I both came back relaxed as all get out and had two days of blissful recovery before we returned to work.  <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/451123/\">I\'ve posted all of my images on flickr</a>.\r\n<br clear=\"all\" />','Baking in Florida',1,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','baking-in-florida','','','2005-06-15 14:27:36','2005-06-15 19:27:36','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/baking-in-florida/',0,'','',1),
	(230,1,'2005-06-22 23:14:27','2005-06-23 04:14:27','<p>Trish and I (among several other friends) are searching for an apartment.  We have found a few good prospects but nothing that gives us the firm caress of confidence that we are looking for.  We want to find that perfect place.  Here\'s my advice for finding your dream joint.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Take your time.  There are tons of properties for rent all the time.  Wait until you find the one you want.</li>\r\n<li>Search all possible sources.  Newspapers, online directories, craigslist and realtors.  Don\'t discount driving around and looking for signs.  Not only will you find tons of things that aren\'t advertised, sometimes before anyone else has gotten a chance to look at the place, but it also helps give you an opportunity to see the neighborhood and learn the roads and stores in the immediate area.</li>\r\n<li>Explore all of your options.  Look at as many places as you can.  You have to live there for a year.  This is a big decision and could make your life a living hell or a wonderful paradise.</li>\r\n<li>If you call an advert for a place and it takes them four days to get back to you, this is not the place for you.  If it takes them four days to get back to you when you are trying to give them money, they will never call you back when you need them after you move in.  You have more chance of drinking every ounce of water pouring from your hot water heater than you do of the rushing over to help you.</li>\r\n<li>Know what you want before you even look. Number of bedrooms, price range, acceptable areas, types of housing.  Make sure you know what you are don\'t want.  What\'s going to be a deal breaker and what are you willing to bend on.</li>\r\n<li>Find out what the other tenants are like.  If this means breaking down the doors of your future neighbors, so be it.  I don\'t know if you can take the landlord\'s or heaven forbid the realtor\'s opinion into account but i suppose they would have a reasonable idea.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Above all the most important thing is to be patient and don\'t lose your cool.  I am totally eager to get a place, but impatience will lead to a crappy apartment that will make me want to move back into, heaven forbid, my parent\'s house.</p>','Apartment hunting advice',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','apartment-hunt-advice','','','2005-06-22 23:14:35','2005-06-23 04:14:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/apartment-hunt-advice/',0,'','',7),
