	(329,1,'2006-03-24 14:56:55','2006-03-24 19:56:55','<h1>The Special Place</h1>\r\n<p>As I sit here I canâ€™t help but think how great it is.  I have a little place to call my own, a hide-away of sorts.  I spend a lot of time here and I have grown to like it.</p>\r\n<p>Itâ€™s sort of dark here.  There isnâ€™t much light at all.  I would use my lighter but I am afraid that I will set something ablaze and start an inferno.  Thereâ€™s a lot of stuff in here.  I think there is a coat and boots underneath of me.  The tire iron is poking me in the leg and the jack is underneath my rear end.   I think there are some bottles of oil here too.  There must be a leak.  I can feel water sloshing around underneath of me.  Everything around me is drenched.  I shiver every time I am here.  Itâ€™s cold and damp. The smell is a combination of oil, mildew and exhaust.  It makes me a little light-headed but it goes away when I get hit with an overwhelming smell of gasoline.  Even though my friends are all here itâ€™s very muffled.  I canâ€™t hear much of anything.  I can only hear them when everyone gets very loud.</p>\r\n<p>My friends are having such a good time with me here. They are laughing and whooping and screaming and cheering.  All they talk about is how great it is that I am here.  It makes me feel like a celebrity.  The thrill wears off after a while though.  They quiet down and I think they forgot that I am even here.  Theyâ€™ll come back though.  The entertainment is too appealing to them. </p>\r\n<p>I donâ€™t necessarily like it here though.  I donâ€™t have a choice though.  When my friends came to get me tonight, they convinced me to play out a kidnapping scenario in front of a huge crowd of people.  They snatched me up and stuffed in the trunk at the Dairy Queen and sped away.  They promised to let me out, but I should have known that they wouldnâ€™t.  My friends are jerks.  I should expect this sort of thing.  The problem is that they have been driving over curbs and speed bumps for the last hour.  I am getting tired of it.  I am hurt. But they are having fun still.</p>\r\n<p>Most people would say that I am sick for thinking this is a great place.  Itâ€™s terrible, it smells and itâ€™s painful.  They are probably right, but the thing that makes it great is that next time it will be someone else.</p>\r\n<p><em>written February 2003</em></p>\r\n','The Special Place',0,'',NULL,NULL,'static','closed','closed','','the-special-place','','','2006-03-24 14:59:29','2006-03-24 19:59:29','',0,'http://veryraw.com/the-special-place/',0,'','',0),
	(236,1,'2005-06-26 08:19:37','2005-06-26 13:19:37','<p>Trish and I were driving around Media last night in our seamingly neverending hunt for an apartment.  I lean forward toward my steering wheel and in the corner of my eye I see something fly in the window.  It hits my shoulder and I feel it land on my back.  Trish starts screaming, \"Oh my god pull over! It\'s huge!\"  I have no idea what the thing is.  For all I know its a freaking vampire bat or a flying rabid baby or something worse.  I start screaming, \"Just get it off!\" She won\'t touch it.  </p>\r\n<p>As I start to brake, but while I am still movng, I throw the car in park.  The car comes to a grinding, painful stop and the two of us fly out of the car.  Now the two of us, twitching with a case of the heebie-jeebies are looking all over the car for this thing.  She describes it to me as what sounds like a huge flying roach or waterbug.  It had apparently crawled into the back seat when I jumped out ofthe car.  We couldn\'t find it.  After about five minutes, standing in the middle of the street in Media with all of the doors of the car wide open we decided toget back in the car and move on. </p>\r\n<p>Twenty minutes later, the thing flies out of the back seat and past Trish\'s head.  It lands near the windshield then flies to the dashboard.  Trish starts freaking again.  I managed to actually stop the car this time in my panic to get the hell out of the car. Didn\'t manage to pull off the road mind you, just stop the car.  We are running around the car looking for a stick to use to chase it out of the car.  I find one and it avoids my stick and runs to the other side of the dash.  I was terrifed it was going to run down into the dashboard and lay eggs in the heater or something.  I manage to knock it to the floor then out of the car.  </p>\r\n<p>When the dust settled, we stood outside of the car staring at each other, we noticed that there was a guy, possibly one of our future neighbors, standing in his yard watching the two of us the whole time.  His face had disbelief all over it.</p>','Bug attack.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','bug-attack','','','2006-02-15 09:19:36','2006-02-15 14:19:36','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/bug-attack/',0,'','',5),
	(237,1,'2005-06-26 10:13:20','2005-06-26 15:13:20','<div style=\"float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/bratacious/21513759/\" title=\"photo sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos16.flickr.com/21513759_a3a38f2d54_m.jpg\" alt=\"\" style=\"border: solid 2px #000000;\" /></a>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 0px;\">Originally uploaded by <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/people/bratacious/\">Bratacious</a>.</span></div>\r\nMichelle took this picture when Debbie was cooking us Puerto Rican dinner on Friday.    It\'s the greatest use for a shirt pocket ever.\r\n<br clear=\"all\" />','Beer pocket',1,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','beer-pocket','','','2005-06-26 10:15:46','2005-06-26 15:15:46','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/beer-pocket/',0,'','',0),
	(251,1,'2005-07-27 19:08:16','2005-07-28 00:08:16','<p style=\"float: left;margin:0px 10px 5px 0px;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/28990566/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos23.flickr.com/28990566_a94ecab8e3_m.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"200\" alt=\"Bike Route - April 11, 2005 - 6.1 miles\" /></a></p>\r\nAs mentioned before in my entry about the amazing <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2005/07/24/sports/20050724_LANCE_SLIDESHOW_1.html\">Lance Armstrong</a>, I have been riding my bike. Since I moved to Media I have been getting out more to ride.  Using this great Google maps application called <a href=\"http://www.sueandpaul.com/gmapPedometer/\">GMaps Pedometer</a> I can track my ride turn for turn and see how far I have traveled. I was just saving the links on del.icio.us but I decided last night to screenshot them and upload them to flickr where I can make notes and comments about the course I rode as well as dates and important areas to remember when mapping out future routes to take on my rides.  Anyway for those who are interested you can take a look at my maps.  They are in my <a href=\"http://flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/653066/\">Bike Routes set</a>.','Riding my bike. Mapping my route.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','riding-my-bike','','','2005-07-27 19:08:57','2005-07-28 00:08:57','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/riding-my-bike/',0,'','',0),
	(238,1,'2005-06-29 14:05:54','2005-06-29 19:05:54','<p>Stop saying that.  The only time that its acceptable to say that is at an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting.  And you had better be a freaking alcoholic. If you say that anywhere else when you introduce yourself you should be thrown out.  You\'re just trying to be funny.  You\'re not.</p>\r\n<p><em>Okay upon talking to Mark I decided to put a break in here.  The rest of the entry is complete nonsense and may not make as much sense (or humor) to you as it did to me. Read beyond this point at your own risk.</em></p>\r\n<!--more-->\r\n<p>I wish my name was Timothy Jack Daniels Crowe. Like... I wish thats what my parents had named me.  It would be great cause then people would think that I was trying to be funny like in the aforementioned example.  But that would actually be my name.  It would be awesome when I went to job interviews and shit and they thought I was just being a complete jerkoff.</p>\r\n<p>Problem is though that I can\'t change my name to that because it wouldn\'t be natural.  Then I would actually be doing it just for the humor. </p>\r\n<p>It would be even better if my parents had raised me in the mormon or amish tradition.  Then people would be able to grin at the irony of the name of such a chaste and prudent man.</p>','Hi.  I\'m Tim and I\'m an alcoholic.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','im-an-alcoholic','','','2005-06-29 18:12:24','2005-06-29 23:12:24','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/hi-im-tim-and-im-an-alcoholic/',0,'','',0),
	(239,1,'2005-06-28 12:46:38','2005-06-28 17:46:38','<p>A few months ago I was having an issue with a module I was developing for the website at the college.  It\'s a problem that I have run into before but simply ignored it because it wasn\'t an enormous problem.  You submit a form.  It performs some action.  You hit the back button.  You receive a message that reads something like this...</p>\r\n<blockquote>The page you are tyring to view contains POSTDATA. If you resend the data, any action the form carried out (such as search or online purchase) will be repeated. To resend the data, click OK. Otherwise, click Cancel.</blockquote>\r\n<p>So it\'s not a big deal but whats going to happen is that whatever action had just been performed is going to be performed again.  This may not matter if the action is updating a message or deleting based on some unique identifier, but if the action is a purchase from an online store or adding a user account, this could cause some serious issues.</p>\r\n<p>The problem originates in the HTTP Header where this information is stored.  The browser remembers all the information that it sent in a request to the web server you are communicating with.  So theoretically if you clear that information from the browser you will eliminate the problem.</p>\r\n<p>My solution to the issue is to tell the browser not to cache the page.  After your application does its work, you will probably redirect to a feedback page or back to the originating page to display some thanks or feedback.  Before sending the <code>redirect</code> header, send <code>cache-control</code> header.  This will tell most browsers not to cache the page.  Then if the user hits the back button, they will be sent to the page they were at prior to the form submission (back to the form itself) instead of the page that is performing the actions.  It looks like this.</p>\r\n<code>\r\n<pre>\r\n< ?php\r\n  // a bunch of stuff that performs the actions you want.\r\n\r\n  // some headers to disable caching\r\n    header(&quot;Cache-Control: no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate&quot;);\r\n    header(&quot;Cache-Control: post-check=0, pre-check=0&quot;, false);\r\n    header(&quot;Pragma: no-cache&quot;);\r\n\r\n  // send it to a new page.\r\n    header(&quot;Location: http://veryraw.com/&quot;);\r\n?>\r\n</pre>\r\n</code>\r\n<p>There are some assumptions made here.  I generally send to a different page when a form is submitted. I do my work there then redirect to somewhere else depending on what the action performed was.  Some developers prefer to submit to the page the form is on.  In this case <a href=\"http://ad.hominem.org/log/2005/03/eliminating_the.php\">the problem would come if the page was reloaded</a> rather than if the back button was clicked. Regardless of your methods the solution should still work.</p>\r\n<p>Try it.  Let me know what you think.  Here is some further reading if you want to know where I got my methods from.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://us2.php.net/header\">php.net: header</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.w3.org/Protocols/\">W3C: HTTP - Hypertext Transfer Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Eliminating the \'resend POSTDATA\' error.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','postdata','','','2005-06-28 12:52:18','2005-06-28 17:52:18','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/postdata/',0,'','',0),
	(240,1,'2005-06-29 15:44:24','2005-06-29 20:44:24','<div style=\"float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/22441751/\" title=\"photo sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos16.flickr.com/22441751_a5a79cca93_m.jpg\" alt=\"\" style=\"border: solid 2px #000000;\" /></a></div>\r\nI just saw <a href=\"http://www.kingkongmovie.com/ef239524432ba87f1ca8f70eed4b1fa7/en_large.html\">the trailer for the King Kong remake</a>.  It looks freaking amazing. It\'s the first movie in a long time that has given me that \"Oh crap\" reaction.  I am so excited to see this.  King Kong fights a freaking T-rex. I can\'t wait.\r\n<br clear=\"all\" />','King Kong gives me a rise!',1,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','king-kong-gives-me-a-rise','','','2005-06-29 18:14:32','2005-06-29 23:14:32','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/king-kong-gives-me-a-rise/',0,'','',1),
	(241,1,'2005-06-30 11:42:18','2005-06-30 16:42:18','<p>I some how managed to take two broken iPods (a 10gig first generation with a dead battery and a 20gig third gen with a broken screen) and combine them into one very broken ipod that doesn\'t really fit together tightly and only works when its plugged into the wall.  I know you\'re impressed. <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/sets/522941/\">Check out the pictures.</a></p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/22613784/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos18.flickr.com/22613784_a0c63fdca7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" alt=\"the montrosity pieced together\" /></a>','Call me Dr. Frankenstein',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','call-me-dr-frankenstein','','','2005-06-30 11:42:37','2005-06-30 16:42:37','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/06/call-me-dr-frankenstein/',0,'','',3),
