	(243,1,'2005-07-06 15:03:19','2005-07-06 20:03:19','<p>I was just reading this entry on <a href=\"http://www.7nights.com/asterisk/archives05/2005/07/dreamhost-on-rails\">asterisk</a>.  He\'s pimpin\' <a href=\"http://www.dreamhost.com/\">dreamhost</a> again.  Everyone who uses it does.  I\'m thinking of switching there myself.  I\'d like to be able to run a few domains on the same account and testing new languages wouldn\'t be horrible.  Plus god help me if I had the amount of storage available that they offer. I can\'t do it though (leave the comment that is).  I always feel bad about it cause I hate senseless comments so much.</p>\r\n<p>Anyway, everytime I see someone pimping dreamhost on I want to leave a comment like \"Be sure an\' tell \'em, Large Marge sent ya!\"  I\'m sorry its just what I think of.  And then I picture that face.  Large Marge\'s face.  And I laugh so hard. I loved that movie and that part in particular was like the single greatest moment in horror history.  If you have no idea what I\'m talking about go buy Pee Wee\'s Big Adventure and enjoy.</p>\r\n<p>While I\'ve got your attention, go read <a href=\"http://iam.thecolossus.net/?p=92\">Mark\'s entry about our conversation this morning</a>.</p>','Be sure an\' tell \'em...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','be-sure-an-tell-em','','','2005-07-06 15:10:38','2005-07-06 20:10:38','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/be-sure-an-tell-em/',0,'','',4),
	(244,1,'2005-07-11 23:02:58','2005-07-12 04:02:58','<p>Although I enjoy my job at <a href=\"http://dccc.edu/\">the college</a> immensely, there was once a job that I enjoyed more.  After dropping out of Millersville University, I got a job at USAirways. I threw bags; loaded the bellies of planes.  I loved that job like Woah!, but in time realized that someday I would want more then aching knees and back. I left the job and took a less certain path.</p>\r\n<p>I do miss that job, though. I miss racing around on those tugs and conveyor belts.  Throwing other people\'s things around with wanton regard.  The excitement as the engines screamed near your head and threw anything in their path across the tarmac.  I miss the dominos in the breakroom with guys three times my age.  We mocked and taunted each other as we slammed the dominos on the table with vigar and screamed \"<strong>pants!</strong>\" at full volume when we threw down some points.</p>\r\n<p>It was the thrill of doing something that others didn\'t get to do.  When the plane was coming in you would watch the monitors as the status updated to \"arrived\" and your gates team would grab their things and rush out the door to greet the customer. Working hard to get the freight or bags to the baggage claim or to another plane to make a quick connection then loading the next flight\'s cargo to get the flight out on time.</p>\r\n<p>If you work for an airline on the gates you\'ll read this and laugh at the romanticized version of what goes on behind the scenes of an airline. It\'s dirty, hard, honest work, but I loved doing it.  To this day everytime I drive behind a diesel truck on a cool morning, I am comforted by the memories of those carefree laid back mornings on the ramp at Philadelphia International.</p>','The comforting smell of diesel.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-comforting-smell-of-diesel','','','2005-07-11 23:03:02','2005-07-12 04:03:02','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/the-comforting-smell-of-diesel/',0,'','',6),
	(245,1,'2005-07-18 20:42:27','2005-07-19 01:42:27','<p>I\'ve grown quite fond of biking recently.  I have gone on several <a href=\"http://www.sueandpaul.com/gmapPedometer/?centerX=-75.31050682067871&centerY=39.911711314759685&zl=3&polyline=yosrF~gnjM~S%7BMhFnOpOqLrDdLcZbSzBhGHjd@cHnFsJlSmN%60KjVxo@rAzZtKaDv%5EvuAxIbN%7BH~IhFjOwCbHml@ps@%60A~EdEuAh@%60DcEfBgBsK~p@u%7C@_@%7BKdFiGmMmTg_@suAuGsOcD~Bs@mIaVqo@uI%60DtIkDzNgJxF_NhD%7CLs@lAdFpN%7BA%7DDjDgCwIiYf@a@iR%7Bh@lGyGeD%7BGz@uAoCsK\">good</a> <a href=\"http://www.sueandpaul.com/gmapPedometer/?centerX=-75.20347595214844&centerY=39.99737491734879&zl=4&polyline=si%7DrF%60m%7BiMgExAyBd%5BuArBkC%60@mDQsFtAsK%60GwNzMkPpWoChKaMdRsETcDwBaHuLeQaReGsDqEiI_FoIgOmIgWgDiSa@gR~C_EpCiLt%5DkGpY%7BDtReJzMwH%5DuDvRyCzMuFzGyGzD_R%60VcNlTqIvXjDkK%60D%7BLxHwKjEmG%7CKuO%60DgE~JoGnCsEf@eDrDaPtBcKdJGhHiLhIma@~I%7B%5DxFmK~GsD%60KqAl%5Bh@~QzC%7CNlGlIpPvQdRzNzMfHdKlFYhG%7BIxEoHnDoMx%5B%7B%60@bTcKxISjB%7BG%60AoO%5CiExCgA%5C%5D\">treks</a> which some may have seen in the side list of links.  As my interest in biking has grown I have also been reading Tour de France news.  Interesting stuff.  I  also heard a story about how Lance Armstrong\'s oversized heart and excessively efficient muscles allow him to trudge up the Alps during the tour.  Now I can\'t stop thinking about Lance.  I read as much as  can about him. I look at pictures of him.  It\'s creepy.  I have even caught myself dropping Lance trivia into conversations and going as far as saying \"Lance would never do that,\" as if I knew him.</p>\r\n<p>Anyway, for those of you who are not eerily obsessed with Lance but would like to see some really bizarre happenings at the tour, <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mpk/sets/591459/\">check out the first half of this photoset</a>.</p>','I think I\'ve fallen in love with Lance Armstrong!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','fallen-in-love-with-lance-armstrong','','','2005-07-18 20:42:59','2005-07-19 01:42:59','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/i-think-ive-fallen-in-love-with-lance-armstrong/',0,'','',4),
	(246,1,'2005-07-19 20:04:44','2005-07-20 01:04:44','<p>I found this band yesterday that I really like.  Gay for Johnny Depp. They are pretty good, remind me of The Blood Brothers.  So I do a search for them and I come up with there <a href=\"http://gayforjohnnydepp.com/\">website</a>. Its freaking horrible. A goddamned nightmare. Let me tell you whats wrong with the site...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The name of the band is not even on the site.  I wasn\'t sure if it was even the bands website.</li>\r\n<li>Frames.  Bloody frames.  Stop fucking using frames. You\'re not hiding anything from me, I will get what I want from your site if I want it.  Frames will not stop me.</li>\r\n<li>Flash music player.  Whats the point.  Offer me music to download. I don\'t want to listen to it on your rotten website.</li>\r\n<li>Creative non-descript titles for your links.  They aren\'t creative really, I don\'t know what they are.  I don\'t know how to find the content I want.</li>\r\n<li>The worst offense of all.  How do I buy your fucking album.  The sites I am refered to are un-navigable. I can\'t find your album anywhere.  Why would I ever buy an album from a store I can\'t find anything in.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>After all this I still want to buy the album but I don\'t know how.  I tried amazon but got no where.  Putting your music on amazon isn\'t selling out, its smart.  Why would you make your music so difficult to find.</p>\r\n<p>Just for prosperity sake I should mention a few other things that bother me in addition to those mentioned above about band websites...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Stop using Flash</strong>.  I can\'t link to a part of your site if you are using flash.  It makes it impossible to navigate and I don\'t bloody care how many things you can get to fly across my screen in like three seconds.  <a href=\"http://handsomeboymodelingschool.com/\">Handsome Boy Modeling School</a> is a classic example of the overuse of Flash. If you click that link there is a good chance your computer will come to a stand still and your browser will crash.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Don\'t put a link up to content then put an under construction page there</strong>. It\'s so annoying.  I hate in the off occasion that I can actually find what I want on a band site the content isn\'t actually there. <a href=\"http://thebloodbrothers.com/flash.html\">The Blood Brothers</a> are not only a great example of this (try downloading a song or two), but they also use worthless un-navigable flash.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Offer me some sample music</strong>. I mean full songs.  Snippets never get stuck in my head and make me hunt your album down.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Give me metadata</strong>. Before you upload those songs to your site, make sure the metadata is proper so I can find it again in my music player later.  If I can\'t find it, I can\'t listen to it again and again, therefore it will never get stuck in my head and force me to buy your album. I downloaded two songs from the <a href=\"http://www.yeahyeahyeahs.com/\">Yeah Yeah Yeahs</a> website last night and they had no metadata. It took me like five minutes to find it again once I imported it into my itunes library.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This is certainly not a comprehensive list.  This is merely a list of the things that irritate me most about band sites. When I go to a band site, I want to know history, lyrics, discography and I want to download media.  Give me information on your site.  Your music is your art, not your website.</p>','If you have a band, listen up!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','band-listen-up','','','2005-07-19 20:08:41','2005-07-20 01:08:41','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/if-you-have-a-band-listen-up/',0,'','',1),
	(247,1,'2005-07-22 10:36:43','2005-07-22 15:36:43','<p>As I noted a few weeks ago, I have been <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/living-in-meatspace/\">busy with my move</a>.  Trish and I have been in our new place for a week now and things are really getting together.  I am finally hanging pictures and mirrors after some painting and organizing.  We have filled the dumpster for our building twice now with things we are throwing away and the best part, I went out and bought a grill last night.  Life is good.</p>\r\n<p>The move has really initiated a life style change of sorts.  I call this my quality of life move.  Not only am I living with Trish now, which lets me see her more often, but it also cuts all driving times significantly.  I have a 5 minute drive to work now.  Instead of getting home around 6:30, I\'m finishing dinner around 6:30.  This obviously gives me a lot more time at night to do what I want at night.  Furthermore, I am not making three trips a week to Trish\'s house a whopping 40 miles from my house.</p>\r\n<p>The other difference is that with a refridgerator full of food and beer, I end up eating out less.  Very healthy.  I actually feel better physically.  and I eat more regularly.</p>\r\n<p>Then there\'s the coffee pot.  My god.  How nice is it to have a coffee pot in your place.  Cutting my drive from an hour to five minutes in the morning has given me 55 minutes to sit in my apartment and enjoy a half of a pot of coffee before I go to work.  Drinking coffee in your underwear is always better than drinking it in your car on the way to work.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ll take some pictures of the place and post them so you can see what I\'m living like.</p>','Looks like I have an apartment',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','looks-like-i-have-an-apartment','','','2005-07-22 10:36:57','2005-07-22 15:36:57','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/looks-like-i-have-an-apartment/',0,'','',2),
	(248,1,'2005-07-24 19:26:40','2005-07-25 00:26:40','<p>A few years ago I started thinking about what would happen if my parents house burnt down and all my childhood images were lost, or worse, all the images of my parents and their parents were lost too.  A thourough family history lost to flame. That\'s rough. That\'s alot of history. I have commented before that I think I am the single most photographed person on earth.  There are literally ten-thousand images of me over the course of my life.  My brother and sisters too.</p>\r\n<p>The though of this made me cringe.  I enjoy not only leafing through the images but feel that someday these will be the things that allow my children\'s children to get an idea of who I was and how life was when I was young (that is to say that some wonderful science isn\'t found to prevent me from becoming a vegetable by eighty years old). So I decided that the best thing to do was to scan every single image in my mother\'s house (I swear I wasn\'t high).  It\'s an undertaking that has nearly swallowed me.  Sometimes I am really into it and other times I really couldn\'t care less.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ve scanned images from my father\'s and mother\'s childhoods and paintings and poems and handprints from all of my siblings.  I\'ve scanned images so old that no one remembers what they are anymore.</p>\r\n<p>The problem then is how the hell do I remember what these images are and who is in them and when they were taken.  There\'s a bounty of information that you might need when you actually want to use these images later.  File names and folder structures can only take you so far on this.</p>\r\n<p>I searched and searched for software to help me with the collection of image information.  I tried Picassa, it nearly solved the problem but wasn\'t perfect for what I was looking for.  Then I finally tried <a href=\"http://flickr.com\">flickr</a>. As you may already know I am madly in love with flickr.  But there is a reason for my childish infatuation which stretches far beyond the desire to share and lookat photos.</p>\r\n<p>When images are uploaded they are tagged (categorized) and dated and captioned and titled.  Most importantly though, they are backed up somewhere where the evil life erasing fire can\'t get it (theoretically).</p>\r\n<p>This still doesn\'t solve the issue of sitting down at the kitchen table with the kids and leafing through your albums telling stories and laughing like any good hallmark family does, but its just the setup.</p>','Laying out a photo album of thousands of digital images: the setup.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','laying-out-a-photo-album-setup','','','2005-07-24 19:26:47','2005-07-25 00:26:47','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/laying-out-a-photo-album-of-thousands-of-digital-images-an-idea/',0,'','',9),
	(249,1,'2005-08-04 13:10:04','2005-08-04 18:10:04','<p>In <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/laying-out-a-photo-album-setup/\">the setup to this idea</a>, I explained the monstrous task that I was facing.  The archiving and eventual laying out of thousands of images into comprehensive annotated album is no simple task.  I may have a working plan for solving this issue.</p>\r\n<p>The first part involves <a href=\"http://flickr.com\">flickr</a>. Using their developers API, an application, web-based or stand-alone, would be developed which would allow you to look at your flickr photostream in chronological order (as opposed to date uploaded order).  The application would allow you to do the following things.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ensure that the date taken information attached to the image was correct.  This can be done in flickr but by viewing them in chronological order would allow you to ensure images flow in time.</li>\r\n<li>Correct and elaborate on captions tags, and titles.</li>\r\n<li>Define tags.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Define tags may not be the right wording.  Rather than define I should say tell whether they are people, places, things or descriptions.  This is important later.</p>\r\n<p>The key to this application is to focus on metadata.  The more clear your data is now the better your final product would be.  With that information, the application would output an XML file with all of the information in it.</p>\r\n<h4>This is where the idea gets bit hairy</h4>\r\n<p>With the file outputted with the flickr information, a template of some sort would be created to lay all of this information out into quark or inDesign. Rules would be set for how to show captions and titles and dates.  The template would have to know which categories of tags to display, people and places, or just places, or just people, How large the largest images are allowed to be.  Whatever.  There are probably already examples of this somewhere.  I don\'t know.  I\'m a web professional not a print designer.  Then the tags would be used as an index so you could figure out what pages in the book each tag appears on.</p>\r\n<p>When printed and bound this would create an all inclusive album of your images and details in chronological, look at it with your kids on the kitchen table book.  It creates a history, with details of your family and your life.  Then a disk could be included with the high-res original of each image organized into folders by page if someone wanted to have a printed picture.  But it allows you to have a real, tangable, actual photo album that pictures won\'t fall out of and get misplaced.  The details are all there and no one will forget whats in the pictures.  Not to mention, if you have a family the size of mine, it would be easy to print a volume for my brother and sisters, parents, whoever without too much effort.  With on-demand printing, this would be rather easy.</p>\r\n<p>The point to all this is that although flickr may not be perfect, what I am trying to do is get all of my images in one place, with proper information.  Then I can work with it however I want.  I have no doubt that someday I will want to abandom flickr, but by then I would hope I have this project long finished.  Saving my memories, not just for me, but for my children and their children too, thats what the intent is</p>','Laying out a photo album of thousands of digital images: the solution/idea.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','laying-out-a-photo-album-solution','','','2005-08-04 13:10:26','2005-08-04 18:10:26','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/laying-out-a-photo-album-of-thousands-of-digital-images-the-solutionidea/',0,'','',4),
	(250,1,'2005-07-26 14:34:19','2005-07-26 19:34:19','<p>So I waited an hour and a half for the cable guy to come to my apartment.  Didn\'t need to be here.  The heavily accented gentleman who took my order on Sunday must have misunderstood what I wanted.  They came in to put in digital cable.  I didn\'t want it.  I wanted standard.  All I need is CNN, Discovery and the History Channel and I\'m set.  So I didn\'t need to be here when they came in.  No biggy really.  They go to the pole and set me up.  </p>\r\n<p>The point to my story here is that when the guys come in they are telling me I am getting digital cable, I tell them, \"No I just need Discovery and the History Channel.\"  The guys look at each other then look around the place.  Dual screens.  Metal playing. National geographic.  Wired.  Reading about Burning man. Two full bookshelves. SUSE linux book on the coffee table. I know exactly what they were thinking.</p>\r\n<h1>\"A nerd lives here!\"</h1>','Nerd lives here.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','nerd-live-here','','','2006-02-15 09:14:35','2006-02-15 14:14:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/nerd-live-here/',0,'','',5),
	(252,1,'2005-08-25 06:29:01','2005-08-25 11:29:01','<p>A look at an image like <a href=\"http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap050805.html\">Triple Sunset</a> from <em> Astronomy Picture of the Day</em> sparks wild imaginative scenerios in my head.  The ideas it gives me are awesome.  Most of them lead back to my love of Star Trek or Star Wars (see <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/nerd-live-here/\">Nerd lives here</a>). But there\'s something else that this sort of image prompts me to do.</p>\r\n<p>\"<em>Only 149 light-years away in the constellation Cygnus...</em>\"</p>\r\n<p>Start from earth and go out.  The moon... </p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 light year = 5.87849981 &#215; 10<sup>12</sup> miles</p>\r\n<p>149 light years = 8.75896472 &#215; 10<sup>14</sup> miles</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(((149 light years) / (120 miles)) / 365) / 100 = 199 976 364</p>\r\n\r\nhttp://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap050825.html\r\nhttp://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap060415.html\r\n\r\nhttp://www.guardian.co.uk/science/story/0,,1768191,00.html\r\n\r\nhttp://webisto.com/space/','Exercises in futility expand your thinking power.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','exercises-in-futility-expand-your-thinking-power','','','2006-06-22 12:08:46','2006-06-22 17:08:45','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/exercises-in-futility-expand-your-thinking-power/',0,'','',0),
	(253,1,'2005-09-09 15:40:18','2005-09-09 20:40:18','<p>I recently bought a helmet (finally) to wear while I ride.  Particularly in Media the chances of getting hit by a car are, in my eyes, pretty solid.  I thought it might pay to have something to prevent my head from getting destroyed when I do eventually get hit.  Also with the gift certificate Trish gave me for timbuk2 <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/27180248/\">I got a new bag</a>.  It\'s pretty awesome.  Makes carrying a bag while riding super easy and I can fit like eight human heads in it... or clothes for work.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ve mentioned before that I have been doing some research into bike touring.  It\'s something that I would like tyo do a little of next spring and, if I like it, alot more the year after with a trek cross country.  Jason Hill is riding from the Arctic Circle to Tierra del Fuego, Argentina and <a href=\"http://www.tourparabienestar.com/blog/\">telling his story along the way</a>.  I\'ve been reading this blog for a little while.  It\'s better than the other stories about touring I\'ve read because this one unfolds over time because he\'s doing it right now. Worth a read if you are interested in the trials of distance biking.</p>\r\n<p>This link is half for me and half for y\'all.  Someday (if I actually do ride cross country) I will need the information about flying home.  <a href=\"http://www.ibike.org/encouragement/travel/bagregs.htm\">Airline regulations for flying with your bike</a>.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.northwestwatch.org/publications/sevenwondersexcerpt.asp\">This article</a> gives the skinny on why bikes rule, as if you needed more reasons.</p>\r\n<blockquote> North Americans might not believe it, but my love affair with my vehicle puts me, not my Oprah sofa-mate, squarely in the transportation mainstream. The bicycle is the world\'s most widely used transport vehicle. Worldwide, bicycles outnumber automobiles almost two to one, and their production outpaces cars three to one. Rush-hour traffic in China is dominated by human-powered vehicles; even in the wealthy cities of Europe and Japan, large shares of the populace get around by bike.</blockquote>\r\n<p>It also mentions that a human on a bicycle is the most efficient creature or vehicle on earth.</p>\r\n<p>Programs of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/france/story/0,11882,1547732,00.html\">the one in Paris</a> are rad.  I would love if they had something like <a href=\"http://www.worldchanging.com/archives/000899.html\">these programs</a> at Temple.  Should would make it easier to get to class form the train station in time.  Or maybe get across campus for another class.</p>\r\n<p>And last a few bike related links that I found interesting but never shared</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://ghostcycle.org/\">Ghost Cycle</a> - They leave bicycle painted white on the street in every spot someone was killed on a bike in attempt to make people more aware and make streets more biker friendly.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.biketree.com/\">Bike tree</a> - A sweet futuristic looking method for string bikes.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.myra-simon.com/bike/tips.html\"> Myra VanInwegen\'s Bike Articles</a> - Some good articles that may be some help to someone, they were to me.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.re-cycle.org/\">Re Cycle</a> - Re-condition old bikes to fight poverty.</li></ul>','A collection of biking related stuff.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','biking-related-stuff','','','2005-09-09 15:40:32','2005-09-09 20:40:32','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/biking-gear-new-bikes-and-old-bikes/',0,'','',0),
	(254,1,'2005-08-05 22:22:01','2005-08-06 03:22:01','Last night I went to the second meeting of the <a href=\"http://phillystandards.org/\">Philly Standards Organization</a>.  Had a good time.  I was a little nervous before going cause I wasn\'t sure what the level of knowledge in the room would be.  I was pleasantly surprised though to find a very healthy mix of skill sets and a wild passion for web standards.  Its very rare that I walk into a room of people and feel nearly immediately at home.  Also stange to be around such a large group of people that all get my jokes.  There was great conversation and alot of awesome ideas thrown around.  There was a str0ong sense of community. There was even talk of guest speakers. In <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/nerd-live-here/\">a testiment to how much of a nerd I am</a>, I was totally half stock at the prospect of meeting some of the web standards originators.  Looking forward to seeing what else may come from the group, but for now I\'m loving the strong desire for community within the group. ','Sure feels good to be among friends...',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','sure-feels-good-to-be-among-friends','','','2005-08-05 22:22:09','2005-08-06 03:22:09','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/sure-feels-good-to-be-among-friends/',0,'','',3),
	(256,1,'2005-08-08 23:56:40','2005-08-09 04:56:40','<p><a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/32512410/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://photos21.flickr.com/32512410_c63e1b665b.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"280\" alt=\"Shot of my geoblogger map\" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://geoblogger.com/\">Geoblogger</a> is a site that displays your flickr images on a map.  It knows where to display your images by the longitude and latitude tags that you add to your images.  If you want to know more about the specifics, try the geobloggers website.  Dan says it better that I.</p>\r\n<p>So I\'ve been doing this for a little while now, but a new interface for <a href=\"http://geobloggers.com\">geobloggers</a> was realeased recently, and its really quite nice.  I\'m totally loving the way it operates.  Even better is the fellow that mantains the site.  Not only did Dan take the time to answer my messages to him about the site but he went out of his way to show me how to craft the URL\'s to show my images only and control the way it appears to you.  Dan went way out of his way for someone who is maintaining this site as a hobby and for free.  An upstanding chap for sure.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.geobloggers.com/?sUsername=Timmy%20Fury&fLat=37.70&fLon=-74&iZL=11&iMaxRecords=25&sMapMode=map&iZL=6\">Try checking out my map of images that I have geotagged.</a></p>','Geoblogger: what an awesome application should be.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','geoblogger-what-an-awesome-application-should-be','','','2005-08-08 23:56:50','2005-08-09 04:56:50','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/geobloggers-what-an-awesome-application-should-be/',0,'','',5),
	(257,1,'2005-09-03 11:28:35','2005-09-03 16:28:35','<p>I had thought I had thrown out as much as I could before I made <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/looks-like-i-have-an-apartment/\">my recent move</a>.  I spent hours upon hours throwing away every little thing I could think of throwing out.  But after the actual move, quickly realized that I hadn\'t thrown out nearly as much as I previously thought.  The day after we finished moving in we filled the dumpster in our parking lot with boxes and old crap that I didn\'t even realize that I owned.  Taking a quick glance around the apartment as I write this and I see even more crap that I could ditch but just haven\'t.  Then there are the four boxes of stuff that are just being stored at my mother\'s house.  They are things that I don\'t use and probably never will but can\'t bring myself to throw away yet.</p>\r\n<p>So here is my point.  If you are moving, throw <strong>everything</strong> away.  If you haven\'t used it in the last six months (maybe less), throw it away.  You don\'t need it and after about 2 weeks you won\'t remember that you ever had it.  None of those possesions are really needed and you will feel better when you don\'t have as much stuff.  When everything you own is visible to you all the time, and nothing is stored away in boxes somewhere you will feel better.  Like a load has been lifted from your shoulders. Not to mention your moving will be easier and you won\'t need to find a bigger place everytime you move out of your current place.</p>','Moving made easier.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','moving-made-easier','','','2005-09-03 11:29:26','2005-09-03 16:29:26','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/tips-for-moving/',0,'','',0),
	(258,1,'2005-08-14 14:30:35','2005-08-14 19:30:35','<p>There\'s been a bit of crazy talk on <a href=\"http://macweblog.blogspot.com/2005/08/im-losing-my-mind.html\">Brian\'s blog</a>.  And it was continued in <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/geoblogger-what-an-awesome-application-should-be/\">the comments of my last entry</a>.  The idea is a cross country ride.  A tour from ocean to ocean.  <a href=\"http://www.biketouring.net/\">John Dorsey</a> has written a really extensive account of his first trip across and the adventure that the idea offers is nearly more than I can handle.  It sounds exciting and fun.</p>\r\n<p>There are obvious issues though.  I am currently about 50 pounds outside of the weight I would need to be to make a ride like that.  John says that the only thing that can prepare you  for six weeks of riding 75 miles a day is six weeks of riding 75 miles a day, but I must say that being in relatively proper shape from the start will make it easier.  I figure two years will be a proper amount of time to train for something like this.  Weights and eating right and all.</p>\r\n<p>I need to do some reasearch on bikes and get a new lighter bike.  Mine currently weighs about 35 pounds.  I should probably get a lighter one if I am going to strap 100 pounds of gear to it.  I also need to get my endurance up and take some really long rides.  I would like to make the ride to King of Prussia sometime in September.  I would like to plan a few other long rides and by next June (or there abouts) I would like to make a really long, multiple day journey.  New York City to Philadelphia and later Boston to Philadelphia or Washington.  </p>\r\n<p>There is also this <a href=\"https://www.nationalmssociety.org/pae/event/event_detail.asp?e=6654\">City to Shore bike tour</a> that I think I could probably participate in by the end of September if I worked hard through August and the beginning of September.  Thinking about it but not sure.</p>','Crazy talk of biking',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','crazy-talk-of-biking','','','2005-08-14 14:30:48','2005-08-14 19:30:48','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/crazy-talk-of-biking/',0,'','',3),
	(259,1,'2005-08-15 11:04:16','2005-08-15 16:04:16','Apparently showering doesn\'t qualify as cleaning the shower.','A lesson learned by living with my girlfriend.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-lesson-learned','','','2005-08-15 11:15:10','2005-08-15 16:15:10','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/a-lesson-learned-by-living-with-my-girlfriend/',0,'','',4),
