	(261,1,'2005-08-20 10:25:47','2005-08-20 15:25:47','<p>Using aerial photos, officials have found a 400 foot waterfall in California.  I should say they didn\'t just find it.  They had apparently found it then lost it, then found it again.  As I read <a href=\"http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8927720/\">the article on MSNBC</a> I thought to myself, How the hell do you lose a 400 foot waterfall.   Then, on further inspection of this <a href=\"http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/object/article?f=/c/a/2005/07/24/BAGMVDSP311.DTL&o=2&type=travelbayarea>map from SF Gate</a>, and this <a href=\"http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2005/08/0815_050815_waterfall.html\">article from National Geographic</a>, I realized how.</p>\r\n<p>The waterfall is called <strong>Whiskeytown Falls</strong>, located in <strong>Whiskeytown National Recreation Area</strong>.  Hmmm... I wonder.</p>','Lost Waterfall found, please claim.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','lost-waterfall-found-please-claim','','','2005-08-20 10:25:57','2005-08-20 15:25:57','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/lost-waterfall-found-please-claim/',0,'','',0),
	(262,1,'2005-09-05 11:25:18','2005-09-05 16:25:18','<p>I was trolling the flickr forums today in a <a href=\"http://flickr.com/groups/flick_off/\">particular group</a>.  The group is set up to protest what I saw as the imminent merging of accounts for flickr with accounts for yahoo.  Come on people.  Like you didn\'t see this coming.  If they had waited like three more weeks someone cool like kottke would have suggested it and then everyone would have jumped on the bandwagon and then it would have been acceptable.  But since it came from the corporation and not the community first its evil.</p>\r\n<p>In all seriousness though, I yearn for a service that can connect to every single piece of webware that I use so I don\'t have to use multiple passwords.  Obviously, I\'m not sure how much I would trust a company with all of my access to all of my accounts everywhere, but the concept is a dream.</p>\r\n<p>I don\'t know if everyone on flickr missed the memo, but hating corporations for being corporations stopped being cool like five years ago.  Once the dotcom implosion occured everyone should have realized that businesses do things for a reason, to stay alive.  They aren\'t out to fuck you and take your life away from you, they are basing their decisions on what will help them to build the largest customer base in the long run.  To be honest with you, the closed minded, corporation hatin\', indie crowd is only good for one thing.  They make things seem cool enough that the mainstream wants to be involved.</p>\r\n<p>In the end though, flickr is merely a service and at some point you will ditch said service for something else or for nothing at all.  You\'ll just find that spending hours on the internet is lame and go do something real.  It\'s not that big of a deal.</p>','Flickr\'s real merger with the conglomerate',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','flickrs-merger','','','2005-09-05 11:25:24','2005-09-05 16:25:24','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/stop-it-already-with-the-sensationalism/',0,'','',0),
	(264,1,'2005-09-05 11:18:29','2005-09-05 16:18:29','<h3>sensationalism type two: \"I found that cool thing before you did!\"</h3>\r\n<p>I am guilty of this to an extent.  I <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/04/oh-my-freaking-hell/\">pimped flickr</a> (still do) and <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/02/delicious-one/\">swung from the balls of del.icio.us</a> (still do).  But over the last few days a bunch of blogs I read and news sites have been dishing the scoop on google talk.  This is before it even came out.  Talking about how its gonna rule and crap.  It finally hit today and after trying it for one day it gets a resounding two thumbs down from me.  You have no file sharing and it doesn\'t communicate with AOL.  Forget it.  Furthermore, its based on my gmail address.  I get about 50 spam a day there.  If I use google talk, they are gonna call me all day long to talk to me about how small my wang is or how suzie gets stuffed. I have never had a problem with AIM in eight years of using it and they are going to have to give me a damn good reason to leave.</p>\r\n<p>My point here is that everyone needs to just calm down on trying to tell everyone how wonderfult he next thing to come out of google labs is.  A few weeks ago whent hey gave you the ability to look at your search history (a truly beautiful thing) everyone was crying foul that google was tracking everything they did.  Now google is great again just because everyone wants to be the first to get the rumor out there. Everyone be cool.  All google has done is released <a href=\"http://messenger.yahoo.com/\">another</a> <a href=\"http://messenger.msn.com/Xp/Default.aspx\">worthless</a> <a href=\"http://www.google.com/talk/\">messenger</a>.</p>\r\n<h3>In closing</h3>\r\n<p>If you are going to get all crazy over something, get nuts over something real.  How about the fact that <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiwifruit\">kiwi fruit are also called Chinese Gooseberries</a> or that the bug you have called a Japanese beetle for your entire life is actually called a fiery searcher</p>','Google talk.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','google-talk','','','2005-09-05 11:18:29','2005-09-05 16:18:29','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/google-talk/',0,'','',0),
	(263,1,'2005-08-29 17:32:45','2005-08-29 22:32:45','<p>I started school again this morning.  This basically means that regular posting will start again because I am going to be thrust back into thinking mode.  I don\'t mind though.  As fun as the summer has been I have been stagnating and school always gets the ideas flowing.  Regardless, I received an email from Temple this evening that was pimping the beta version of the newest version of the student portal.  There are so many errors it makes my heart sad.  Here\'s the one that shows up all over the place.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK Date: Mon, 29 Aug 2005 22:23:35 GMT Server: Oracle-Application-Server-10g/10.1.2.0.0 Oracle-HTTP-Server Connection: close Transfer-Encoding: chunked Content-Type: text/html; charset=iso-8859-1\r\nOK\r\nThe server encountered an internal error or misconfiguration and was unable to complete your request.\r\n\r\nPlease contact the server administrator, you@your.address and inform them of the time the error occurred, and anything you might have done that may have caused the error.\r\n\r\nMore information about this error may be available in the server error log.\r\n\r\nOracle-Application-Server-10g/10.1.2.0.0 Oracle-HTTP-Server Server at tuportal2.temple.edu Port 443\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>There are more once you log into the portal but for fear the error messages will give something away about my account.  I know that Beta webware is all the rage right now but when companies like google or yahoo release beta webware it works.  It may not be full featured, but it works.  You can\'t send an email to every student on the first day of class and tell them to check out something cool, then provide them with something broken.</p>\r\n<p>Beside being total bad form, from a strictly development and security standpoint, the information that can be drawn from this kind of message can be used to bring a site to its knees.</p>\r\n<p>On the up side, I did find this page on temple\'s site that has <a href=\"http://mdev.temple.edu/webcams/bartoncam/\">live webcams</a>.  The gears are turning on that one.</p>','It\'s supposed to work though.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','hide','its-supposed-to-work-though','','','2005-10-17 11:32:20','2005-10-17 16:32:20','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/08/its-supposed-to-work-though/',0,'','',3),
	(265,1,'2005-09-12 10:18:13','2005-09-12 15:18:13','<p>With oil prices pushing ever higher and the impending gloom of <a href=\"http://www.lifeaftertheoilcrash.net/\">peak oil</a>, I wonder how the relative size of American cars will be effected (<a href=\"http://media.skoopy.com/misc/minicars/\">Check out these photoshoped images of the future of vehicles</a>).   The big SUVs and trucks aren\'t really fun anymore if it costs you too much to drive them.  I am hoping these will die a fast death.  The same people who drive them are the same people who think that 1 inch of clearance is enough when you are passing a biker at 70 mph.</p>\r\n<p>I want a new car. Not a new used car, a new car. Until now the idea was out of my reach because of my driving history.  As of March when my insurance renews again I will be three years without a ticket or an accident and I will turn 26 in April.  So my insurance will be lower and buying a new car becomes doable.</p>\r\n<p>If you have had a conversation with me about anything lately you will probably hear me rant about sustainability or conservation or something of the like.  I\'ve added a bunch of environment/sustainability related blogs to my daily reading and enjoy getting myself worked up about all the possible doomsday scenerios. Two years ago I would have wanted a really big, fast, roaring vehicle.  In fact I <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/timmyfury/21032900/\">sold two such cars</a> a little over a year ago and downsized engine size. At the beginning of the summer I rented a Toyota Corolla while I was vacationing in Florida.  Four cylinders of pure joy turned me to the dark side of the economy car.  I drove the car nearly 400 miles and at the end of the week when I refilled the tank (the only refill of the week) it cost me 12 dollars.  Yeah that\'s hot.</p>\r\n<p>All these facts combined have pushed me into thinking that I could step down once again and get me a nice four cylinder or a sweet trendy hybrid.  If they come out with a hybrid Jeep Wrangler, I am so getting one.</p>','In hopes of smaller cars',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','in-hopes-of-smaller-cars','','','2005-09-12 10:18:35','2005-09-12 15:18:35','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/in-hopes-of-smaller-cars/',0,'','',5),
	(266,1,'2005-09-13 19:01:28','2005-09-14 00:01:28','Going to the market is a relatively new concept for me.  I\'m not talking about stopping in for a few items.  I mean the weekly food shopping.  The make a list of things you need kind of shopping.  Trish and I shop at two places every week.  Gentile\'s for produce, Giant for the rest.  They are high quality low cost and we like the way they are arranged.  Regardless, something we have noticed is the level of danger is extremely high.  I am a relatively sentient person.  I know whats going on most of the time and I think I adjust well to my surroundings.  The market is a whole nothing planet though.  There\'s less action at Roosevelt Boulevard and Red Lion Road.  These freaking ladies are freaking crazy.  They have no concept of what\'s going on around them.  And they pay attention to one thing - fresh lettuce.  They will run you down without a second though if you are in front of the eggs. Beware of these maniacs if you happen to find yourself making a trip to the market.  ','Death in the market',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','death-in-the-market','','','2005-09-13 19:01:31','2005-09-14 00:01:31','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/death-in-the-market/',0,'','',0),
	(268,1,'2005-09-15 11:51:36','2005-09-15 16:51:36','<img src=\'http://veryraw.com/images/small/elkcarcass.jpg\' alt=\'Delicious Elk Carcass\' style=\"float:right;margin: 0 0 10px 10px;\"/>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B0001F4ZGY/ref=ase_thesneeze-20/102-1302376-3181759?v=glance&s=gourmet-food\">This product from Amazon is great</a>.  \"Elk Carcass\" sounds  horrible.  Why would you advertise that way. Mark responded with \"gah\", a very appropropriate response.</p>\r\n<p>The reviews are even better though.</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Out of all the carcasses I have eaten (And believe me....I try to treat myself to carcass at LEAST once a month) this is by far the freshest and most tasty. Fans of carcasses will be pleased that you no longer have to scrape these tasty tidbits from the roadside...alas no more trying to grill out those tire marks....no sir-ee Now everybodys favorite online bookstore brings carcass out of the interstate and right to your dinnerplate!</p>\r\n<p>by: M. Sherer \"Meat afficianado\"</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Flavorful flavorful flavorful. And stimulates a euphoria not unlike what I imagine controlled substances to be like--most particularly those dispensed by one Alan Owlsley in in the 60s. I bought a used one, which may have something to do with these extremely colorful flash-forwards I\'ve been having since hosting a dinner party for 18, of Elk Tartar. Still, you can\'t go wrong with elk. Even the used ones pack a wallop you won\'t soon forget. In fact, I\'d argue that ESPECIALLY the used ones will make you the \"life of the party.\" </p>\r\n<p>by:	Doctor LongGhost</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>While it is not quite the whole carcass (no antlers, hoofs or fur) it\'s still a great bargain. And when I\'m having carcass, I like to have oranges with my carcass, and maybe a little fruity zinfandel to wash down the carcass. The health benefits cannot be overstated, considering the impact this will have on your food budget. No more Krispy Kremes.</p>\r\n<p>By the way, this makes a Great wedding gift. what an impression you will make! </p>\r\n<p>Driver9</p>\r\n</blockquote>','A delicious meal for all - Elk Carcass',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-delicious-meal-for-all-elk-carcass','','','2005-09-15 11:51:45','2005-09-15 16:51:45','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/a-delicious-meal-for-all-elk-carcass/',0,'','',2),
	(269,1,'2005-09-19 11:32:05','2005-09-19 16:32:05','<p>Avast.  \'Tis a bit late in the day here for this entry, but \'tis <a href=\"http://www.talklikeapirate.com/piratehome.html\">International Talk Like a Pirate day</a>, today.  Give me the king\'s pardon for not warnin\' ya sooner.  I\'ve been draggin\' me best and swabbin\' the poop deck to be ready for such an occasion.  If ya need to scrape the barnacles of your pirate lingo, your gonna want to click on yonder links below.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.talklikeapirate.com/howto.html\">Why talk like a pirate - and how</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.io.com/~sj/PirateTalk.html\">Pirate glossary</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.thepiratesrealm.com/pirate%20talk.html\">Pirate Talk</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cindyvallar.com/lingo.html\">The History of Maritime Piracy - pirate lingo</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Watch out how much grog ya\' drink in celebration of the day on the jollyboat, ya don\'t want to spend tomorrow in Davy Jones Locker, ya boss might not fancy that too much and you\'ll be flogged.</p>','Ahoy, tis International Talk Like a Pirate Day!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','talk-like-a-pirate','','','2005-09-19 11:32:11','2005-09-19 16:32:11','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/its-international-talk-like-a-pirate-day/',0,'','',0),
	(270,1,'2005-09-22 22:36:33','2005-09-23 03:36:33','<p><img src=\"http://veryraw.com/images/large/verylongengagement.jpg\" /></p>\r\n<p>From the director of <a href=\"http://imdb.com/title/tt0211915/\">Amelie</a>, Jean-Pierre Jeunet, starring the star of <a href=\"http://imdb.com/title/tt0211915/\">Amelie</a>, Audrey Tautou, comes <a href=\"http://imdb.com/title/tt0344510/\">A Very Long Engagment</a>.  It\'s a story about a girl\'s search for her fiance after he is reported dead from a battle in World War one.</p>\r\n<p>It\'s a little gruesome in the beginning.  It quickly converts to a wonderful hunt for Mathilde\'s fiance. What I love most about the movie is it walks you through every step of the search for Manech without dragging.  It\'s compelling and interesting.  And the best part of all is that up until the very end you don\'t know whether they are actually going to find him or not.  I won\'t tell because I want you to see it, but Trish was a little disappointed because it didn\'t give her the nice clean ending that she loves.</p>\r\n<p>Okay, I don\'t care if you see it or not.  I love that Mathilde finds Manech but he isn\'t in the same shape he was at the beginning.  He\'s not deformed, he just doesn\'t remember her.  I love that the story ends in such a true and pure way.  The entire time she is looking for him, even though he has been reported as dead, out of her love for him.  The whole search is about love and hope.  In the end the feeling of the movie isn\'t cheapened by a happy go lucky, everything is perfect,  remember you ending.  She finds him but he has no idea who she is.  Is she disappointed? No.  She\'s happy that she found the one she loves.  The theme of the movie is preserved and everyone gets what they want.  Except for Trish, who loves closure in her movies.</p>\r\n<p>I also loved the subtitles.  It was in French, like Amelie, and as <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/03/kerenann-nolita/\">I\'ve mentioned before</a>, I love the French Language.  Gives it a magical feeling that I haven\'t felt since I watched <a href=\"http://imdb.com/title/tt0299977/\">Hero</a>.</p>','A Very Long Engagement',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-very-long-engagement','','','2005-09-22 22:38:15','2005-09-23 03:38:15','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/a-very-long-engagement/',0,'','',2),
	(271,1,'2005-09-20 09:01:28','2005-09-20 14:01:28','<p>I was brushing my teeth the other day.  I had noticed that the bristles were a bit worn and it should probably be replaced, but I waited.  I waited too long.  In the middle of brushing my teeth, every bristle in the brush fell out of the tooth brush in my mouth leaving behind a bare handle.  It was bizarre, terrifying even.  It\'s like driving down the road and the steering wheel falling off in your hands.</p>\r\n<p>I looked in the linen closet and there was luckily an unused toothbrush there. It was \"soft\".  The handle was flexible like a bendy straw.  When I had finished brushing, my mouth felt no cleaner than before.  It was weird.  Don\'t even know why I bothered.  I had to go out and buy another one of my trusty \"medium\" brushes.  <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B0000C4KJK/sr=1-5/qid=1127224730/ref=sr_1_5/102-1302376-3181759\">the Oral B Advantage</a>.  I have been using it for years.  I have bought several different types of brushes as my secondary (for travel or campin) and nothing holds up quite like it.  </p>','Oral B Advantage For President!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','oral-b-advantage-for-president','','','2005-09-20 09:01:48','2005-09-20 14:01:48','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/oral-b-advantage-for-president/',0,'','',2),
	(272,1,'2005-09-27 13:41:56','2005-09-27 18:41:56','<p>The information you are about to receive is not for the weak of heart or those who care not about colonic health.  I offer this information simply because I was amazed myself. It may or may not be healthy, you be the judge.</p>\r\n<p>Yesterday, upon waking I ate a measured cup of <a href=\"http://www.kashi.com/golean_cereal.aspx?SID=1&Category_ID=48&Link_ID=27&\">Kashi GoLean</a> <em>(10g)</em> and a <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01fa.html\">banana</a> <em>(3g)</em>.  I went to class, on the way to work I had an <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01e9.html\">apple</a> <em>(3g)</em>.  At lunchtime I had a turkey and cheese on <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s03rg.html\">wheat</a> sandwich <em>(4g)</em>. <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s0453.html\">Pretzels</a> <em>(2g)</em> a yogurt with a combination of <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01l1.html\">rasberries</a> and <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01ff.html\">blueberries</a> <em>(3g)</em>. An <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01in.html\">orange</a> <em>(3g)</em> as a midafternoon snack.</p>\r\n<p>To this point we are at a very healthy 28 grams of fiber.  But we haven\'t covered dinner yet.</p>\r\n<p>I had a salad with two <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s02a3.html\">tomatoes</a> <em>(2g)</em>, two stalks of <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s01uk.html\">celery</a> <em>(2g)</em> and <a href=\"http://www.nutritiondata.com/facts-001-02s028g.html\">red pepper</a> <em>(2g)</em>.  There was more in the salad but that was all that was there with significant fiber content.</p>\r\n<p>None of this is quite rediculous though.  34 grams of fiber in a day is alot but healthy.  The kicker is the main course though.  We made fajitas.  I had two.  Nothing in them of fibrous consequence right? Right.  But the whole wheat tortillas we made the fajitas with weighed in at a whopping 21grams of fiber a piece.  And I had two.</p>\r\n<p>That\'s 76 grams of fiber for the day.  Needless to say, everything is moving along smoothly today.</p>','A very high fiber day.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','a-very-high-fiber-day','','','2005-09-27 13:42:44','2005-09-27 18:42:44','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/a-very-high-fiber-day/',0,'','',0),
	(273,1,'2005-09-29 15:03:22','2005-09-29 20:03:22','http://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/25/realestate/25cov.html','Buy vs. Rent',0,'',NULL,NULL,'draft','closed','closed','','buy-vs-rent','','','2005-09-29 15:03:22','2005-09-29 20:03:22','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/buy-vs-rent/',0,'','',0),
	(274,1,'2005-09-30 07:42:40','2005-09-30 12:42:40','<p>Since Google added <a href=\"http://maps.google.com/maps?t=k\">satellite images to Google maps</a> and moreso since they released <a href=\"http://earth.google.com\">Google Earth</a> I have read a glut of articles about <a href=\"http://www.mcwetboy.net/maproom/2005/09/google_earth_privacy_and_security_roundup.phtml\">politicians freaking over the ability for terrorists to use the maps to collect information to plan an attack</a>.  The idea is rediculous.  Maps may be a useful starting place but saying that a terrorist could get the information needed to plot an attack from a low quality satellite image is like saying a research scientist could find everything they need in an encyclopedia.  I don\'t know if they realize it but maps have been available to the general public for decades.  I have several maps sitting next to my desk right now.  Not only do they have very detailed information about the US and the world but they can also be carried around where ever I go.  I don\'t even need google maps. </p>\r\n<p>The whole idea strikes me as wreaking of two problems.  The first is the blatant overuse of the terrorist threat.  Its politicians preying on the fears of their citizens.  Its politicians making a sad attempt to convince their constituents that they are doing something when most of us know that politicians do nothing but fuel the bureaucracy of the government.  Second it shows how little politicians understand about the direction that the future is heading and the impact technology is going to have on it.  Google maps has not provided access to previously secret information.  Google maps has  simply given every person with access to a computer and an internet connection the ability to see it for free.  Nothing new here. </p>','The rediculous idea that Google maps could be used as a tool for terrorists',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','the-possibility-of-using-satalite-images-by-terrorists','','','2005-09-30 07:42:55','2005-09-30 12:42:55','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/09/the-possibility-of-using-satalite-images-by-terrorists/',0,'','',6),
	(275,1,'2005-10-01 08:27:55','2005-10-01 13:27:55','<p>Today is the first day of October which means that places will be converting shortly to the haunted versions of themselves.  I realized this last night as I drove past the carwash down the road.  The sign in the front read \"TRYOUTS FOR HAUNTED CARWASH TODAY.\"  This carwash does the haunted thing every year but this is the first time I have seen that they had tryouts.  So I have come up with a list of the scariest things you could hear in a carwash to help anyone who might want to tryout. As you read the list be sure to use a scary ghost voice or the throaty voice of Frankenstein.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I\'m using a course soap!</li>\r\n<li>I won\'t be using a lambskin chamois!</li>\r\n<li>We don\'t have a water softener!</li>\r\n<li>You\'re going to have water spots on your car when you leave!</li>\r\n<li>The wax is drying before I have a chance to buff it out!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Feel free to offer more.  This is just a start.  The auditions are cut throat and you\'ll need all the help you can get!</p>','Everything is haunted, even the carwash!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','everything-is-haunted-even-the-carwash','','','2005-10-01 08:28:03','2005-10-01 13:28:03','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/everything-is-haunted-even-the-carwash/',0,'','',0),
	(276,1,'2005-10-10 15:19:53','2005-10-10 20:19:53','<p>Frequently I think to myself that I am just wasting my time by going to school.  This is not to say that the investment is a waste and won\'t get me somewhere.  I mean that for the most part the things I learn in my IS classes are things I already have a good deal of knowledge about from work or personal reading.  I am mostly self-taught.  I don\'t think that I am perfect by any means but a lot of my opinions about technology and web development and process are developed based on the reading of many wise individuals and hours  of thinking on my own about these topics, rather than ideas that are forced on me by a select few professors.</p>\r\n<p>I am taking two classes this semester.  Project Management and Database Design.  These are two topics that I have read about excessively.  They are two things that I have thought about at length and they are subjects that I have alot of opinions on (as if there\'s anything I don\'t have an opinion about).  Regardless this semester has been somewhat of an eye opener for me.  There are oodles of concepts that I have thought I have understood in the past but by going to class and sitting through it from beginning to end, I am making connections that I haven\'t made before.  I am learning terms for things and ways of discussing concepts that I could never quite put into words.</p>\r\n<p>My point is that although I have in the past found school a little tedious, this semester is different.  I am learning things that I have already learned all over again for the first time.  I\'m going to class and I\'m loving it.  There\'s conversation and debate and I\'m loving it.  I just wish I could go back full time so I could get my learn on in a more solid and fullfilling way.</p>','Official learning',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','official-learning','','','2005-10-10 15:19:56','2005-10-10 20:19:56','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/official-learning/',0,'','',1),
	(277,1,'2005-10-18 14:59:05','2005-10-18 19:59:05','<p>Just got the word that my car is ready for me to pick up.  That\'s great.  Had it inspected today and had to replace the entire rear brake setup.  $600 inspection.  Plus the $250 for the new tires and alignment this weekend.  Could end up being $200 more if I can\'t get the two tickets I got for expired inspection thrown out.  It seems like every year I get nailed on my inspection.  Last year, right after buying the car I threw down nearly $1200 for inspection.  The year before it was $1400 for the big blue ford I was driving then.</p>\r\n<p>Something tells me that my affinity for the $400 car is going to grow old someday.  At which point I will need to either buy a new car (a whole new can of misery for sure) or move into the city and do away with my car altogether.  Who knows.  For now I will just deal.  All in all the car has cost me only $2500 total.  Not too bad.</p>','Nobody knows the inspections I\'ve seen, nobody knows my sorrow!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','nobody-knows-the-inspections-ive-seen-nobody-knows-my-sorrow','','','2005-10-18 14:59:47','2005-10-18 19:59:47','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/nobody-knows-the-inspections-ive-seen-nobody-knows-my-sorrow/',0,'','',2),
