	(279,1,'2005-10-20 09:25:40','2005-10-20 14:25:40','Although I don\'t have any particular interest in anything going on in the Middle East other than my addiction to petroleum and my desire to own a flying carpet or genie lamp, I have been following the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saddam_Hussein\">Saddam Hussein</a> saga since before his capture.  I\'m not saying that I\'m all pro-Saddam or anything.  I wouldn\'t exactly call myself a Ba\'athist, but the man is intriguing if nothing else.  I have heard thousands of news reports about him since the capture in late 2003 and he has remained ever defiant.  I don\'t think I have heard a single report that doesn\'t have him calling someone a dog or an infidel.  The man knows that this trial will lead to his hanging in a public square and still, when asked to state his name in court, he says things like (paraphrased) \'I will not answer this question because as the president of Iraq, I do not recognize this as a legitimate court.\'  I heard on NPR the other night that when he was visited by Iraqi officials shortly after his capture, that he basically called them all pussy\'s for not coming to kill him.  Man that guy is defiant as shit. Shortly after his capture, his oldest daughter stated \"Saddam was tranquillised when captured [...] He would be a lion even when caged. Every honest person who knows Saddam knows that he is firm and powerful.\" Preach on girl! Hallelujah!\r\n\r\nI wish there was a record of all the people he has called an infidel.  And if there were such a record I would like to travel to Iraq, find Saddam and get my name on that very long list. I would also like to get shirts made that read \"Saddam called me an infidel!\"  I\'m still working on a design.','Sassy Saddam',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','sassy-saddam','','','2005-10-20 09:26:00','2005-10-20 14:26:00','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/sassy-saddam/',0,'','',0),
	(280,1,'2005-10-20 21:17:53','2005-10-21 02:17:53','<p>Trish and I arrived from the gym tonight and someone was parked in <a href=\"http://www.grindinglight.com/blog/\">Burn\'s</a> spot.  As I walked past his car I noticed that there was someone in the car and they were surfing <a href=\"http://www.myspace.com\">myspace</a> on a laptop.  I\'m walking to the door and realize, that guy is skimming off my wireless connection.  Looks like we got ourselves a <a href=\"http://www.answers.com/main/ntquery?s=war+driver&method=2&gwp=13\">war driver</a>.  So we go inside and unplug the modem and sure enough when he was finished with the page he was reading, he clicked on another link and realized that the large man staring at him from the doors in front of him had disconnected him.</p>\r\n<p>With him gone I logged into the wireless router we use to connect Trish to the network in our apartment.  I locked that shit down tight. Limit by MAC address, limit number of IP\'s, encrypt the shit out of it, password the wireless, password the network, rename the network, you name it, if it was an option, I did it.  We were lucky though.  This guy was really only out for a quick myspace fix.  Luckily he wasn\'t out for a quick, charge the shit out of my credit card fix.</p>\r\n<p>Moral of the story, <strong>lock your fucking network down</strong>.</p>','War Driver Unwanted!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','war-driver-unwanted','','','2005-10-24 17:23:32','2005-10-24 22:23:32','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/war-driver-unwanted/',0,'','',9),
	(281,1,'2005-10-28 16:07:51','2005-10-28 21:07:51','<p>Since I started working in the web services department at the college, we have slowly been weeding through the content on the pages of the site.  Making things easier to find and making sure information is only maintained in one place has been a key objective of ours.  Basically its easier to maintain and less confusing to our customers.  It was pointed out to me in a meeting yesterday that it was nearly impossible to find directions to the various campuses on our site.  The issue was that they were buried in a page that had a list of campuses.  The campus names linked to pages that profiled the campus.  On that page there was a link to the directions for that campus\' county.  Then finally on that page you would click on a link that jumped to the part of the page that had the directions to that campus.  Little bit of overkill.</p>\r\n<p>Since google released the <acronym title=\"application programming interface\">API</acronym> for their maps I have been toying with them and attempting to get them to do what I wanted them to do so I could improve the directions on the college\'s homepage.  So after my meeting yesterday, when it was made abundantly clear to me that I was not the only person who had issues with the directions situation on the site, I sat down and forged through and finished the map.  You can see it on the <a href=\"http://www.dccc.edu/locations/\">locations page</a>.  I am really very excited about this.  You click on one of our locations and get a form to enter your address and when you submit you go to <a href=\"http://local.google.com/\">google local</a> for directions from your door to ours.</p>\r\n<p>Not only that but I also streamlined the content on that page so they linked only to directions and maps for each location.  This of course is all in an effort to make the site more usable for our customers.  After all, if they can\'t find the school, they can\'t sign up for classes and thats why we\'re here.</p>','Information findability, directions and Maps.',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','information-findability-directions-and-maps','','','2005-10-28 16:07:54','2005-10-28 21:07:54','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2005/10/information-findability-directions-and-maps/',0,'','',3),
