	(324,1,'2006-03-13 10:50:01','2006-03-13 15:50:01','<h2>Spider Crickets, Camel Back Crickets, Cave Crickets</h2>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"width:240px;float:right;padding:10px;margin:10px 0 10px 10px;background:#FDF8E2;\">\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mimbrava/50462430/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://static.flickr.com/26/50462430_40be79fb74_m.jpg\" alt=\"camel cricket, top view\" /></a>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mimbrava/50462429/\" title=\"Photo Sharing\"><img src=\"http://static.flickr.com/24/50462429_a5e8b6d671_m.jpg\" alt=\"camel cricket, head on\" /></a>\r\n<p>These images were used with permission of <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mimbrava/\">Mim Eisenberg</a>.  Take a look at some more of Mim\'s amazing <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mimbrava/tags/insect/\">insect pictures</a>.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever you call them they are bloody terrifying. I wrote about these terrifying <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/spiders-crickets-lions/\">cricket pests</a> in January of 2005 and had an overwhelming response, 69 comments over   the course of the next year. The response was all accross the country, with   commenters hailing from northwest Arkansas, South and North Carolina, Virginia   Beach and Norfolk, Virginia, Cincinnati, Ohio, Oklahoma (where they call them   sprickets), Missouri, California, Long Island, Texas, Winfield, West Virginia.   I felt this was enough of a response that it was neccesary to do some research   to help those who visit rid themselves of these terrifying animals.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Sweet Jesus, what are those things!</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Cave Crickets are unmistakable. These crickets are a tan color with dark stripes.   Unlike other crickets, cave crickets are wingless, but have more powerful, long   legs that give them amazing jumping capability. They are also chirpless; a silent   terror. These crickets will eat nearly anything, which explains why   <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/spiders-crickets-lions/#comment-1388\">Joy\'s   friend has seen them eating her cat\'s poop.</a> Furthermore, as   <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/spiders-crickets-lions/#comment-1416\">Thomas</a>   and <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/01/spiders-crickets-lions/#comment-1431\">Glen</a>   pointed out the are not just summer/spring creatures, they can weather the cold   too. Though, the largest amount of hits to my site in search of information   about cave crickets has come in the spring of 2005 and 2006.</p>\r\n<p>These buggers are nocturnal and aren\'t attracted to light. They use their long   antennea to feel through dark spaces and they generally live in <strong>actual   caves</strong>. Though, as you would find if you read through the comments on   my entry about these crickets, they are found nearly everywhere; basements,   crawl spaces, washing machines, condos and apartments. These are however not idea   situations for these creatures to be in.  Wikipedia points out...</p>  \r\n  <blockquote title=\"Cave cricket - From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\" cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cave_Cricket\">\r\n	<p>While they have been known to take up residence the basements of buildings, \r\n	  many cave crickets live out their entire lives deep inside actual caves. In \r\n	  those habitats they sometimes face long spans of time with insufficient access \r\n	  to nutrients. To avoid starvation, they have been known to devour their own \r\n	  extremities, even though they cannot regenerate limbs.</p>\r\n	</blockquote>\r\n<p>It is important to note that these crickets do not bite.  They aren\'t harmful to babies and they don\'t attack 	you when you come near. It sometimes seems as though the jump toward you, but they are merely trying to escape 	the fate of a million roaches. In September of 2005 Steven J. Taylor led a team from University of Illinois at 	Urbana-Champaign and reported that cave crickets left there homes at night and traveled up to 260+ feet from their	home in search of food.</p>\r\n<blockquote title=\"When cave crickets go out for dinner, they really go, researchers say\" cite=\"http://www.news.uiuc.edu/NEWS/05/0907crickets.html\">\r\n	<p>Previous research indicated that most crickets stay within 50 meters (164 \r\n	  feet) from their caves. As part of the formula for a buffer zone proposed by \r\n	  the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, a range for cricket foraging was recommended. \r\n	  The buffer zone also extends outward to control for the effects of invasive \r\n	  red imported fire ants (Solenopsis invicta Buren). The buffer-zone formula helps \r\n	  to guide where to apply treatment applications against the ants.</p>\r\n	<p>Buffer zones are designed to help maintain a healthy vegetative community, \r\n	  including woodland and grassland species, around cave entrances to protect cave \r\n	  life from disturbance, including that created by encroaching urban development.</p>\r\n	<p>On average, adult crickets were found farther from the cave entrance than \r\n	  were the nymphs. While 51 percent of all crickets were found to be within 40 \r\n	  meters (131 feet) of the cave entrance, 8 percent were found at locations 80 \r\n	  meters (262 feet) and beyond.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>This finding is important when you are considering your actions in ridding yourself of these pests. They are searching for food to bring back to their   home. Their intension is not to bother. In suburban areas, their homes have   been encroached upon and in most areas, 260 feet makes up several pieces of   property. This makes it even easier for cave crickets to end up in your basement or crawl space.</p>\r\n  \r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>How can I get rid of them?</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Is it a mole or a camel..........? recently mentioned in a newsletter about \r\n  pest control from as a problem on a golf course in the area as well.<br />\r\n  http://www.oznet.k-state.edu/entomology/extension/KIN/KIN_2005/kin-8/05ksnew8.htm</p>\r\n \r\n<p>I am just very anti-pesticide. Cave crickets aren&#8217;t indoor breeders though. \r\n  Spraying the area that you see them in is not very effective because they are \r\n  generally solitary and only wander into your house by accident. Everything I \r\n  have read to date on them suggests that you eliminate cool dark areas. <a href=\"http://www.ipm.iastate.edu/ipm/iiin/ccamelcr.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Eliminating \r\n  hiding and breeding places</a> around your house and moreover in your yard will \r\n  help to prevent them from sneaking into your house. </p>\r\n  \r\n<hr />\r\n<p>#comment-1321 alisa<br />\r\n  Having a dehumidifier in our garage seems to help. I think we need to seal more \r\n  areas around windows and our garage door. I am going to try to figure out how \r\n  to keep our basement as dry as possible and make it less &#8220;cave-like&#8221;. \r\n  Also, since I can&#8217;t stand them, I am just going to stay out of our basement \r\n  at night if I can help it - they seem worse then. </p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n  <p><strong>find out where this information came from</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>First, discover where the crickets are getting inside and stop up the holes. \r\n  If that fails to keep them out, the Canadian version of the U.S. Environmental \r\n  Protection Agency suggests mixing some molasses and vanilla extract or lemon \r\n  juice in water. Crickets are lured to this bait and drown in it. A flyswatter \r\n  works very nicely, too.</em></p>\r\n  <hr />\r\n  \r\n<p> Terminix - pest library<br />\r\n  * Store firewood away from the home and off the ground.<br />\r\n  * Dispose of piles of lumber or store such items off the ground.<br />\r\n\r\n  * Clean up piles of leaf litter and clean up any debris that could provide shelter.<br />\r\n  * Remove any heavy ground cover in landscaping within 10 feet of the home.<br />\r\n  * Install yellow &quot;bug&quot; light bulbs in outdoor fixtures to attract \r\n  as few crickets as possible.<br />\r\n  * Seal as many exterior cracks and holes as possible in the outside walls.<br />\r\n  * Improve crawl space ventilation to make the subspace less attractive to camel \r\n  crickets<br />\r\n\r\n  http://www.terminix.com/Pest/Library/index.cfm?fuseaction=category&amp;pestCategory=Occasional&amp;pestID=12</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Maybe they aren\'t really an issue.</h3>\r\n\r\n  <p>\r\n    BAY AREA BUG EATING SOCIETY (B.A.B.E.S.)<br />\r\n    For All Of Your Bug Eating Needs<br />\r\n    http://www.planetscott.com/babes/bugfeature.asp?featureID=6</p>\r\n\r\n		\r\n<p>or cage them for good luck</p>\r\n\r\n  \r\n  <hr />\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n  <p><strong><cite>Charlie</cite> Says:</strong> comment-1270</p>\r\n\r\n			\r\n						\r\n			<p>We&#8217;ve had camelback crickets for about 15 years. It&#8217;s a good bet they are breeding in a woodpile that&#8217;s too near our house.<br />\r\nBut I don&#8217;t have another place to put the woodpile.  Some of these buggers get in the house. In particular they come inside in the fall.  I&#8217;ve applied Sevin dust around the woodpile (it&#8217;s in a shelter and does not get wet). Also, I go out at night and kill individual crickets with Raid or something similar. This keeps the population down. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>On another site I just noticed two more ideas. (1) Use glue boards inside the house in dark cave-like places. Glue boards are just cardboard with a very sticky glue. This should get rid of individual crickets that stray into the house. (2) Sprinkle Borax dust near where they are breeding. Good idea!!! This is a little known idea. Borax dust kills cockroaches and a lot of other pests. As some have said, &#8220;it cuts the bugs like glass cuts humans&#8221;. It really does. They lose fluids through the cuts and dehydrate and die. I&#8217;m going to apply Borax powder right after I finish this note. I&#8217;ve used it for other pests, and feel sort of stupid because I didn&#8217;t think of it sooner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A by-the-way&#8230; you can make ant poison (sweet eating ants only) by blending Borax powder into Karo syrup. Add Borax and stir and do this until the mixture is saturated. Borax is CHEAP&#8230; a lot cheaper than the usual pesticides.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n			<p><strong><cite>Charlie</cite> Says:</strong> comment-1357</p>\r\n			\r\n						\r\n			<p>On October 3 I posted a message concerning our camelback cricket problem.  All experts say the trick is to kill them outside the house. Apparently the ones that come inside just wander in through cracks. Kill them outside the the problem is gone.</p>\r\n<p>So we sprinkled Borax (Boric Acid) powder around our woodpile.<br />\r\nThat&#8217;s where they seem to be hatching. It&#8217;s under a shelter, dry, and near the house. Borax (sold as a roach killer) will kill most crawling insects.  I bought a large container of Borax (advertised as a roach killer) at a dollar store for $2.00 and sprinkled it generously around the woodpile in a band about 12 inches wide.  Then I sprinkled some flakes of dry oatmeal on top of the Borax to give the buggers something to eat and a reason to walk in the Borax. Contact with the Borax kills them&#8230; they do not have to eat it. There are now dead camelback crickets around the woodpile. I check every night after dark and the live cricket count is zero.  Before doing this treatment those critters were having a party out there every night.  We&#8217;ve had no camelbacks in our home for about three weeks. None!!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After 15 years of putting up with these things we seem to have a solution. And it&#8217;s a cheap solution, too.</p>\r\n<p>Of course if you put the Borax in places were it will be wet from rain, this may not work at all.</p>\r\n<p>Another thing we did was to sprinkle Borax on the threshold of basement doors that we seldom open. We have been convinced this is the place they have been coming inside.  There are now dead sowbugs and other dead creepy-crawly things on the thresholds along with the corpses of a few camelback crickets.</p>\r\n<p>This turned out to be easier than we thought. We&#8217;ve used Borax (Boric Acid) to kill roaches but until recently never thought about using it to kill camelback crickets.\r\n</p>		\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Links not checked but probably worthwhile</h3>\r\nhttp://ohioline.osu.edu/hyg-fact/2000/2066.html\r\nhttp://www.puyallup.wsu.edu/plantclinic/resources/pdf/pls42crickets.pdf\r\nhttp://www.bugspray.com/articles98/camelcrickets.html - corporate sponsored\r\nhttp://extension.missouri.edu/explore/agguides/pests/g07366.htm\r\nhttp://www.mgofmc.org/crickets.html\r\nhttp://ag.arizona.edu/urbanipm/insects/cricketmanagement.html - broad ranging not specific to camel\r\nhttp://www.wvu.edu/~agexten/ipm/UPM/1/VII-19.pdf\r\nhttp://www.ipm.iastate.edu/ipm/iiin/node/95 - about pesticides in general.\r\nhttp://www.uky.edu/Ag/Entomology/entfacts/struct/ef641.htm\r\nhttp://www.uoguelph.ca/pdc/Factsheets/Insect/Crickets.html\r\nhttp://www.ces.ncsu.edu/depts/ent/notes/Urban/camelcrickets.htm\r\nhttp://www.hgic.umd.edu/_media/documents/el50.pdf\r\nhttp://www.getipm.com/thebestcontrol/bugstop/control_cricket.htm\r\n\r\n<h3>government management resources</h3>\r\nhttp://chppm-www.apgea.army.mil/ento/bulldec00.htm\r\nhttp://es.epa.gov/techinfo/facts/safe-fs.html\r\n\r\n<h3>Effects of Borax</h3>\r\nhttp://www.fda.gov/fdac/features/2002/602_squad.html\r\nhttp://sanbruno.ca.gov/city_services/our_community/householdchems/page_4.htm\r\nhttp://www.montgomerycountymd.gov/content/dpwt/SolidWaste/documents/hazardous_waste/clean_ways_poster.pdf\r\nhttp://www.answers.com/borax\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<p>the searches<br />\r\n  http://www.google.com/search?q=crickets+in+basement&amp;hl=en&amp;hs=vnD&amp;lr=&amp;c2coff=1&amp;safe=off&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;start=50&amp;sa=N</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last updated March 17, 2006</p>','Spider Crickets, Camel Back Crickets, Cave Crickets',0,'',NULL,NULL,'static','closed','closed','','crickets','','','2006-06-03 15:46:54','2006-06-03 20:46:52','',0,'http://veryraw.com/crickets/',0,'','',0),
	(325,1,'2006-03-15 09:37:54','2006-03-15 14:37:54','<p>At the gym the other night I walked into the locker room and went to the sink to wash my hands.  As I turned to leave there was a guy standing at the urinal completely naked.  He looked me right in the face and said, \"hello\". It\'s one thing to say hello to me in the locker room.  Its something completely different to say hello while you\'re holding yourself at the urinal.  Its something completely different if you\'re naked.  Saying hello to another man in the locker room while you\'re naked is unaccceptable.  So I look away from the guy to avert my eyes but I end up looking into the shower room directly into the face of another naked man... he says \"Hello.\" What the hell.  So I turn to go back to my locker to get my things and leave and there\'s another naked man walking toward me.  Oh sweet Jesus.  I am now surrounded by naked men.  Just then.  When I think that it couldn\'t possibly get any worse, YMCA starts blasting over the speakers.  It had been just weird, now it was disturbing.  I got out of the way of the oncoming naked man as fast as I could so I didn\'t risk getting stuck in the doorway Three Stooges style with two naked men.</p> \r\n<p>I don\'t really understand why old men feel that they need to walk around the locker room naked.  There is nothing wrong with it per se, I just think that perhaps these guys should wear a loin cloth or something when they are walking to the shower.</p>','Regardless of how spectacular they are, please just put them away!',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','regardless-of-how-spectacular-they-are-please-just-put-them-away','','','2006-03-15 09:38:37','2006-03-15 14:38:37','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/03/regardless-of-how-spectacular-they-are-please-just-put-them-away/',0,'','',2),
