	(351,1,'2006-07-19 17:40:14','2006-07-19 22:40:14','<p>This entry was prompted by Brian\'s entry about <a href=\"http://www.bittermonk.com/2006/07/17/canned-content-management/\">bad canned content management systems</a>, which was prompted by his frustration with said systems.  What follows is a recycled email I sent to a friend who shall remain nameless.  He was working on his master degree and had built a site to assist his students.  Basic site with a calendar and some downloadable stuff for his students to help them practice.  He asked me for my opinion about his site from a standards compliance point of view.  I needed to point out to him a few things about the idea of standards compliance.</p>\r\n<p>The significance of this recycled content, my response to my unnamed friend is that there is no catch all for every situation.  Whether you are talking about standards compliance or content management solutions, there\'s an almost right and a lot of wrongs in every situation.  The key is to pick the right almost right solution.</p>\r\n<p><em>The passage has been edited a bit to make myself look like a slightly less illiterate baffoon, and to remove any mention of the aforementioned friend.</em></p>\r\n<blockquote title=\"An email sent to a friend\">\r\n<p>Standards Compliance is kind of a nebulous idea.  The term is thrown around pretty freely in the industry and has lost some of the punch it used to have.  To be standards compliant, you have to select a standard (html,xhtml,xml) and a level of that standard to follow.  If you were to use a standard such as HTML4.0 (a completely respectable standard) you could consider your site completely compliant.  You are currently using the HTML4 frameset standard (also known as a doctype) and you are using it properly.  Your site is completely standards compliant.</p>\r\n<p>A concept that has a little more weight and significance is \"adherance to best practices\".  When you adhere to best practices...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>you are not only making sure your site is compliant with your selected standard,</li>\r\n<li>but you also make sure that your markup is semantically constructed (in otherwords you use tags for what they are meant to be used for, tables for tabular data, headings for headings, lists for lists),</li>\r\n<li>you provide meaningful and useful content in a way that is written to be consumed on the web (seperated into subheadings and lists) because information is digested differently in print and on the web.</li>\r\n<li>and you take accessibility into account.  Accessibility for not only for those of special need but also for those who use use mobile devices or those who would just prefer to print your information and read it on the hopper.</li>\r\n<li>and last but not least you seperate content(html), presentation(css), and behavior(javascript). </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This may sound like a lot, but its all easily achievable.  The web standards movement (not to be confused with standards compliance) is about best practises through use of the 3 layers of seperation (mentioned above) and a little planning and contiousness of what you are doing. </p>\r\n<p>In the end though, it comes down to a few things...</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>amount of time you have to pour over content to make it \"compliant\"</li>\r\n<li>will best practices make your cool thing not as cool (are you stiffling creativity to achieve something that the next guy could say you didn\'t achieve because his definition of best practices is different than yours)</li>\r\n<li>and what is your definition of best practices.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Practically speaking though, this approach makes modifying your work a lot easier and takes a lot of strain off of you.  And you also have to keep in mind that my field is easily one of the most rapidly evolving you could pick.  Furthermore, this isn\'t like print or presentations or flyers.  If its not right today you can make it better tomorrow.  Bottom line, if your product achieves what you intend it to achieve then its not wrong. </p></blockquote>','Validity is in the eye of the beholder',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','validity-is-in-the-eye-of-the-beholder','','','2006-07-19 17:40:14','2006-07-19 22:40:14','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/07/validity-is-in-the-eye-of-the-beholder/',0,'','',1),
	(352,1,'2006-07-29 11:09:10','2006-07-29 16:09:10','Mark sent me this article the other day about <a href=\"http://www.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,70131-1228653,00.html?f=rss\">Parker replacing the money in Monopoly with debit cards</a>.  Thats unfortunate.  I think this is the worst idea ever.  The money is the game.  Never again will someone say, \"Imagine if all this money were real!\"  I\'m going to go out and buy Monopoly with money.','Everyone go buy a copy of Monopoly',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','everyone-go-buy-a-copy-of-monpoly','','','2006-08-05 21:31:36','2006-08-06 02:31:36','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/07/everyone-go-buy-a-copy-of-monpoly/',0,'','',0),
	(353,1,'2006-08-05 21:31:01','2006-08-06 02:31:01','<p>Its no secret that I am a big nerd. I ahve mentioned in the past that <a href=\"http://veryraw.com/history/2005/07/nerd-live-here/\">I don\'t watch the normal channels</a>. In Delaware County, my channels are almost exclusively between 60 and 70.  I have grown increasingly more fond of the latter two channels in the series.  Food network and Home and Garden network.</p>\r\n<p>One host in particular has caught my eye.  <a href=\"http://www.altonbrown.com/\">Alton Brown</a> has an amazing show called <em><a href=\"http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/show_ea\">Good Eats</a></em>. The show is part cooking show, part science lesson.  Not only does he crash through numerous recipes each show without the grueling step by step, but he gives you the history and science behind whatever he\'s talking about.    Plus the way the show is shot is a lot of fun.  Jumpy and natural.  Like it was shot with a camera in his own kitchen rather than manufactured in a studio.</p>\r\n<p>I\'ve been watching his new show too.  Its called <em><a href=\"http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/show_ab\">Feasting on Asphalt</a></em>.  Alton and his crew are riding across the states trying roadside foods and telling you about them.  The show is shot in a similar twitchy style as <em>Good Eats</em>.  The great thing about this show is that, unlike Rachael Ray\'s <em><a href=\"http://www.foodnetwork.com/food/show_ad/\">$40 A Day</a></em>, Alton will tell you when what he\'s eating is shit.  It\'s an awesome show.  I\'ve enjoyed it a lot; I think you would too.</p>','Alton Brown is like god',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','alton-brown-is-like-god','','','2006-11-20 10:22:17','2006-11-20 15:22:17','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/08/alton-brown-is-like-god/',0,'','',2),
	(354,1,'2006-08-12 09:56:49','2006-08-12 14:56:49','<p>Trish and I saw <a href=\"http://www.cirquedusoleil.com/CirqueDuSoleil/en/showstickets/quidam/intro/intro.htm\">Quidam</a> last night.  It was an amazing show.  I have been to the circus many times in my life.  I\'ve seen Ringling Brothers six times and Circ du Soleil twice.  I enjoy Ringling Brothers.  Its fun but after seeing Circ du Soleil, it just can\'t match up.  The thing that makes Circ du Soleil so amazing is that once you are in the tent, you get transported to a different world.  The experience is all encompassing.  The music and the lighting and the set all work together to pull you away form reality and into whatever world of fancy they are trying to create.  For the time that you are in the tent, you forget everything except whats going on on stage.  Circ du Soleil recreates the feeling that I love about my favorite books; being pulled away temporarily to another place.</p>\r\n<p>If you ever have a chance to see Circ du Soleil I can\'t emphasize enough how much its worth the money to see the show.</p>','Transported to a different world',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','transported-to-a-different-world','','','2006-08-12 09:56:49','2006-08-12 14:56:49','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/08/transported-to-a-different-world/',0,'','',1),
	(355,1,'2006-08-16 13:05:48','2006-08-16 18:05:48','<p>I just finished this book called <em><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/038551641X\">The Afghan Campaign</a></em>.  It\'s classified as \"historical literature\".  It\'s based on fact but is still mostly invented story.  After reading <em><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0375725601\">The Devil in the White City: Murder, Magic, and Madness at the Fair that Changed America</a></em> and <em><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0679745580\">In Cold Blood</a></em> nearly back to back, I was hot for historical literature.  I was also looking for something that was epic in scale and would give me a good manly rise from the thought of conquest</p>\r\n<p><em>The Afghan Campaign</em> is about Alexader the Great\'s conquest of Afghanistan around 330 B.C.  It follows the experiences of a single soldier and the trials and tribulations which he goes through over the course of the expedition.  It was a good read.  It provided great incite to the history of the Afghan people and their customs and ways of thinking which for the most part (basing my comparison mostly on the what I learned about the Afghan people while reading <em><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1594480001\">The Kite Runner</a></em>) has not changed much since.</p>\r\n<p>The book really tried very hard to be this great epic.  It was so close too.  I was totally rooting for it and I was totally into the book. I liked the story and I liked the characters.  When I finished though, I realized that it fell just short of my expectations.</p>\r\n<p>So there I was, left hanging, still thirsting for the epic tale that I had expected.  I needed to be quenched.  There was only one appropriate thing to do. So i decided to reread the <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0786926813\">Dragonlance Chronicles</a> Trilogy.  I read them before, but I stopped after the trilogy.  There is another trilogy that follows, then the story is continued in later books.  I\'m going to read them all.  I loved the books the first time I read them and I have cruised through 100 pages in 3 train trips from home to work.</p>\r\n<p>As much as I love these though, I am apparently having an internal struggle with my inner nerd.  I find myself unconsciencely covering any parts of the book that would tell anyone I am reading a Dungeons & Dragons based novel.  As if someone would actually notice. But as Mark said, \"That\'s fair, though in truth you don\'t need to. Plus they can\'t make any of the loser jokes and you can always bust out the bestseller status on them.\"  Too true Mark and besides, if anyone actually knows what they are, there\'s a good chance they are having the same internal struggle.</p>','Struggling with my inner nerd',0,'',NULL,NULL,'publish','closed','closed','','struggling-with-my-inner-nerd','','','2006-08-16 13:05:47','2006-08-16 18:05:47','',0,'http://veryraw.com/history/2006/08/struggling-with-my-inner-nerd/',0,'','',3),
